<FIRST>r i AM-Vanuatu     03-08 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vanuatu,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-President Gets Six-Year Jail Term for Trying to Replace Prime
Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT VILA, Vanuatu (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ex-President George Sokomanu was
sentenced Tuesday to six years in jail after being convicted of
trying to install his nephew as prime minister of this South Pacific
island chain.
   Sokomanu, who has been president since 1980, was dismissed from
office in January for plotting against Prime Minister Walter Lini.
   Sokomanu's nephew, Barak Sope, and opposition leader Maxime
Carlot were given five-year prison sentences and former member of
Parliament Willie Jimmy was sentenced to two years. The charges
against Sokomanu, Sope and Carlot carried maximum sentences of life
imprisonment.
   Three defendants were acquitted.
   Sokomanu was convicted of inciting mutiny within Vanuatu's
paramilitary forces last December in an attempt to replace Lini's
elected government with an interim administration headed by Sope.
   Sokomanu and the other defendants were taken into police custody
just before Christmas.
   At the time of of his arrest Sokomanu acknowledged his action was
unconstitutional, but he said Lini was unable to govern after
suffering a stroke. He said he tried to install Sope as prime
minister to restore economic power.
   Sope and Lini had been engaged in a power struggle for more than
a year.
   Acquitted by British-born Judge Gordon Ward were former member of
Parliament John Naupa, Sokomanu's private secretary John Kalititi
and Frank Spooner.
   Those three and Jimmy had been charged with lesser counts of
conspiracy to overthrow the government and with administering and
making unlawful oaths and statements at a Dec. 18 swearing-in
ceremony.
   Ward was brought in from the Solomon Islands to hear the most
controversial case in Vanuatu's brief history and to pass judgment.
His decisions are subject to appeal.
   Sokomanu was removed from office in January by the Electoral
College which accused him of gross misconduct.
   Sokomanu had served as head of state and Lini as head of
government since Vanuatu became independent in July 1980.
   Vanuatu, formerly the Anglo-French New Hebrides, had been jointly
administered by Britain and France since 1906.
   It has a population of about 130,000 and is 1,395 miles northeast
of Sydney, Australia.
</TEXT>
