<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-KosherMoscow     03-08 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kosher Moscow,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Chef Says Soviets Approve Kosher Eatery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli chef says Soviet authorities have
given him approval to set up a kosher restaurant in Moscow.
   Shalom Kadosh said Tuesday that he discussed the idea last week
in Moscow with city officials and tourism and trade representatives.
   ``The Soviets are showing a great readiness to help us create the
restaurant as quickly as possible,'' he said on Israel Television,
though they have imposed ``some limitations on the signs'' of the
future restaurant.
   The Israeli daily Yediot Ahronot said the eatery will be funded
by American Jewish activists and its prices will be subsidized.
   Kadosh, chef at Jerusalem's Sheraton-Plaza Hotel, said the menu
would be based on Israeli cuisine and that some products would be
imported from Israel. He said the kosher certificate will be given
by the chief rabbi of Moscow.
   Kadosh said he plans to travel to Moscow in the near future to
help organize the restaurant and will supervise it through short
visits.
   ``The aim is not making profit but creating a kosher food place
for Jews and tourists,'' Kadosh said. ``My best profit would be a
contribution to the Soviet-Israeli ties.''
   The Soviet Union cut ties with the Jewish state following the
1967 Middle East war. In recent years, the two countries have
exchanged consular missions.
   Last month, the first Jewish community center in the Soviet Union
in 50 years opened in Moscow.
</TEXT>
