<HEAD>Nun Sentenced To Day In Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WITHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dominican nun who painted peace slogans
on the runway of a U.S. Air Force base was ordered to sit through a
court session as punishment for refusing to pay a fine.
   Sister Mair-Colette Ludden was fined $232 Tuesday by magistrates
in this town 40 miles northeast of London who convicted her of
criminal damage at Alconbury base. She said she would not pay
because the money would go toward a system which supports nuclear
weapons.
   Under an obscure regulation, court chairman Dolph Claydon ordered
the nun to stay within the court precincts for the rest of the day.
   The sister said later: ``It was a great relief when they let me
stay in the court. I was told later it was equivalent to spending a
day in the cells.''
