<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AnthonyConvicted     03-08 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anthony Convicted,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts Senator's Ex-Aide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury Tuesday convicted a former aide
to U.S. Sen. Howard Metzenbaum of accepting $1,300 in illegal
payments from two Polish immigrants who had sought the senator's
help.
   Ladd J. Anthony, 47, of Cleveland sat impassively, with one elbow
on the defense table, when the verdict was read in U.S. District
Court.
   Anthony said, ``No comment,'' to reporters as he left the
courtroom.
   His attorney, Elmer A. Giuliani, said it was too early to say
whether there would be an appeal.
   In a statement distributed in the federal courthouse after the
verdict was read, Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said the decision was ``the
end to a sad episode that began in November 1986,'' when he asked
the Justice Department to investigate allegations that Anthony had
been acting improperly with his constituents.
   It is illegal for federal employees to accept money or any thing
of value in return for performing their official duties.
   ``Those who are sworn to uphold the law should expect no leniency
when they break the law,'' Metzenbaum said.
   No date was set for sentencing.
   Anthony was convicted of accepting $300 from Irena Boc, who
testified last week that she gave Anthony the money in an envelope
in 1983 to help her with an application for U.S. citizenship.
   Waclaw Pietrzykowski testified that Anthony solicited $2,300 from
him in 1985 to help the daughter of his landlady, Anni Wojcieszko,
with her application to the Ohio State University College of
Veterinary Medicine. Pietrzykowski and Wojcieszko testified they
gave Anthony $1,000 and that he later returned $500.
   The trial began March 1.
   In closing arguments, Giuliani tried to shift blame for the
alleged payoffs to others and to point up discrepancies in testimony.
   But prosecutors blamed the discrepancies on time lapses and the
difficulty Polish witnesses had with the English language.
   ``The truth is Ladd Anthony is the one ripping off these
people,'' said Jackie M. Bennett Jr., a lawyer with the Justice
Department's Public Integrity Section.
   ``Ladd Anthony is the one who took advantage of some of the most
vulnerable people in our society,'' Bennett said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MusicalChocolate     03-08 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Musical Chocolate,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Julia Child Recipe Set to Music</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attention, dieters. The musical recipe for a
wickedly delicious chocolate cake by Julia Child is being cooked up
at the Kennedy Center tonight. It takes about 20 minutes to devour,
and it doesn't contain a single calorie.
   But composer Lee Hoiby warns that his ``Bon Appetit!'' a new
musical monologue performed by actress Jean Stapleton with Hoiby at
the piano, may tempt chocolate lovers to break their vows of
abstinence.
   ``I am tempted not only by the lyrics but by the cake itself,''
confesses Hoiby, who is trying to observe a diet of such macrobiotic
foods as cabbage, brown rice and fish with seaweed.
   ``I often give in to temptation and say I'll make up for it
later,'' he said during a prerehearsal interview. ``I love chocolate
cake. The things that are out of reach are what we love in this
world.''
   Hoiby's piece is based on the videotape of a 1961 television
cooking lesson by Julia Child, and will be served as the dessert
course for an evening of Hoiby's music at the Terrace Theater.
   After its world premiere here, Hoiby and Miss Stapleton will
perform the work at Long Beach, Calif., on March 31 and at Santa Fe,
N.M., on April 9.
   On stage, Miss Stapleton sings and pantomimes her way around an
imaginary kitchen, using lyrics taken from Miss Child's tape, as she
prepares a ``very special, ve-e-ery choc'late-ly, bittersweet,
loooovely cake'' called Le Gateau au Chocolat, l`Eminence Brune.
   ``What I love is her wonderful sense of theater,'' the actress
says. ``She's not just a cook. She's a character, very rich and very
humorous.''
   Miss Stapleton makes the most of the TV chef's comic touches,
tapping an invisible cake pan and instructing her audience to
``knock out the flour on the floor, if you have a self-cleaning
kitchen like mine.''
   And she engages in a fast-paced musical race with an electric
mixer, as she beats egg whites in an unlined copper bowl. ``We're
going to see who wins,'' she sings, ``and I think maybe I'll win ...
because I'm bigger.''
   Hoiby says ``Bon Appetit!'' _ which takes its title from Miss
Child's familiar closing line _ was composed as a concert
curtain-raiser for a longer work he wrote in 1984, his operatic
version of the late Ruth Draper's monologue, ``The Italian Lesson.''
   Hoiby and associate Mark Shulgasser came up with the idea of
using the script of a Julia Child cooking lesson as a vehicle for
Miss Stapleton, a veteran of Broadway musicals who is better known
as Archie Bunker's wife, Edith, on the ``All in the Family'' TV
series.
   Miss Stapleton wrote Miss Child for permission. Miss Child
happily agreed, and sent a batch of her tapes for viewing. Hoiby,
who watched them for four full days, became intrigued by the chef's
``rhapsodic phrases'' and musical metaphors.
   ``Her speaking patterns really grab you, the phraseology, the
unexpected little interjections,'' he said. ``There is a kind of
musical cadence in her speech which one isn't aware of unless one
starts to set it to music, and then there it is.''
   Is there something musical, too, about chocolate cake?
   ``Well, you see, chocolate cake, it's a very special moment,''
Hoiby replied. ``It's an indulgence, something you don't want to do
too much of. It's like a reward _ you ate all your spinach, now you
can have your reward. It's put in a very special category as a
treat.''
   Getting hungry?
   After tonight's concert, members of the audience will gather at a
reception to nibble on the real thing, Le Gateau au Chocolat,
l'Eminence Brune, prepared from Miss Child's recipe by the Kennedy
Center chef.
   ``The cake is going to be the icing,'' says Shulgasser.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-OvernightVisits     03-08 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Overnight Visits,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court: Divorced Mother Can't Let Boyfriend Stay Over While Kids Are
Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The boyfriend of a mother of three cannot
spend the night while the children are home, the state's highest
court has ruled.
   The state Supreme Court on Tuesday upheld a lower court decision
to bar the boyfriend, Joseph DiPippo, from staying overnight, saying
the ruling raised no major constitutional issues.
   Civil libertarians expressed surprise at the decision and found
the remark that the case raised no constitutional questions
disturbing.
   ``I think that the state of Rhode Island has made a very poor
statemeent about women, divorced women, single parents and their
children, and their collective rights to privacy in their own
homes,'' said Patricia A. Hurst, an American Civil Liberties Union
attorney for Carla J. Parrillo.
   Ms. Parrillo and her husband, Justin Jr., were divorced in May
1986, and Ms. Parrillo was given custody of her children, two
daughters and a son, ages 8 13 at the time. Parrillo was given
visitation rights.
   In June, the Parrillos returned to Family Court, and Ms. Parrillo
wanted her ex-husband to see the children in a location away from
her home. Parrillo wanted his ex-wife restrained from having any
``unrelated males'' stay overnight at her house.
   Ms. Parrillo contended that her ex-husband began to harass her
upon learning that she was dating DiPippo.
   DiPippo stayed overnight once or twice a week, Ms. Parrillo said,
and it caused no harm to her children, who were in separate
bedrooms. She told the court that her children liked DiPippo, but
she had no plans to marry him in the near future.
   Parrillo began reducing his support payments when he learned
DiPippo was visiting, the high court said.
   The children told the lower court's judge in a private meeting
that they all got along well with DiPippo, although the son said
there were times he disliked the man.
   But the judge ruled the overnight visits ``in the presence of the
children, were not conducive to their general well-being, at least
in terms of their psychological welfare,'' the high court said.
   The judge also had noted that if Ms. Parrillo married DiPippo,
the issue would become moot.
   Ms. Parrillo appealed, saying the judge erred because no evidence
existed that her sleeping with DiPippo psychologically harmed her
children.
   But the high court upheld the Family Court decision, saying that
ruling ``was without question directed at Joseph. ... Joseph may
still visit the marital domicile overnight, with the exception of
those times when the children are with their mother.''
   Hurst said she hoped Ms. Parrillo would appeal the decision.
   ``The practical effect on Carla Parrillo is that she is precluded
from conducting her private activities in the privacy of her own
home at her discretion,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
