<FIRST>r w PM-NavyDeaths     03-08 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navy Deaths,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Recruit's Death Blamed on Safety Neglect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of a 19-year-old Navy recruit during
training a year ago resulted from the service's neglect for safety
procedures and pressure on the training system from higher-ups,
according to a congressional investigation.
   In a report released Tuesday, the General Accounting Office said
Lee Mirecki of Appleton, Wis., died at the Navy's Pensacola, Fla.,
Rescue Swimmer School in part because of ``an intimidating,
non-volunteer atmosphere and inadequate controls at the school and
its superior commands.''
   Some of the flaws remain uncorrected, the GAO said. And it found
that of 16 other Navy training deaths between Jan. 1, 1986, and the
end of last year, safety problems contributed to five of the
fatalities.
   ``The bottom line is that Navy instructors still are not trained
to conduct high-risk training and that students still are not
screened to make sure they can handle the dangers,'' said Rep. Toby
Roth, R-Wis., who requested the investigation along with the other
members of the state's congressional delegation.
   Roth called Mirecki's death ``a tragedy waiting to happen,''
pointing to GAO findings that he was unqualified for the swimming
rescue course, had untrained and unsupervised instructors and was
prevented from dropping out because of pressure on the school to
increase the number of graduates it turned out.
   ``This GAO report is a catalog of failures by the Navy, which led
to Lee Mirecki's death and others,'' Roth said at a news conference.
He vowed to follow up to see that remaining problems are resolved
and asked Vice Admiral John Disher, head of the service's training
system, to contact families of recruits who died in training ``to
tell them what really happened.''
   The GAO said it had discussed its findings with the Navy and
reported that officials ``generally agreed'' and ``were receptive to
suggestions on how to improve training safety'' and accident
investigations.
   Mirecki panicked during a swimming-pool drill known as ``sharks
and daisies,'' in which swimmers must free themselves from an
instructor who grabs them from behind, simulating a drowning person.
After counseling and medical examination, he was found ``not
physically qualified'' for the course because of a phobia of being
held under water.
   But despite the findings, he was re-enrolled in the class and
forced to undergo the drill again. GAO said Mirecki left the pool
and clutched an equipment rack, shouting such things as ``I quit''
and ``Please don't put me back in the water,'' but was dragged back
to the pool by instructors. After a struggle in the pool, he was
removed unconscious and could not be revived.
   An autopsy found that Mirecki probably died of heartbeat
irregularity caused by extreme fear, fatigue and decreased oxygen.
The lead instructor was found guilty by a general court martial of
negligent homicide and sentenced to a demotion and 90 days'
confinement. Eight others associated with the class were given
various administrative punishments, including demotions and
reprimands.
   Some improvements have been made, GAO said. The ``sharks and
daisies'' drill has been dropped, instructors are given better
training and safety equipment is kept on hand at the swimming pool.
There also is a clearer policy regarding students' rights to drop
out of a course, the investigators said.
   But the GAO said there remains great pressure on students not to
drop out of a course because it is made clear to them that doing so
will adversely affect their careers, and that there still is no
system to alert instructors to students with a history of problems.
</TEXT>
