<FIRST>r i PM-Raisa     03-08 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Raisa,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Media, in Switch, Report on Raisa Gorbachev's Views</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tass did not go into loving detail on what Raisa
Gorbachev wore or who did her hair, but it did report on what the
first lady was thinking about some world and domestic issues _ an
unusual turn for Soviet media.
   Mrs. Gorbachev, wife of the president and Communist Party chief,
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, spoke at a a reception she gave Monday in
honor of International Women's Day, a Soviet holiday that is being
celebrated today.
   She talked about her husband's reform policies and about how the
world's women have improved prospects for peace, and Tass, the
official Soviet news agency, reported her views.
   State-run television frequently shows the stylish Russian first
lady and Western journalists interview her. But it is rare for
fellow Soviets to be let in on her thoughts.
   ``If people currently are more confident of a peaceful future, we
know that much of the credit goes to women actively working on all
continents for friendship, cooperation and profound mutual
understanding of nations,'' Mrs. Gorbachev said at the reception, as
reported by Tass.
   For Tass to be covering the reception itself _ for wives of
ambassadors and other diplomats in Moscow, wives of members of the
ruling Communist Party Politburo and Soviet women in various fields
_ was unusual.
   Before Gorbachev came to power four years ago, Kremlin wives
almost invariably were kept backstage.
   Mrs. Gorbachev changed that. The attractive, 57-year-old former
teacher of Marxist-Leninist philosophy has taken a role somewhat
resembling that of the wife of a U.S. president.
   Not all Soviets are delighted with the change.
   Many are taken aback by her wardrobe, large and glamorous by
Soviet standards. Others grumble that she is too involved in her
husband's work.
   On Monday, Mrs. Gorbachev gave the grumblers some ammunition by
going public with some of her views.
   Speaking of her husband's reforms, she said, ``Soviet people are
putting into practice plans of revolutionary restructuring. We are
connecting to it the destiny of our country, of our nation. We want
our public life in all aspects _ socio-economic, political, moral,
ecological, and in the sphere of human rights and freedoms _ to be
worthy of a human being.
   ``By transforming and renewing our society on a socialist basis,
on the principles of humanism and democracy, we are making our
country more open for all the nations of the world.'
   She greeted her guests individually and gave each a bouquet,
reported Rebecca Matlock, wife of U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock.
   ``She's a very attractive, intelligent and vocal woman. If they
let her speak more often, everyone would benefit,'' Mrs. Matlock
told The Associated Press.
   The Gorbachevs later attended a televised celebration held in the
Bolshoi Theater in Moscow to mark International Women's Day.
   This time, things were a little more typical.
   Gorbachev sat on the dais with other Politburo members and
dignitaries.
   His wife was in the audience.
</TEXT>
