<FIRST>r w PM-Whistleblowers     03-08 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whistleblowers,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whistleblower Bill on the Move Again in the Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill to protect so-called ``whistleblowers''
who expose government waste, fraud and abuse is back in the Senate
after a compromise between sponsors and the Bush administration.
   ``This very well might be the first bill to be signed by the
president this year,'' Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said at a news
conference Tuesday in which sponsors unveiled a revised version of
the measure.
   The bill would ease the way for federal employees to win
reinstatement if demoted or fired after disclosing mismanagement.
   Then-President Ronald Reagan blocked the measure by a pocket
veto, meaning he refused to sign the bill and Congress was out of
session at the time. He said it could result in the government
fighting legal battles against itself.
   Reagan's move received heavy criticism in a surprised Congress
and from Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   Lawmakers agreed under the compromise to give up a provision of
last year's bill that would have allowed a special counsel
representing employees to go to court, said Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich.
   In turn, the administration agreed to a provision barring the
special counsel from opposing whistleblowers in any action before
the Merit Systems Protection Board, the agency that enforces civil
service safeguards.
   The administration also agreed to greater privacy protection
under the bill, while the senators approved a minor rewording under
which employees are deemed whistleblowers if their exposure of
waste, fraud or abuse was ``a contributing factor'' in the decision
to discipline them. The change inserted the word ``contributing.''
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh promised in a letter to Levin
``our cooperation to discourage any amendments, in either body of
Congress, that might in any way interfere with this agreement.''
   ``None of the changes to which we have agreed detracts in any way
from the Congress' intent to strengthen whistleblower protections,''
the letter said.
</TEXT>
