<FIRST>u p AM-StLouisElection     03-08 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-St Louis Election,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Wins Democratic Primary In St. Louis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Vincent C. Schoemehl, seeking to become
only the third mayor in city history to gain a third term, easily
won the Democratic primary on Tuesday against two oppponents.
   In final, unofficial results, Schoemehl had 36,743 ballots, or
61.5 percent of the vote, to former Alderman Michael V. Roberts, who
had 20,581. A third candidate, retired businessman John Noel, had
2,382.
   Schoemehl's nomination would be tantamount to a third four-year
term in the heavily Democratic city. The general election will be
held April 4.
   ``This has been a tremendous day for St. Louis,'' Schoemehl said.
``We in fact have a very bright future in the track that we are on.''
   In the Republican mayoral primary, auto repair shop owner Bernard
J. Elking edged Joan F. Lang, who owns a pet grooming shop, by 31
votes. Elking had 928 votes to 897 for Lang. Roy Lang, a used tire
dealer who is not related to the other candidate, had 138 votes.
   Voters also cast ballots for aldermen in 10 of the city's 28
wards.
   Election commissioner Jerry B. Wamser had predicted that fewer
than a third of the city's 216,500 voters would participate in the
wake of a late winter storm that dumped 11 inches of snow on the
area Sunday and Monday. By late Tuesday, that estimate was
downgraded to possibly only 25 percent in spite of temperatures that
rose to the low 30s.
</TEXT>
