<DOCNO> AP890308-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0319EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     03-08 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Leader Says Backing from ASEAN Weakening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cambodian resistance's main backer,
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, has lessened its once
firm support for a U.N. peacekeeping force in postwar Cambodia and
for other key resistance proposals, a guerrilla leader says.
   Prince Norodom Ranariddh also said Tuesday that he would leave
for the United States this weekend to ask Washington for more covert
aid to force Vietnam to be more flexible at the negotiating table.
   The resistance has repeatedly requested arms, but Washington
provides only limited non-lethal aid.
   Ranariddh is the son of central Cambodian resistance leader
Prince Norodom Sihanouk and commands one of three guerrilla groups
resisting Vietnam's 10-year-old occupation of Cambodia.
   He told a group of reporters that ASEAN's support for the
resistance proposals weakened at peace talks last month in
Indonesia. ASEAN mediated those talks, which brought together
Vietnam and the warring factions in Cambodia.
   Ranariddh said he was troubled by the shift.
   He said only a U.N. peacekeeping force can prevent renewed
fighting and a return of Vietnamese troops, who have said they hope
to withdraw next year, or by brutal Khmer Rouge guerrillas.
   Vietnam and the government it installed in Cambodia have opposed
introducing an armed international force.
   ``I am very sorry for the sake of my people that the ASEAN stand
is not as firm as before,'' Ranariddh told a group of reporters.
   He said a majority of ASEAN delegates at the conference did not
support an international peackeeping force and no longer clearly
support the idea of an interim postwar government under Prince
Sihanouk's leadership and comprised of the three resistance factions
and the Vietnam-backed regime.
   ``They do not support even the idea of having free
self-determination and free elections in Cambodia,'' he said.
   In 1982, ASEAN sponsored the formation of the guerrilla
coalition. It gives the group sanctuary and arms and leads the
diplomatic struggle against Vietnam. The non-Communist ASEAN
includes Thailand, Indonesia, Singapore, Malaysia, Brunei and the
Philippines.
   The guerrilla coalition joins the nationalist forces of Sihanouk
and Son Sann with a group they strongly distrust, the militarily
potent Khmer Rouge. The fanatical Communist group killed hundreds of
thousands of people when it ruled Cambodia from 1975 until Vietnam
ousted it in the late 1978 invasion.
   Ranariddh would not name the ASEAN countries whose support had
weakened, nor say why that support had weakened. He said, however,
that said a notable exception was Singapore's Prime Minister Lee
Kuan Yew.
   In January, Thai Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan was host to
an unprecedented visit to Thailand by Hun Sen, premier of Cambodia's
Vietnamese-installed government.
   Some diplomats said Chatichai has seriously weakened the
resistance in his rush to get a settlement and transform Cambodia's
battlefields into markets for Thai goods. Ranariddh has said his
father, who had quit as resistance coalition president, resumed the
post in February to counter the increasing worldwide support for Hun
Sen.
   Ranariddh said that during his trip to Washington he would tell
officials that other steps are needed to weaken the Khmer Rouge
aside from U.S. attempts to pressure China to halt its aid to them.
   He expressed optimism that China, which arms the guerrillas, and
the Soviet Union, which arms Vietnam, will reach an agreement on
Cambodia during their summit in May. He said they recently had
converged on many points and all that remains was for the Soviets to
guarantee a Vietnamese pullout and the Chinese to guarantee in turn
that the Khmer Rouge will not return to power.
   ``If they will overcome this, (the settlement is) finished,''
Ranariddh said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
