<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-PieceofTheirMind Bjt   03-08 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Piece of Their Mind, Bjt,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Dear Sir, You Bum' _ an Old Tradition Hailed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he's been told by a fellow
from Lubbock, Texas, not to worry about all the inside-Washington
talk about an administration aimless and adrift. ``All the people in
Lubbock think things are going just great,'' the president says.
   If Bush wants assurance that the people will tell him when things
are going just great, and not so great, all he has to do is wander
down Pennsylvania Avenue to the National Archives, storehouse of the
nation's records. An exhibition there celebrates 200 years of the
people petitioning the government _ or giving it a piece of its mind.
   Exhibit A along those lines comes from a boy named Anthony, who
was in H.B. Milnes School at Fair Lawn, N.J., when President Ford
pardoned President Nixon for the crimes of Watergate. Anthony had a
fixed mixed opinion:
   ``Dear President Ford,
   ``I think you are half right and half wrong.
   ``Yours truly,
   ``Anthony Ferreira.''
   Bush, replacing Reaganites with Bushites, also would find
familiar echoes in the 1789 complaint of Mary Katherine Goodard, who
lost her job as postmaster of Baltimore after serving through the
tough days of the Revolutionary War.
   Said her petition: ``She hath been discharged without the
smallest imputations of any fault, and without any previous notice
whatever. ... These are but poor rewards indeed for 14 years
faithful services, performed in the worst of times.''
   To no avail. She didn't get reinstated.
   The Constitution's First Amendment gives the people the right
``to petition the government for a redress of grievances.'' But even
before the government existed, the American people were exercising
their right to talk back to authority.
   In 1773, the governor of Connecticut petitioned a member of the
British Parliament to protest the closing of the port of Boston in
retaliation for the Boston Tea Party. He wrote, ``We are at a loss
to conceive how the destruction of the East India Company's tea
could be a just or reasonable ground for punishing so severely
thousands of innocent people.''
   Seventeen years later, Pennsylvania Quakers petitioned for the
abolition of slavery: ``The blessings of liberty ... ought
rightfully to be administered, without distinction of colour, to all
descriptions of people.''
   Some petitions to government have been eloquent, some funny, some
moving.
   Annie Davis, a slave from northern Maryland whose mistress
refused to let her join her family, wrote to President Lincoln. She
urgently wanted to know her status: ``You will please let me know if
we are free ...''
   One of the biggest petitions ever to reach Washington remains in
the condition received in 1893 _ rolled up on two huge wooden spools
nearly seven feet high. It consists hundreds of sheets, taped
together, bearing an estimated 150,000 signatures, appealing for a
new bureaucracy.
   ``We the undersigned ... hereby most respectfully petition that
there be founded ... a Road Department, similar to the Agriculture
Department, for the purpose of promoting knowledge in the art of
constructing and maintaining roads.''
   Congress obliged by creating the Office of Road Inquiry in the
Department of Agriculture. Must have pleased the petition's creator,
a bicycle manufacturer.
   Few petitions have had as deep an impact as the one Earl Gideon
wrote in pencil in 1961 from his prison cell in Bay County, Fla.,
where he was serving five years for breaking into a poolroom. ``The
question is very simple. I requested the court to appoint me an
attorney and the court refused.''
   The Supreme Court agreed. Its landmark Gideon decision upheld the
right of poor defendants to be represented by lawyers, at the public
expense if need be.
   In the midst of the Depression, Franklin Roosevelt got a petition
from some young citizens of the Cream Street School in Hyde Park,
N.Y., protesting the removal of a teacher: ``Do we have to have
another teacher when we want Mrs. Sheridan so much? Mr. Roosevelt
you do so many big things, can't you find a way to help us in this
little thing? Because this is a big thing to us kids. It's a pretty
tough `new deal' for us young Democrats and Republicans.''
   But even FDR knew the limits of his powers. Mrs. Sheridan, like
Postmistress Goodard, didn't get her job back, the petitions of the
people notwithstanding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Tower-Senate     03-08 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower-Senate,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Tempers Wear Thin in Tower Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flattery is the first and firmest rule in the
Senate, but in a single day the debate on Defense
Secretary-designate John Tower produced a series of mutual attacks
on integrity, motives and competence.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole touched off Tuesday's fireworks
when he announced that Armed Services Committee Chairman Sam Nunn,
D-Ga., had detailed investigators to check new allegations against
Tower.
   ``Partisan unit,'' Dole later called it. ``Strike force.''
   ``Highly questionable if not inappropriate,'' Republican Sen.
Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania said. ``I think it needs to be pursued
to see where it leads us.''
   Nunn, leader of the Tower opposition, defended himself a short
while later by saying he had been informed the FBI would no longer
look into allegations against Tower.
   He then was asked about Republican claims that his effort to
derail Tower is really an attempt to grab power for himself at the
Pentagon, or perhaps jockey for position in the 1992 White House
campaign.
   ``It's an onslaught,'' he said, ``The basic rule is if you don't
have the facts on your side, you try to destroy the credibility of
someone who is presenting them on the other side. So I think that
formula is in full effect right now.''
   And when Democrat Dennis DeConcini of Arizona said that an FBI
report on Tower turned up evidence of ``wrongdoing,'' Republican
Warren Rudman of New Hampshire replied tartly. That wasn't so, he
said _ at least not the way Americans use the term.
   ``I'm an American, too,'' shot back DeConcini.
   Hearing DeConcini's retort, Rudman persisted that Tower had
committed no legal wrongdoing.
   Shot back DeConcini, ``In my judgment it's wrong. OK?''
   But the sharpest exchanges were saved for an extraordinary late
afternoon performance. Roughly 30 senators stayed in their seats for
the debate, the ultimate courtesy in an institution where most
lawmakers come to the Senate chamber only to cast their votes before
hurrying back to their offices.
   They saw an exchange between Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine, and Rudman, who said it was a ``fact'' that there
was no evidence in the FBI report that Tower had ever been impaired
by alcohol in performing his duties.
   Mitchell, a former judge, interrupted to say that was Rudman's
opinion, not a fact.
   Rudman said he had spent 24 years practicing law, and knew how to
read evidence.
   ``I think I know how to do that just as well as you do,'' said
Mitchell, who is a former federal judge as well as a lawyer.
   ``I'm sure,'' shot back Rudman, a former New Hampshire attorney
general.
   Nothing was too good to pass up as partisan feelings boiled over.
   Dole complained bitterly that Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C. was
guilty of ``vicious personal attacks'' for earlier citing
allegations contained in the FBI report from witnesses who said they
had seen Tower ``crocked,'' ``sloshed,'' and ``comatose.''
   Hollings protested, but Dole persisted that the South Carolinian
was an insulter of longstanding. He referred to the ``comment he
once made about the senator from Ohio'' and later referred to a
long-ago crack about the ``senator from Texaco.''
   The first was a reference to Hollings' description of Sen. Howard
Metzenbaum years ago as the senator from B'nai B'rith. The second
was Hollings' one-time description of Texas Democrat Lloyd Bentsen.
   Amidst the partisan crossfire, Dole's irritation with one of his
Republican colleagues, Virginia's John Warner, slipped out.
   Dole said that as the senior Republican on the Armed Services
Committee, Warner had known what Nunn was doing but had not passed
the word along to the Republican leadership.
   ``I don't know why he didn't tell me,'' Dole said of his Virginia
colleague.
   ``He should have.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
