<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Pledges `New Era' For Housing Department</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp, pledging a ``new
era'' at HUD, said he will actively seek solutions to the nation's
housing problems, from discrimination to homelessness to urban
blight.
   ``I'm willing to be audacious,'' Kemp said Tuesday in his first
congressional testimony as secretary of Housing and Urban
Development.
   Members of the House Banking, Finance and Urban Affairs Committee
warmly welcomed Kemp, a former nine-term congressman, noting his
appearance in itself was a good sign after poor Capitol Hill
relations with President Reagan's HUD Secretary, Samuel Pierce.
   Pierce, dubbed ``Silent Sam'' by his opponents, last appeared
before the housing committee in March 1985. By contrast, Kemp
pounded the table and spoke emotionally as he vigorously testified
about his commitment to curing housing ills.
   ``Snow or sleet or rain, I think it's very symbolic that I am
here today,'' said Kemp.
   He outlined several issues where HUD will take sharp turns away
from Reagan's administration and vowed to work with Democrats and
Republicans in Congress on the housing and economic development.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Senators Propose Permanent Airline Smoking Ban</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop has endorsed a
proposal by two senators to permanently ban cigarette smoking on all
domestic flights.
   The measure introduced Tuesday would expand the current
prohibition against smoking, which covers flights of two hours or
less and is due to expire in April 1990.
   ``The time has come to protect the health and safety of all
airline passengers,'' said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., who
co-sponsored the bill with Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
   At the senators' news conference to announce the proposal, Koop
said such a ban is ``long overdue.''
   He cited a recent study by the National Cancer Institute which
found that passengers in non-smoking sections of airliners had
levels of nicotine in their saliva and urine similar to travelers in
smoking areas.
   The bill would leave intact the $1,000 fine that can be levied
against those violating the smoking ban, and the $2,000 penalty for
people caught tampering with smoke detectors in airline restrooms.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Sullivan Sees No Reason to Change Catastrophic Care Program</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan says he sees no reason to change the new catastrophic care
program financed by a surtax on elderly Americans.
   ``We're aware of a number of concerns that have been expressed
(about the financing provision) but ... we are also concerned about
the many examples of our elderly citizens being wiped out
financially by the tremendous costs of illness,'' Sullivan said
Tuesday.
   ``We feel that because this legislation has just been enacted we
don't have much experience with it yet. We'd like to follow this and
see if adjustments need to be made,'' he told the House Ways and
Means Committee.
   Leaders in the House and Senate also have been generally
unsympathetic to complaints from senior citizens who oppose the
financing provision of the program, which helps the elderly and
disabled bear the cost of illness that otherwise would threaten
their financial stability.
   For Medicare-eligible Americans _ those who are over 65 or
disabled _ whose incomes are high enough that they pay at least $150
a year in federal income taxes, the surtax is 15 percent of their
income tax this year. Next year it is 25 percent and it could rise
by as much as 1 percentage point a year after that.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Subcommittee Approves Uniform Poll Closing Bill</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to impose a uniform closing time
for polls across the 48 contiguous states has cleared a House
subcommittee.
   The elections subcommittee of the House Administration Committee
approved the measure Tuesday on a voice vote. Rep. Al Swift,
D-Wash., the subcommittee chairman, said he expects Congress will
approve the bill this year.
   The measure, similar to ones twice approved by the House, now
goes to the full committee.
   Election officials in the West have complained that voters in
their states sometimes decide not to vote when the winner of a
presidential election is known before their polls close and that the
drop in turnout has affected the outcome of close local races.
   Under the bill, polls would close simultaneously in the 48
contiguous states at 9 p.m. EST. In the Pacific Time Zone, daylight
saving time would be extended for a maximum of two weeks in
presidential election years. The extension would allow polls in that
time zone to close at 7 p.m. PDT.
   Alaska and Hawaii are exempt from the legislation.
</TEXT>
