<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Prices, Dollar Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices fell on the Tokyo Stock Exchange on
Wednesday, erasing gains in the morning session, and the U.S. dollar
declined against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar closed at 128.73 yen, down 0.30 yen from Tuesday's
129.03-yen finish. It opened at 128.68 yen and ranged between 128.65
yen and 128.90 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 61.08-point
gainer the previous day, fell 100.28 points, or 0.31 percent,
closing at 31,837.66.
   After morning gains, dealers said the Nikkei started to fall on
selling that followed news of the arrests of former Labor Ministry
official Takashi Kato and Masao Tasumi, an executive of the
employment information conglomerate Recruit Co. That brought to 12
the number of people arrested in connection with a
stock-profiteering scandal involving politicians and business
leaders.
   In currency dealings, the dollar declined mainly because of
selling for profit taking, traders said.
   But the dollar-yen rate moved little in the absence of
market-affecting incentives, said one trader with a major commercial
bank in Tokyo.
   Market participants also were reluctant to make major moves
before Friday's release of U.S. employment figures for February,
said another.
</TEXT>
