<DOCNO> AP890308-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0450EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SovietPremier     03-08 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Premier,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Gives Frank Look At Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov, offering a rare glimpse
inside the workings of the Kremlin, says reformers began planning
changes in the Soviet system two years before Mikhail S. Gorbachev
came to power.
   He said planning for perestroika, Gorbachev's program of economic
and social reform, began in 1983, about the time former KGB chief
Yuri Andropov became Soviet leader.
   ``Even at that time, we had forces who understood that everything
was not healthy in our economy,'' Ryzhkov told 33 female journalists
gathered in St. Catherine's Hall of the Grand Kremlin Palace on the
eve of International Women's Day.
   Ryzkhov's frank remarks touched on details of his personal life
and frustration with the slow pace of reform.
   He promised to reveal the long-secret Soviet defense budget in 12
to 18 months, after accountants have arranged it in a form
comparable to U.S. figures, apparently for use in arms negotiations.
   As part of the plan to shift Soviet spending ``from swords to
plowshares,'' defense factories that produce 60 percent military
hardware and 40 percent consumer goods will move to a 50-50 ratio by
1991 and 40-60 by 1995, he said.
   For example, the Moscow Aviation Factory soon will produce pasta,
he said.
   Ryzhkov said he found the slow pace of economic reform the most
upsetting part of his job.
   ``I like to see how the decisions we are taking in the state
bodies are implemented in the level of real life,'' he said. That is
why he enjoys visiting factories that remind him of the Ural
Machine-Building Plant in Sverdlovsk where his career began, ``to
feel the smell of machine parts being manufactured, the smell of
real work,'' he said.
   Ryzhkov blamed part of the country's problems on corrupt
bureaucrats. He also said 40 percent of factory equipment must be
replaced.
   ``We have to make certain investments, we have to have know-how,
and we have to have time for that,'' he said.
   The premier also tackled the notorious shortage of laundry soap.
   ``In Moscow, we used to sell 80 tons of detergent daily. Now we
sell 300 tons daily, and still we have lines for detergent.'' Then
he quipped, ``I don't believe the overall washing has increased all
that much.''
   He suggested that journalists created a self-fulfilling prophecy
by publicizing a soap shortage until people began hoarding even more.
   To eliminate shortages, he said, wages must stop rising faster
than retail trade and productivity.
   In an unusual discussion of his personal life, Ryzhkov said he
answers his own phone in a 13-hour to 14-hour workday, and continues
work at home. As a result, he misses the theater and concerts.
   The 59-year-old premier said his wife, Ludmila, is a mechanical
engineer who designed excavators at the same factory where he rose
to director.
   He said she reads extensively on the countries they visit and
works on behalf of orphans.
   Ryzhkov said his daughter is a law professor at the Academy of
the Interior Ministry, and her husband also is a lawyer, in the
customs office. They have two children, Ludmila, 2, and Nikolai, 6.
   Women already hold 25 percent of the management jobs in the
Soviet Union, and this should expand under perestroika, Ryzhkov said.
   ``Until now, administrative methods were more suited to a man
with a loud voice,'' he said. ``Now we have to control the economy
not with a shout but with an intellect, and that will allow women to
have their say.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
