<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0609EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-AlabamaElection     03-08 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alabama Election,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Loses Bid to Become First Black Alabama Congressman This Century</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mayor who was trounced in his bid to
become the state's first black congressman since Reconstruction
praised his Democratic primary opponent, the secretary of state, for
avoiding racial politics.
   ``We did not lose tonight. Alabama won,'' Tuskegee Mayor Johnny
Ford said after being soundly defeated by Secretary of State Glen
Browder in Tuesday's runoff.
   Browder, 46, a former Jacksonville State University professor and
legislator, swept 12 of the 3rd Congressional District's 13 counties
in defeating Ford, who won only in predominantly black Macon County,
where he lives. The rest of the east Alabama district is
three-fourths white.
   With all precincts reporting, Browder had 44,384 votes, or 63
percent, to Ford's 26,257 votes, or 37 percent.
   Browder will now face state Sen. John Rice, who hopes to give the
GOP its first congressional gain in Alabama in a quarter-century.
The special election is scheduled for April 4.
   ``Mayor Ford ran an excellent campaign,'' said Browder. ``He
added class to it. The way he campaigned, the way we campaigned, is
testimony to his career and his future in Alabama politics.''
   Ford, 46, said the Democratic primary, by avoiding virtually any
hint of negative racial politics, ``demonstrated to the nation that
Alabama is on the move.''
   The seat became open with the death Dec. 13 of Bill Nichols, a
Democrat who had represented the eastern Alabama district for 22
years. The district, which includes the university town of Auburn
and the industrial town of Anniston, traditionally has been
Democratic.
   Browder narrowly led Ford in a splintered field of nine
candidates in the first Democratic primary Feb. 14.
   Alabama's last black congressman, Jeremiah Haralson, served from
1875 to 1877.
</TEXT>
