<FIRST>r a PM-Lottery-Death     03-08 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lottery-Death,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends Say Lottery Winner Died A Happy Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALDOSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three new cars, a used car, three pairs of
shoes, a pair of pants and half a racehorse were about all Jake
Malham had time to buy with $1 million in Florida lottery winnings
before he died of a heart attack.
   Malham, a liquor store and lounge owner who died Monday at age 53
of an apparent heart attack, became the first Georgian to win big
money in Florida's lottery. Friends said Tuesday he died a happy man.
   ``All that money didn't change Jake,'' said R.B. Spriggs, a
friend of Malham's for 30 years. ``It probably relieved him, more
than anything else, of financial pressures.''
   If anything, Spriggs said, the money only made a nice guy nicer.
   After he won the Jan. 12 drawing, he bought new cars for himself,
his mother and his girlfriend, Joann Williamson. Ms. Williamson said
he bought a used car for his brother and the pants and shoes for
himself.
   After that, he was the ``same old Jake,'' she said.
   Malham paid off the debts on his property and gave $1,000 each to
six employees at First State Bank and Trust's branch in Valdosta.
Friends said he had told the employees he'd give them a share if he
ever hit the lottery.
   But Jim Griffin, another longtime friend, said, ``I think the one
thing he was most proud of was that he had paid off everything he
owed.''
   Even after Malham won the Scratch Three lottery contest, he
continued to open his liquor store at 8 a.m. each day, and still
lived in the same mobile home.
   Recently, Malham and Spriggs traveled to Henderson, Ky., to watch
the running of a horse in which they both owned shares. The horse,
Cash Not Silver, won its heat, Spriggs said, and the overjoyed
Malham was showing off his trophy at his liquor store the morning of
his death.
   His body was found in his mobile home that afternoon.
   Spriggs said Malham changed so little that when they traveled
together to the dog races in Jacksonville, Fla., and the horse races
in Tampa, Fla., bills were split 50-50 just as if his pal didn't
have a fortune.
   ``That was fine with me. I didn't want anything from him, and he
knew that,'' Spriggs said.
   Malham had told Spriggs that of the $800,000 he had cleared after
taxes, he had invested about $600,000 of it in high-yield
certificates of deposit, ``so he wasn't blowing this money. He knew
what he was doing.''
   Spriggs and Ms. Williamson said Malham had battled health
problems for much of his life. But they didn't think the excitement
of winning the lottery contributed to his death.
   ``The only time I really worried about his health is when he won
it the lottery. I made him sit down, he was so excited,'' Spriggs
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
