<DOCNO> AP890308-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern-Finances     03-08 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Finances,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cash Drain, Pilot Walkout Moving Eastern Closer To Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strike-bound Eastern Airlines is rapidly draining
its cash reserves and soon may have to seek bankruptcy protection,
auction off its assets or, most likely, sell itself to the highest
bidder, analysts say.
   The possibility of Eastern filing under Chapter 11 of federal
bankruptcy laws was heightened Tuesday when the airline said it
couldn't last until the weekend without its 3,600 pilots, most of
whom have refused to cross the picket lines of the striking
Machinists union.
   Eastern is quickly bleeding the $400 million in cash it had on
hand at the beginning of the year, and faces large debt payments
that could force it to seek protection from its creditors, analysts
said.
   ``They're not forced to declare bankruptcy but they can also see
those payments looming in the horizon,'' said Bill Swelbar, director
of industry analysis for Airline Economics Inc.
   The option that analysts see as most likely, however, would be an
outright sale of the 60-year-old carrier. Carl Icahn's Trans World
Airlines already has discussed buying Eastern.
   Analysts place a purchase price anywhere from $400 million plus
debt payments to $900 million for ailing Eastern, which lost $335.4
million last year, nearly double its 1987 loss.
   Analysts doubt that Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent
company, Texas Air Corp., planned to thrust Eastern into bankruptcy
when the Machinists strike began Saturday. Lorenzo used bankruptcy
filing as a way to break the union contracts at Continental Airlines
after Texas Air bought that airline in 1983.
   ``I think the game plan was to force this thing to a showdown and
hopefully get the pilots across the picket line, basically undoing
the Machinists,'' said Louis Marckesano, an analyst with Janney
Montgomery Scott Inc. of Philadelphia.
   But the pilots' decision to honor the strike may have thrown a
wrench into Lorenzo's strategy. A federal judge Tuesday refused to
order the pilots back into the cockpit.
   Most of Eastern's cash _ an estimated $350 million _ represents
money that customers paid in advance for tickets that now must be
refunded or transfered to competitors that honor the tickets. The
money will dwindle within several weeks, according to analysts.
   With limited flights, Eastern, which did about $10 million in
daily business before the strike, has few advance bookings and no
revenue. So it must drain cash reserves to pay wages, overhead and
debt.
   Eastern could get a cash transfusion from the pending $365
million sale of its profitable Northeast shuttle _ one of two
Eastern operations still running _ to New York developer Donald
Trump. Eastern says the strike has not affected the deal, which
awaits final federal approval.
   Repayment of debt associated with the sale and a required pension
fund payment would leave Eastern with about $210 million.
   ``If they don't get the proceeds from the shuttle I would say
they'd have to declare bankruptcy by the end of the month,'' said
Philip Baggaley, an airline bond analyst for Standard &amp; Poor's
Corp., a major Wall Street credit-rating agency.
   ``If they do, they could probably survive another month or two
and try to sell more operations and more assets,'' he said. ``But
the prospects aren't good no matter what happens.''
   Despite shutting down most of its operations and laying off 9,500
non-union workers this week, analysts estimate Eastern has an
operating cash loss of at least $2 million a day for payments
ranging from leasing airport ticket counters to paying 1,500
remaining employees.
   But should Lorenzo file for protection, he would have a tougher
time abrogating the unions' contracts than he did at Continental. As
a result of 1985 amendments to the bankruptcy laws, Lorenzo first
would have to negotiate further with the Eastern unions and
demonstrate that he had no alternative before firing the workers.
   Another option would be for Eastern to auction its planes,
airport gates, routes and landing rights to other airlines in a
liquidation under Chapter 7 of federal bankruptcy laws.
</TEXT>
