<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0633EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     03-08 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Separatists Kill Politician</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Tamil separatists killed a
moderate Tamil politician in eastern Sri Lanka today, just one day
before he was to take his seat in Parliament, authorities said.
   In the capital, suspected anti-government radicals burst into a
research laboratory and shot and killed the former vice chancellor
of Colombo University, police said.
   V. Samkpanthamurthy was walking to the rice paddies near his home
in the village of Kakudha when he was gunned down by two men on a
motorcycle, the military said. Kakudha is about 135 miles east of
Colombo.
   The military blamed his killing on the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, the biggest and most militant Tamil group waging a nearly
6-year-old insurgency for a separate nation.
   Samkpanthamurthy, a leading member of the moderate Tamil United
Liberation Front, was chosen to take one of the 10 Parliament seats
won by the party during the Feb. 15 general election.
   The governing United National Party will control 125 of the 225
seats.
   In the capital, four men burst into the College House across from
Colombo University and fatally shot Professor Stanly Wijesundera,
police said.
   The 65-year-old professor of biochemistry had served as
vice-chancellor of the university for more than 11 years.
Wijesundera retired four months ago and had been working on a
research project, university officials said.
   Police blamed Sinhalese radicals for the killing.
   They said the professor's slaying may have been to protest plans
by President Ranasinghe Premadasa's government to reopen seven
universities that were closed over the last two years because of
student unrest.
   Government officials have said the unrest was fueled by militants
of the ethnic Sinhalese majority, who oppose government efforts to
grant minority Tamils greater autonomy.
   The only university currently operating is in the northern town
of Jaffna.
   The government earlier announced that the seven universities
would reopen on March 2, but postponed the date without giving any
reason.
   The students have been protesting the detention of colleagues who
had opposed an India-sponsored 1987 peace accord aimed at the Tamil
insurgency in the island's north and east provinces.
   Sinhalese radicals said the accord grants too many concessions to
the Tamils, who make up 18 percent of the country's 16 million
people.
   They say they are denied jobs, education and money for
development by the Sinhalese, who are predominantly Buddhist, make
up 75 percent of the population and control the government and
military.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, are a majority in the north and
east, and militant Tamils have been demanding an independent
homeland in those provinces.
</TEXT>
