<DOCNO> AP890308-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0633EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-BurlingtonMayor     03-08 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burlington Mayor,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Socialist Mayor's Party Wins Mayoral Contest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Contents in second to last graf may offend some readers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A close associate of four-term socialist
Mayor Bernard Sanders was elected to succeed him, and he promised to
carry on Sanders' ``fight for the rights of ordinary people.''
   Peter Clavelle, 39, Sanders' community development director,
easily defeated Aldermen President Nancy Chioffi, a Democrat, in
Tuesday's election.
   With all precincts reporting, Clavelle drew 5,626 votes, or 53
percent, to Chioffi's 4,400, or 42 percent.
   A ``tax revolt'' candidate and one from the environmentalist
Greens party split the rest of the vote.
   Sanders, the nation's only socialist mayor, had decided to teach
and write rather than serve another two-year term. Clavelle shies
away from the socialist label, but ran under the banner of Sanders'
third-party Progressive Coalition.
   ``What the people have said today is that Progressive government
is good government and they want more of it,'' Clavelle told about
150 supporters. He said he would continue to push most of Sanders'
platform, which includes affordable housing and public access to the
Lake Champlain waterfront.
   He said voters wanted an administration that would continue the
``fight for the rights of ordinary people. It's a fight for the
rights of tenants, it's a fight for housing for the homeless, it's a
fight for decent jobs for everyone in this economy.''
   Sanders, 47, said Clavelle's victory was proof that the
Progressive Coalition wasn't his ``one-man show. It's a movement.
That's what we accomplished tonight.''
   ``There is one city in America that has said we can go beyond
status quo politics, we can talk real issues to the people, we can
have a dream of a city and a state and country that is fundamentally
different than it is now,'' said Sanders, who ran unsuccessfully for
Congress last fall.
   Voters, however, didn't pass two referenda backed by the
coalition that would have set up new taxes to pay for a $1.25
million childcare program.
   Elsewhere around Vermont Tuesday was Town Meeting Day, and
residents braved sub-zero temperatures to travel to their town
halls, approve school budgets and socialize with friends and
neighbors not seen for a year.
   In more than 80 towns, residents voted on a non-binding
resolution asking the Legislature to reinstate the death penalty,
last used in the 1950s. At least 54 towns supported capital
punishment, but nearly 30 rejected or tabled it. One town that voted
down the resolution cited the recent film, ``The Thin Blue Line,''
which suggests that an innocent man faced the death penalty in Texas.
   Two years ago, about 30 towns took up the question, and
two-thirds voted for reinstatement.
   But most town meeting debates were over local issues. Residents
in the central Vermont town of Plainfield applauded their town road
crew, but residents in neighboring Marshfield lost patience when
people couldn't agree on whether to replace an old bridge.
   Pointing a crooked finger at a long-winded neighbor, Russell P.
Goslant said, ``Why keep arguing over a damn old bridge? ... Why
keep arguing over something that don't amount to nothing?''
   When Goslant spoke, at mid-afternoon, the town was averaging an
hour to debate each article on the 27-article warning.
</TEXT>
