<FIRST>r a PM-People-CuomoBasketball     03-08 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Cuomo Basketball,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuomo Wins Basketball Match Against Assemblyman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Known more for fast rhetoric than a fast
break, Gov. Mario Cuomo took off his tie, tied on his sneakers and
defeated Democratic Assemblyman Richard Brodsky in a 30-minute game
of one-on-one basketball.
   Tuesday's game, which Cuomo won 18-12, had symbolic import for
Brodsky, the only announced Democratic candidate in this year's
Westchester County Executive election. The Republican incumbent,
Andrew O'Rourke, challenged Cuomo and lost in the 1986 gubernatorial
race. Beating the guy who beat O'Rourke could have been a good omen
for his campaign.
   But Cuomo, a former minor-league baseball player and avid amateur
basketball player, maintained a lead throughout most of the game and
outpowered the smaller Brodsky in a game played before about 50
people at the State Police Academy gymnasium.
   ``It was a good fight,'' the 5-foot-8, 150-pound Brodsky puffed
after the game.
   The 5-foot-11-inch governor was unusually reticent, saying, ``He
had as many fouls as I had,'' before grabbing the ball and returning
to the court. Brodsky scored about half his points at the foul line.
   In a later game, the governor's team beat the state Assembly's
team, 67-63.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
