<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Arms     03-08 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Arms,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guns And Explosives Found Near Thatcher Conference Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police found guns and plastic explosives hidden in
a forest near a building where Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher is
to address a Conservative Party conference next week, authorities
said.
   The weapons were found near the northeast England village of
Scalby, about two miles from Scarborough, where the governing
Conservatives are to gather.
   Mrs. Thatcher survived an IRA bomb attack on Oct. 12, 1984 that
killed five people during the Conservatives' annual convention at
the coast resort of Brighton. The blast partly demolished the hotel
in which she was staying.
   North Yorkshire police, who are responsible for the Scarborough
area, said they saw no reason to recommend cancellation of the March
17-18 conference of the Conservatives' national council at
Scarborough's Spa Conference Center.
   The deputy chief constable of North Yorkshire, Frank Morritt,
told a news conference on Tuesday that he could not discount a link
between the arms cache and Mrs. Thatcher's planned visit to
Scarborough.
   Police said the cache of guns, ammunition and Czechoslovak-made
Semtex explosive was found Monday in a forest clearing beside a
road. It was unearthed by accident by a man gathering leaf mold for
his garden, police said.
   Police did not reveal how many weapons were found, but said the
amount of Semtex was substantial. The London newspaper The Daily
Telegraph said 25 pounds of the plastic explosive was found.
   Army bomb disposal experts say Semtex is frequently used in IRA
bombs.
   The British government has repeatedly accused Libyan leader Col.
Moammar Gadhafi of supplying the IRA with arms and Semtex in
retaliation for Mrs. Thatcher's backing of U.S. bombing raids
against Libya in April 1986.
   She gave permission for U.S. warplanes to fly from British bases
to take part in the attack.
   Gadhafi vowed unspecified revenge against Britain shortly after
the raids. He has frequently expressed support for the IRA, which is
fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA wants to unite predominantly
Protestant Northern Ireland with the Republic of Ireland.
   Morrit on Tuesday called on owners of hotels and guest houses in
the Scarborough area to tell police about any recent visitors who
had given cause for concern.
   Also Tuesday, masked gunmen killed three men at a village gas
station in the Northern Ireland town of Coagh, 50 miles west of
Belfast.
   The Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility in a statement
to the local news media and said the service station was a
stronghold of the Ulster Volunteer Force, a Protestant paramilitary
group that also is banned.
   Police said the three men slain in Coagh, who were chatting when
the gunment drove up and opened fire, had no connection with
Northern Ireland's security forces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
