<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Ashlock     03-08 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Ashlock,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Girl Who Received Friend's Heart Dies Waiting For Another One</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors who treated transplant patient Donna
Ashlock, whose story touched millions after she received the heart
of a boy who had a crush on her, were stunned by her death.
   Donna was three weeks from her 18th birthday and was waiting for
a second transplant when she died Tuesday at her home in Patterson.
   Donna, who recently said she wanted to become a nurse, died
during a midday nap, according to San Francisco's Pacific
Presbyterian Medical Center.
   She had received the heart of 15-year-old Felipe Garza Jr. three
years ago at the medical center.
   Although the transplant initially was a success, her body last
year began to reject Felipe's heart, which he willed to his ailing
friend before a blood vessel in his brain burst and he died suddenly.
   Dr. Andrew Fryer, her pediatric cardiologist, said she was in
``pretty good shape'' when doctors examined her last week.
   ``She was a wonderful little girl and her death shocks and
saddens us all,'' Fryer told reporters. ``We truly admired her
resiliency and ability to cope with things that young girls
shouldn't have to cope with.''
   Dr. Michael Schorr, her family physician, and others praised her
cheerfulness, courage and attempts to live the life of a normal
teen-ager during her nearly four-year battle for life.
   ``She had been through a lot of stress and discomfort, physically
and emotionally. She really kept her spirits up remarkably well,''
Schorr said.
   Although there was no official determination of the cause of
death, doctors suspected cardiac arrythmia, the irregular beating of
the heart, a problem often found in transplant patients.
   Her chances would have been excellent with another transplant,
Fryer said.
   Donna's parents declined to talk with reporters.
   Their daughter was thrust into the limelight when it was reported
that Felipe, who once had a crush on his high school classmate, told
his parents he wanted to leave the ailing 14-year-old girl his heart
after his death.
   ``I'm going to die and I'm going to give my heart to my
girlfriend,'' Felipe told his mother in December 1985.
   Felipe, the son of farm laborers, had been suffering from
blackouts and headaches when he talked about donating his heart to
Donna. He died suddenly on Jan. 4, 1986. Donna, whose own heart had
been critically damaged by a virus, received his heart the next day.
   ``I hope that what Peno (Felipe) did shows how people can help
each other,'' Donna said 12 days after the transplant.
   Donna became an instant celebrity. She was featured in People
magazine, visited with President Reagan and accepted an invitation
from rock star Michael Jackson to visit him in his home near Los
Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
