<FIRST>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0825 03-08 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0825,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Run for Your Wife!,' A British Farce, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS three grafs with other reviews; No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Run for Your Wife!'' gives American
theatergoers a chance to see an authentic production of a British
sex farce without having to cross the Atlantic.
   Whether they would want to is another question entirely. The
play, which opened Tuesday at Broadway's Virginia Theater, is full
of leers, lunges and lame sex jokes. It could bring back celibacy.
   ``Run for Your Wife!'' stars Ray Cooney, who also wrote and
directed. He strikes out on all three counts. In London's West End,
Cooney is sort of a one-man play industry. His other successful
efforts there include such supposedly spicy concoctions as ``Not
Now, Darling,'' ``Move Over, Mrs. Markham,'' ``Why Not Stay for
Breakfast?'' and ``Two Into One.'' The titles are better than the
plays.
   The plot of ``Run for Your Wife!'' spins out of control early.
John Smith, played by Cooney, is a London taxi cab driver. He has
one wife, Mary, in Wimbledon, and another, Barbara, in Streatham.
Both of their tacky apartments, by set supervisor Michael Anania,
are on stage simultaneously. You can tell them apart because one is
blue, the other yellow. His wives are color-coded to match the
apartments. One wears blue, the other yellow. That's the extent of
their characterizations.
   When Smith saves a little old lady from a mugging and gets beaten
up, his twin living arrangements unravel. Most of the evening is
spent trying to prevent one wife from finding out about the other.
   With one glorious exception, the acting is cardboard _ flat and
gray. Only Paxton Whitehead, as a well-meaning but bumbling
neighbor, manages to rise above the drivel. He actually seems to
believe what he is saying. That's no small accomplishment
considering Cooney's inane dialogue.
   The second act trades boring for offensive. It bashes homosexuals
with some crude jokes, primarily focused on one limp-wristed
character who wears a lavender jumpsuit in case you can't figure out
his sexual preference.
   The play has none of the style or wit of ``Lend Me a Tenor,''
another farce which arrived last week. In fact, it makes that
harmless trifle seem like Noel Coward.
   ```Run for Your Wife!'' is one of London's biggest hits. It has
clocked more than 2,500 performances and shows no sign of slowing
down. In New York, it should expire quickly.
   In other reviews, Mel Gussow wrote in The New York Times:
``Accepting the ground rules for allowable contrivances in farce,
the play is still burdened with blind alleys, limp jokes, forced
puns and troubled entendres.''
   ```Run For Your Wife' is what is known in the trade as an
Audience Show,'' wrote Howard Kissel in the Daily News. ``What this
means is that it is so witless and inane that no self-respecting
critic can possibly endorse it, but audiences enjoy it
tremendously.''
   ``The premises of the joke are ramshackle, its convolutions
arbitrary and its conclusion quite remarkably inconclusive,'' wrote
Clive Barnes in the New York Post. ``The results are shabby, with
the actors busting a gut for laughs, rather like a TV sitcom going
down for the third time without a script.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0641EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSSettlement     03-08 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Settlement,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer: Award Sets Record For AIDS Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who said he contracted AIDS from blood
products during heart surgery in 1985 will collect the largest
settlement for anyone who has contracted the deadly syndrome, his
attorney said.
   Attorney Robert L. Habush said Monday that his client, John
Carroll, avoided an appeals battle over a $3.9 million jury award
because of the settlement.
   The amount was not disclosed, but Habush said it was ``very
favorable and still very much a record in dollars in AIDS cases.''
   The largest previous award is believed to be $1.6 millon for an
Atlanta man who contracted AIDS from a blood product that promotes
clotting. That verdict was later overturned on grounds the evidence
was insufficient to prove negligence by the laboratory that provided
the product.
   A San Francisco jury in December awarded $750,000 to the family
of a 5-year-old who contracted the virus from blood he received
during a heart operation in 1983.
   And in February a California jury awarded Rock Hudson's lover,
Marc Christian, $21.75 million because Hudson failed to tell him he
had AIDS. The case increased the responsibility of AIDS sufferers to
tell sexual companions of their plight.
   Carroll wanted his case resolved quickly so that he could decide
how the money would be used, including what charities he would
support, before he died. The 63-year-old man testified during the
trial that he expected to live no more than one year.
   A Circuit Court jury had awarded the suburban Brookfield man $3.9
million in damages in December, but attorneys said appeals could
have taken years.
   The man had filed suit against the Blood Center of Southeastern
Wisconsin, which provided blood products used during his operation.
   John Dawson, the blood center's lawyer, said the case was settled
to both sides' satisfaction.
   ``The blood center remains confident that it was not negligent
and that there was no liability in this case at all,'' he said.
   The plaintiff argued the center was negligent for distributing
blood products that weren't tested for the AIDS virus even though it
had tested products on hand.
   The blood center's attorneys said that, at the time, they could
not be sure of the reliability of AIDS tests and were reluctant to
replace untested blood with tested blood.
   The plaintiff received the blood April 23, 1985, six weeks after
the blood center began testing blood for the AIDS virus.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, breaks down the
body's immune system and leaves the victim open to outbreaks of
other diseases. No cure is known. It is spread through sexual
contact, transfusions of blood and blood products, and the sharing
of contamined hypodermic needles or syringes by drug abusers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
