<FIRST>r a PM-PolkAwards     03-08 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polk Awards,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>1989 Polk Awards In Journalism Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two reporters for The New York Times and the
former editor of The New Yorker are among the winners of the 1989
George Polk Awards in Journalism.
   The awards, decided by a jury of Long Island University faculty
members and alumni, were announced Tuesday.
   The Times' John Kifner won in the foreign reporting category for
his coverage of the Palestinian uprising. Kifner, now on the Times'
metropolitan staff, also won in the foreign reporting category in
1980.
   Keith Schneider, a reporter in the Times' Washington bureau, won
the national reporting award for articles about safety problems with
the government's nuclear weapons production system.
   William Shawn, former editor of The New Yorker magazine, was
awarded the George Polk Career Award in Journalism for excellence in
his 35 years of presiding over the magazine.
   Long Island University established the awards in 1949, the year
after CBS correspondent George Polk was killed while covering the
Greek civil war.
   Other awards went to:
   _ Local Reporting: David Gomez and Patricia Guthrie of The
Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune for a six-part series on official failure
to deal with alcoholism in Gallup, N.M.
   _ Economic Reporting: Donald L. Barlett and James B. Steele of
The Philadelphia Inquirer for stories resulting from a 15-month
investigation into loopholes in the Tax Reform Act of 1986.
   _ Environmental Reporting: Mary Bishop of the Roanoke Times and
World-News for a four-part series on Virginia's unlicensed pesticide
industry.
   _ Financial Reporting: National Thrift News for coverage of the
savings and loan industry.
   _ Network Television Reporting: Brian Ross, correspondent, and
Ira Silverman, producer, NBC News, for reports on banks that launder
cash for drug dealers.
   _ Local Television Reporting: KING-TV, Seattle, for a series of
reports on race relations there in the 20 years since the death of
the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
   _ Radio Reporting: Patricia Neighmond of National Public Radio
for a two-year series on a person with AIDS.
   _ Cultural Reporting: Lawrence Wechsler for ``Shapinsky's Karma,
Boggs's Bills,'' published by North Point Press, San Francisco,
essays about the relationship between the arts and economics.
   _ Photojournalism: Mary Ellen Mark for photographs that appeared
in Life, Texas Monthly and ``Streetwise,'' a collection of still
photographs on the life of street children in Seattle.
   The awards will be presented at a luncheon at the Roosevelt Hotel
on April 12.
</TEXT>
