<FIRST>r a PM-BirchSociety     03-08 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Birch Society,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative Group Moving To Sen. McCarthy's Hometown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>APPLETON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The John Birch Society plans to move its
headquarters to this northeastern Wisconsin town, but Mayor Dorothy
Johnson said she doubts it will give the community an image problem.
   Appleton already is known for its links to the late Sen. Joseph
McCarthy _ annual memorial services are held at his gravesite in
town and a large bust of him is in the Outagamie County Courthouse.
The town also holds the annual Harry Houdini seance, in honor of the
famed magician who grew up in town.
   ``That says our city has a variety of ideas, and isn't it
wonderful we can permit within our social network the whole range of
ideas,'' Ms. Johnson said.
   The conservative organization will close its headquarters in
Belmont, Mass., and San Marino, Calif., and consolidate operations
in Appleton beginning in July, the group said in the March issue of
the John Birch Society Bulletin.
   ``It's a real opportunity here in terms of potential growth and
the economic impact of it all,'' said G. Allen Bubolz, an Appleton
insurance executive who became the society's chief executive officer
in November.
   The headquarters will start with a staff of 27 people and a
payroll of roughly $1 million, Bubolz said.
   The society said Appleton also was nearer the geographical center
of the United States and noted its connections to McCarthy, the
Republican senator who chaired hearings into alleged communist
activities in the United States in the 1950s. McCarthy, who was
later censured by his colleagues, was born in nearby Grand Chute.
   The society is a conservative political organization that
emphasizes fighting the spread of communism and reducing the size of
U.S. government. It claims more than 10,000 members.
   City Attorney Greg Carman didn't share the mayor's views, saying
the move was unfortunate for the community. But he said he would not
advocate any attempt to prevent it.
   Carman said he feared that the McCarthy bust, the annual services
for McCarthy and the Birch Society would present a false image of
the people of Appleton.
</TEXT>
