<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0653EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     03-08 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Closes Proposed Settlement, Evicts Settlers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BET ARYE, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army shut down an illegal
Jewish settlement today, turning out a small group of Israelis who
pitched a tent on the hilltop site in an attempt to launch a new
community.
   The bid to create another Jewish enclave in the West Bank
followed a rally attended by 10,000 people in Tel Aviv whose
organizers called for the founding of eight such settlements.
   Elswhere in the occupied lands today, Palestinians staged a
general strike to mark the 15-month anniversary of their uprising.
   Seven Arabs were shot and wounded during clashes with troops in
the Gaza Strip, Arab hospital officials said. The army said it was
checking the reports.
   Palestinian women staged pro-PLO demonstrations in the West Bank
town of Beit Jalla and in Gaza City to mark International Women's
Day.
   The latest leaflet issued by underground leaders of the uprising
against Israel's 21-year occupation praised women for their ``heroic
role ... in the liberation war.''
   In east Jerusalem, police imposed a curfew on the Arab Isawiye
section and rounded up men suspected of involvement in recent
protests, police said. At least 15 Palestinians were arrested,
Israel radio said.
   After Tuesday night's rally in Tel Aviv, a group of would-be
settlers set out for the site of a proposed settlement called
Ofarim. The site is about 15 miles east of Tel Aviv on land occupied
by Israel since it was captured from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East
war.
   The government's coalition agreement calls for setting up eight
settlements, but final approval has not been granted.
   The Finance Ministry, controlled by the left-center Labor Party,
says the country cannot afford the new settlements.
   Two army jeeps blocked the entrance to the Ofarim site this
morning.
   A Defense Ministry official who demanded anonymity said eight
activists from the right-wing Betar youth movement had set up a tent
at the site during the night but later left at the order of soldiers.
   ``It was a symbolic takeover of the land. When the army came,
they left voluntarily,'' said Yaakov Narodetsky, general secretary
of Bet Aryeh, a settlement about one mile from the Ofarim site.
   Other hopeful settlers last night drove three large mobile homes
out to another Jewish community, Beit Horon, and said they planned
to move out to the proposed new settlement of Talmon later in the
week.
   More than 70,000 Jewish settlers coexist uneasily with 1.7
million Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip,
maintaining more than 130 settlements. Many are dedicated to
continuing Israel's control of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Settlers have called for moving even more Jews out to the
territories to strengthen Israel's hold on the land.
   Elyakim Haetzni, an activist in the settlement movement, said on
Israel's state-run radio station this morning that the settlers
would oppose any peace settlement that called for Israel's
withdrawal from the territories.
   ``The state of Israel cannot turn Jews out of the state of
Israel,'' Haetzni said.
   Palestinians throughout the occupied territories began a general
strike to mark the 15th month of the revolt that began Dec. 8, 1987.
At least 391 Palestinians and 17 Israelis have been killed in the
uprising.
</TEXT>
