<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Refuseniks     03-08 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Refuseniks,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Women Begin Hunger Strikes to Protest Emigration Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 50 Jewish women across the Soviet Union
began a three-day hunger strike today to protest what they say are
arbitrary policies that bar their emigration, a participant said.
   It is the third year in a row that Jewish Women Against Refusal,
whose members have been denied exit visas, have held a hunger strike
beginning on International Women's Day, a Soviet holiday celebrated
on March 8.
   ``These three hunger strikes have all been during the years of
perestroika. Everyone talks a lot about all the changes due to
perestroika, but the situation in emigration is still the same,''
said hunger strike organizer Inna Ioffe, who first applied for an
exit visa 10 years ago. Perestroika is what President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev calls his reform program.
   The women are protesting Soviet emigration procedures and calling
on Soviet leaders to set up a judicial system to review their cases.
   About half of the 46 women participating in the hunger strike
have been refused emigration for reasons of state secrecy, Ioffe
said. Soviet authorities have told them they cannot leave because
they or their relatives have knowledge of state secrets, she said.
   The other half have been denied emigration because their parents
or divorced spouses have failed to certify that they have no
financial claims on the would-be emigrants, she said.
   Women in Moscow, Leningrad, Kiev, Minsk, Vilnius, Irkutsk and
other cities were participating in the hunger strike, Ioffe said.
   ``We have no laws to lean on, and we are never given reasonable
reasons for the refusals,'' she said.
   Ioffe said she has been told she cannot emigrate because her
76-year-old mother-in-law, who also wants to emigrate, was exposed
to state secrets in her work as a botanist.
   More than 20,000 Soviet Jews were allowed permission to emigrate
in 1988.
   Yuri Semenovsky, who has sought in vain for three years to obtain
a Soviet exit visa, said at a recent Moscow demonstration of the
so-called Jewish refuseniks that 80,000 others have had applications
refused.
   The majority of the women who participated in the 1988 and 1987
hunger strikes have now emigrated, said Ioffe, who also took part in
those hunger strikes.
</TEXT>
