<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0721EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-AIDS     03-08 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-AIDS,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Izvestia Says Soviet AIDS Cases Rising Fast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS is spreading at an alarming rate in the Soviet
Union, with the number of infected or ill people forecast to
increase nearly tenfold next year, the government daily Izvestia
says.
   The newspaper quoted the health minister, Yevgeny Chazov, as
saying AIDS now poses no less a danger to the Soviet Union than
nuclear weapons.
   ``The alarming situation with AIDS demands rapid and decisive
measures,'' Izvestia said Tuesday night in the latest of a series of
reports in the Soviet press expressing growing concern about the
deadly disease.
   The Soviets once claimed acquired immune deficiency syndrome was
strictly a Western problem caused by decadent capitalist sexual
mores and drug use. Homosexuals and intravenous drug users are two
of the groups at greatest risk.
   Soviet papers once even claimed AIDS was the result of a Pentagon
experiment in biological warfare.
   Soviet scientists since have debunked such claims, saying their
country needs to mobilize more resources to fight the spread of the
disease, which saps the body's natural defenses and leaves it open
to onslaught by other ailments.
   According to Izvestia, however, the AIDS virus is spreading at an
alarming rate among Soviets.
   In 1988, the paper said, 81 people in the Soviet Union were
carriers of the AIDS virus. By Feb. 1, it said, 44 more cases were
known and now the total number of people infected with the virus is
more than 140.
   ``It's expected that next year, there will be 1,342 sick
people,'' Izvestia said, apparently referring to carriers of the
virus, rather than people actually suffering symptoms.
   Of four Soviets actually suffering AIDS symptoms, three have died
to date, Izvestia said.
   The government newspaper, reporting on a meeting of a special
Soviet commission created to fight epidemics, quoted Chazov as
saying warnings to the Kremlin that AIDS could become a national
calamity had been ignored.
   ``The threat that we face is no less than the ecological `bomb'
or nuclear weapons,'' Izvestia quoted Chazov as saying.
   ``He also stated that workers of the U.S.S.R. Ministry of Health
on numerous occasions tried to inform the government that the
situation was menacing. But noted scientists dealing with the
problem eliminated the acuteness of the question, saying it was all
a false alarm.''
   The United States had 86,157 AIDS victims as of last month,
according to the World Health Organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
