<DOCNO> AP890308-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-TempletonPrize 1stLd-Writethru a0490 03-08 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Templeton Prize, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0490,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scot And German Named Co-Winners Of Top Religion Prize</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS to MacLeod throughout, CORRECTS to Mother Teresa sted
Theresa; Embargoed until at 11 a.m. EST, time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. George MacLeod, an innovative Scottish
churchman, and West German physicist Carl Freidrich von Weizsaecker
today were named winners of the 1989 Templeton Prize for Progress in
Religion.
   The prize, amounting this year to $435,000, is the world's
biggest and is deliberately kept larger than Nobel prizes in the
sciences and literature.
   This is the first time in the award's 16 years that it has been
divided between two winners, a result of rankings by an
international panel of judges, a spokesman said.
   MacLeod, 92, of Edinburgh, was chosen for his founding of the
famed Iona Community, an ecumenical center of prayer, peacemaking
and work that has influenced church life in many countries.
   Weizsaecker, 76, of Munich, was named for initiating dialogue
between the disciplines of science and religion and for research
into links between physics, cosmology and theology.
   MacLeod said in a statement he would use half of the money for
direct action against hunger and the other half for work for peace.
   Weizsaecker, a Protestant layman and the brother of West German
President Richard von Weizsaecker, said his share would go to
deepening relationships between science and faith.
   The winners were announced at a news conference at the Church
Center for the United Nations by John Templeton, American investment
counselor and financier, who founded the prize in 1972.
   He said its purpose is to encourage inter-religious understanding
and to help ``people in all nations to grow spiritually in their
love of God and understanding of God.''
   Previous winners have included the Roman Catholic nun Mother
Teresa of Calcutta, India; U.S. evangelist Billy Graham and the
Russian-expatriate writer Alexander Solzhenitsyn.
   Weizsaecker is the second scientist to win the prize. The Rev.
Stanley L. Jaki, an astrophysicist at Seton Hall University in New
Jersey, won two years ago.
   Choice of last year's winner, Inamullah Khan of Pakistan,
secretary-general of the World Moslem Congress, was temporarily
delayed after some Jewish leaders alleged he had links to
anti-Semitism.
   But the award subsequently was made after an inquiry found the
criticisms unjustified.
   The nine judges for the competition this year included former
U.S. Treasury Secretary William Simon, Roman Catholic Archishop Mark
McGrath of Panama, and British Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe.
   MacLeod, a Church of Scotland clergyman, left a wealthy parish to
minister to shipbuilding workers and their families in Glasgow. In
1938, he founded the ecumenical community on the isle of Iona off
Scotland's west coast.
   With its simple monastic-style commitment to a fivefold rule of
daily prayer and Scripture study, tithing, peacemaking, and
responsible work, the community has drawn interest of Christians
around the world.
   About 100,000 visit there annually to experience its methods
first-hand as a model for religious renewal, peace and Christian
unity.
   MacLeod, who had become a pacifist after witnessing the slaughter
of World War I as a military captain, also founded an early peace
organization, the Fellowship of Reconciliation, which now has
branches in most countries.
   He stepped down in 1967 as leader of the Iona Community, which
has about 200 resident members and thousands of supporter elsewhere.
Elevated to the British House of Lords, he continues a broad
schedule of teaching.
   Weizsaecker was cited as pioneering ``the development of the
inter-relationships of physics, cosmology and theology'' and laying
``the groundwork for the renewal of faith.''
   An astrophysicist, his research into cosmology led him after
World War II to initiate conversations between scientists and
theologians, originally in 1949 at the University of Gottingen in
Germany, and later elsewhere.
   Such conversations spread to other countries in Europe and
America, resulting in an international conference in 1978 on science
and faith sponsored by the World Council of Churches at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
   Weizsaecker, who has written about 40 books on physics,
astronomy, cosmology and religion, has taught at universities of
Berlin, Stasbourg, Gottingen, Hamburg and Munich.
   He recently retired as director of the Max Planck Institute in
Starnberg, a position he held since 1970.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
