<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0858EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-USLawyer     03-08 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-US Lawyer,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Spectators Can Take Notes in American's Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court ruled today that spectators may
take notes during most trials, and an American lawyer who brought
the case said the decision would help open the Japanese legal system
to needed reform.
   Until today's ruling, only reporters for major newspapers and
radio and television stations were allowed to take notes during most
trials.
   The decision came in a case brought by Lawrence Repeta, a Seattle
attorney denied permission to take notes at a tax trial in 1983-84.
Although it ruled in his favor, the court said Repeta's inability to
take notes during the trial was not serious enough to warrant paying
the $10,000 damages he demanded.
   While attending the tax trial as part of research for a book on
Japanese law, Repeta, 38, was repeatedly refused permission to take
notes. With support from the Japanese Civil Liberties Union, he
lodged a complaint, which was rejected by Tokyo District Court and
Tokyo High Court.
   ``As of today, anyone can go into any courtroom in Japan and will
be allowed to take notes,'' Repeta said today.
   ``In a democracy, people have to have free access to the courts,
or they can't be satisfied that the criminal process is being used
fairly.''
   Repeta told reporters there were ``very serious violations of
fundamental human rights principles'' in Japanese criminal trials,
including the holding of suspects for long periods without bail and
without access to a lawyer. In the tax case, Repeta observed, the
defendant was held for 2{ years without bail.
   ``The best remedy for such problems is public knowledge of what
goes on in the courtroom,'' he said.
   In a rare appearance by a foreigner before the Supreme Court,
Repeta told the judges in a January hearing that Japan now has a
responsibility to set an international legal example.
   ``The world looks to Japan to take a leadership role, not only in
economics but also in the cultural and political fields,'' he said.
   About 30 Japanese supported Repeta in the case, including
lawyers, reporters and writers.
   His Japanese lawyer, Yoichi Kitamura, said it took an American to
bring the case ``because Japanese are accustomed to the fact that
spectators are not allowed to take notes.''
   In Japan's controversial ``press club'' system, most government
agencies maintain semi-official press clubs that generally exclude
reporters from small newspapers and magazines, and foreign
correspondents.
   Until today's ruling, only members of judiciary press clubs were
allowed to take notes during most trials. Members of press clubs
still do not have access to court documents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0910EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Tibet 4thLd-Writethru a0491 03-08 0818</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tibet, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0491,0840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Seal Off Tibetan Capital, Order Foreigners Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to with Dalai Lama spokesman proposing talks.
Pickup 12th pvs, ``Troops were...'' DELETES last 2 grafs to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHENGDU, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police dragged people from their homes in
Lhasa, the Tibetan capital, today as troops converged on the city to
enforce martial law after three days of anti-Chinese rioting,
witnesses said.
   Foreigners were given a day to leave the remote southern city.
   An Australian traveler told of security forces in Lhasa pulling
Tibetans out of their homes: ``One or two people were screaming
really frantically as they were being taken away into a truck.
   ``The truck kept coming back,'' he said. ``They would pick up a
couple people, drive off with a half dozen militia holding them
down, then come back.''
   The Australian, speaking by telephone, said he saw police leading
away another group of 12 to 14 youths, some of whom looked as young
as nine.
   An American tourist said thousands of soldiers occupied the old
section of the city, where Tibetans protesting Chinese rule began
rioting Sunday, stoning police and building bonfires of goods looted
from Chinese-owned stores.
   Official reports have put the death toll in the violence at 12,
although Tibetans say far more have been killed, most shot to death
by security frces.
   At midnight Tuesday, trucks with loudspeakers began announcing
the city was under martial law and that Tibetans should stay indoors.
   Dozens of trucks packed with soldiers later entered the city.
   Chinese authorities said the entire city would be ``cordoned
off.'' Anyone ``who defies martial law or instigates others to do so
will be severely punished,'' the official Xinhua News Agency
reported.
   It was the first time China has publicly imposed martial law
anywhere since the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution. It marked an
escalation in the battle with Tibetan protesters, who demand freedom
from China and the return of their spiritual leader, the Dalai Lama,
who fled to exile in India after a filed uprising 30 years ago.
   In New Delhi, the Dalai Lama's government-in-exile today offered
to hold talks in Geneva with Chinese authorities to discuss Tibet's
future.
   ``Despite the current tragic events, we are still ready to hold
talks with the Chinese so that a peaceful solution can be found,''
said Tashi Wongdi, the Tibetan leader's chief representative in New
Delhi.
   The two sides have agreed to meet to discuss the Tibetan
situation but have been unable to agree on a location. China also
refuses to discuss the Dalai Lama's proposal for greater autonomy
for Tibet.
   Troops were not deployed in three previous outbreaks of violence
over the past 18 months that claimed the lives of about 40 Tibetans
and police.
   One American said that after martial law was declared, ``The
Tibetans who'd been marching around were still angry. They felt
frustrated. Others were scared. I saw grown men bursting into
tears.''
   Doje Cering, head of the Tibet Autonomous Government, was quoted
on national radio today as saying separatists had taken China's
restrained stance toward past demonstrations as a sign of weakness.
   ``Now is the time for a radical solution. If we don't adopt that
now, it will seriously influence our social stability.''
   Travelers said police entered one hotel at 2:30 a.m. and another
an hour later and announced that all foreigners must leave Lhasa by
noon Thursday. About 80 foreigners were believed to be in the city.
   ``It's basically a choice between heading for the Nepal border
and flying to Chengdu,'' the provincial capital of Sichuan, one
traveler said. ``But they won't let us out to go to the bank or
prepare.''
   One American traveler said most of the Tibetans wounded in the
clashes have been hiding in their homes. ``It's presumed that
anybody who got shot must be guilty,'' he said.
   Foreigners said security forces were checking identifications of
both the few Tibetans and Chinese out on the streets. There were no
reports of demonstrations or gunfire today.
   All foreigners spoke on condition of anonymity for fear of
reprisal.
   Three Swedes who took photographs of Sunday's initial clash in
the central square were given back their cameras and passports
Tuesday after paying fines of about $54 each. An American who took
more pictures was fined the equivalent of $135, a fellow American
said.
   However, one Swiss who refused to turn over his film Sunday said
police beat him and pointed a gun at his head. He said police still
have his camera and passport and say they will not return them until
he hands over the film and pays a fine. He said he was not injured.
   China has not said how long martial law will be in effect,
although it is certain to last through Friday, the 30th anniversary
of a failed uprising in 1959 that led to the Dalai Lama's exile.
</TEXT>
