<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou plans to sue
Time magazine for printing the comments of a Greek banker who
accused Papandreou of involvement in a banking scandal, the
government said today.
   The announcement made over state-run radio and television did not
say when Papandreou would file suit against the New York-based
magazine.
   Papandreou described as ``despicable'' the interview with
banker-publisher George Koskotas, the central figure in the scandal.
   A spokesman for Time said today the magazine tried to interview
Papandreou before publishing the article.
   ``We remain interested in the prime minister's response to Mr.
Koskotas' allegations. We hope that these matters will be fully and
promptly aired in a public forum rather than a court of law,'' said
Robert Marshall of Time's legal department.
   Opposition parties, meanwhile, continued to demand Papandreou's
resignation. The Greek Communist Party said general elections should
be held as soon as possible. It called for mass nationwide rallies
next Wednesday to protest the scandals.
   The governing Panhellenic Socialist Movement's second four-year
term in office ends in June.
   Koskotas, former chairman of the Bank of Crete, has been accused
of siphoning off $200 million of the bank's funds. He fled Greece in
November and ended up in the United States, where he is being held
in a Salem, Mass., jail pending the outcome of a Greek request for
extradition.
   The Time interview quoted the 34-year-old Koskotas as saying
Papandreou and several leading members of his government allegedly
authorized a plan to embezzle millions of dollars from the bank.
   Government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos made it clear that
Papandreou and his government had no intention of stepping down.
   ``His opponents who never have been and never will be able to
defeat him in elections, dream of his resignation,'' said
Kostopoulos.
   He repeated charges that the Koskotas scandal was part of a
series of ``orchestrated attacks against Papandreou by local and
foreign centers of destabilization'' which were aimed at subverting
what he described as the popular progressive movement in Greece.
</TEXT>
