<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-March     03-08 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-March,0461</SECOND>
<BYLINE>5,000 Students March Legally in Warsaw; 3,000 Rally in Southern
Poland ^By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 young people marched
peacefully today to mark the anniversary of 1968 police beatings of
students and to celebrate a government promise to legalize a banned
student group.
   About 3,000 students at Jagiellonian University in the southern
city of Krakow also rallied to support the group, the Independent
Students Association.
   Those students, heeding an appeal from the university rector, did
not leave campus and risk a confrontation with police. In February,
a series of marches in Krakow resulted in stone-throwing clashes
with police.
   In an unusual move Tuesday, Warsaw officials granted permission
for the march in their city. The decision coincided with an
agreement at negotiations between Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and
government officials to restore legal status to the student
association. Like Solidarity, the student group was banned following
the December 1981 martial-law crackdown.
   The Warsaw march started when about 1,000 people walked two miles
from the Warsaw Polytechnic Institute to Warsaw University, where
they joined about 4,000 students and professors for a rally.
   Police halted traffic for the march, led by a woman pushing twins
in a baby carriage. The marchers chanted ``No success without NZS,''
the initials in Polish for the student group.
   After a wreath-laying ceremony at a campus plaque marking the
1968 events, the participants walked a few blocks off campus to a
monument honoring the 19th century Polish epic poet and patriot Adam
Mickiewicz.
   Police and plainclothes Communist Party worker activists beat
students on March 8, 1968, following student protests against the
closure of a performance of Mickiewicz's patriotic play
``Grandfathers.''
   ``The March events, looked upon from a perspective of 21 years,
make us aware of a certain great truth _ how pitifully ineffective
are the efforts of all those who stand against the natural and
inborn wish for freedom,'' Warsaw University rector Grzegorz
Bialkowski told the students.
   He told students to think about the history of the country and
consider how the 1968 events contributed to current reform efforts
in Poland.
   Many of the students expelled for taking part in the 1968 protest
became leaders of the Solidarity trade union movement, which began
in 1980.
   One, Adam Michnik, now a leading opposition theoretician and
adviser to Walesa, was welcomed to the rally at Krakow's
Jagiellonian University by rector Aleksander Koj, the chief academic
officer.
   ``It's a moving day for me. What happened 21 years ago changed my
generation and my life,'' Michnik said.
   He said students in 1968 protested because, ``We did not agree
that Poland should become a country where people were stripped of
their humanity.''
</TEXT>
