<HEAD>Reporter Arrested While Covering Murder Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter for the country's
largest newspaper was detained in a courtroom today for allegedly
stealing photographs of a prostitute who is the key state witness in
a murder trial.
   Police said the call girl, Pat du Preez, had complained that
pictures of her were taken from her home without permission. Two
photographs of her were published over the weekend by the Sunday
Times.
   Janine Lazarus, a Sunday Times reporter, was sitting in
Johannesburg Supreme Court waiting for the murder trial to resume
when a plainclothes officer served her with an arrest warrant based
on Ms. du Preez's complaint.
   Ms. Lazarus was asked to accompany a police officer out of the
courthouse. After consultations involving her, the police, an editor
and a newspaper lawyer, she was allowed to remain free pending
possible further proceedings in the case. No date was set for such
proceedings.
   Ms. du Preez testified last week against Maria Krebs, 35, who is
accused of murdering her husband, Ralf Krebs, after telephoning an
escort agency and asking Ms. du Preez to come to their home for a
three-way sex session.
   Mrs. Krebs acknowledges having brandished a gun during a scuffle
that ensued but says her husband was killed by a shot that was fired
accidentally.
   The trial has been front-page news in many South African
newspapers for the past two weeks. The prosecution completed its
arguments today.
   Photographs of Mrs. Krebs, usually smiling and elegantly dressed,
have appeared almost daily in the press, while Ms. du Preez has
shielded her face from photographers.
</TEXT>
