<FIRST>r i PM-Arafat     03-08 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arafat,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Chief Lays Cornerstone for Palestinian Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chairman Yasser Arafat today laid
the cornerstone of a Palestinian Embassy in Pakistan's capital.
   Pakistan was the first country to recognize the independent state
declared in November by the Palestine National Council, the PLO's
parliament-in-exile.
   ``We know for freedom there is a very high price,'' said Arafat.
``As you have paid for your freedom, we will continue to pay for
ours,'' he told Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto.
   More than 100 foreign diplomats and dignitaries, many from Middle
East and East bloc countries, attended the ceremony.
   The PNC said Jerusalem would be the Palestinian state's capital,
but it did not specify the state's boundaries.
   A 21-gun salute and a flyover, by six U.S.-made F-16 jet
fighters, greeted the PLO chairman upon his arrival in Islamabad.
   Arafat earlier made a brief stop in Ms. Bhutto's hometown of
Larkana and laid a floral wreath at the grave of her father,
Zulfikar Ali Bhutto.
   The elder Bhutto was overthrown by army Gen. Mohammad Zia-ul Haq
in a 1977 coup and hanged two years later. Zia died in August when
his aircraft crashed. His death paved the way for the first free
elections in more than a decade, which brought Ms. Bhutto to power.
   ``He (Bhutto) is following in spirit this celebration,'' said
Arafat, who was a friend of Bhutto's.
   The PLO chief was expected to meet President Ghulam Ishaq Khan
and Afghan guerrilla leaders before going to India on Thursday.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization's consul general, Ahmed
Alhih, said Arafat hoped to play an ``important role'' in solving
the Afghan problem.
   Moslem guerrillas have battled Afghanistan's communist government
for a decade and have vowed to overthrow it. Last month in Pakistan,
guerrilla leaders declared a government-in-exile, basing the move on
presumptions the Afghan government will fall and the guerrillas will
take power.
   Alhih said the PLO chief is not expected to give the Afghan
guerrilla government recognition. The PLO is allied with Moscow and
New Delhi, while the Afghan guerrillas are supported by the United
States and Pakistan.
</TEXT>
