<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   03-08 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: justifiable wrath.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 6
   The Seattle Times on drug-treatment rules:
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome has broken all the rules, and
society is slowly reacting to the epidemic.
   The latest change is a recommendation from two federal health
agencies to make methadone, a synthetic narcotic, more readily
available to heroin addicts seeking treatment.
   The goal is to fight the spread of AIDS through needle sharing by
intravenous drug abusers.
   In less than a decade, this fatal disease has claimed 49,976
lives, and has been diagnosed in 39,000 more people. After a halting
start the medical community is in hot pursuit of vaccines, but the
disease has proven an elusive target. ...
   Weaning addicts from needles with methadone or reducing the reuse
of needles by distributing clean needles takes a change of attitude
for ... professionals, lawmakers and citizens.
   As the human and financial toll of the AIDS epidemic mounts,
society will be reassessing many old values.
   These early public health adjustments may seem quaint.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 3
   The Westerly (R.I.) Sun on equipping new buses with wheelchair
lifts:
   Public transit officials around the country may blanch at the
thought of an appeals court ruling that requires equipping new buses
with wheelchair lifts for the handicapped.
   There would be good reason for such a reaction, given the
$15,000-per-bus cost at a time of dwindling federal subsidies for
transit systems.
   There is even better reason to applaud the court's dictum to the
Transportation Department.
   We have a national commitment to ease life for the handicapped
insofar as possible.
   It should be undertaken in spite of the substantial outlay this
would entail.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 2
   The Inter-Mountain, Elkins, W.Va., on President Bush's help for
Texas:
   President Bush certainly believes in taking care of his own.
   Among his proposals to improve the nation's productivity are many
that directly benefit the state of Texas.
   He wants a writeoff for domestic oil. He wants to proceed with
the superconducting supercollider, to be located in Texas. He calls
for building a manned space station with headquarters in Houston.
   If he has his way, the productivity should be improved in Texas.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 1
   The Daily Journal, Elizabeth, N.J., on acid rain:
   When asked recently by Canadians when he intended to do something
about reducing acid rain clouds that float northward toward the
dominion, President Bush said: ``I have in mind, `as fast as
possible.'''
   While it's not a firm timetable, it's a welcome change from the
stance of the Reagan administration; it never seemed quite able to
figure out where the pollution was coming from.
   Bush's move is a good one simply because it is right. There are
too many people on the face of our globe to continue abusing it as
we have. A commitment from the world's largest industrialized nation
to abate this maltreatment comes none too soon.
   To that end, Bush has pledged his personal backing, as well as _
to begin with _ $2.5 billion over five years for clean-coal
technology. Let's hope it produces results.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 3
   The Arizona Daily Star, Tucson, Ariz., on Brazil's rain forest:
   Brazilian President Jose Sarney says he's distressed at the way
the world is jumping on Brazil's case about the destruction of the
rain forest.
   He sits on a high horse and talks about how those in the United
States and Europe have no room to throw stones. It is the industrial
nations that gave the world acid rain, a depleted ozone and a
growing greenhouse problem, says Brazil's interior minister.
   Fine, Mr. Sarney. Don't listen to those busybodies from countries
with economies far healthier than Brazil's. Listen to Brazil.
   Listen to what Brazil's diverse, indigenous groups have to say.
Several dozen Amazon Indian tribes got together for a conference
(last month) to demand a say in the development of their homeland.
They want dams on a tributary of the Amazon stopped. ...
   These are people who understand how to use the wonderful,
mysterious plants of the rain forest. They tap resources the
scientists of the developed world have yet to discover. Exchange the
wealth of their culture and rain forest for the short-term gain of a
dam here or a road there and Brazil will shortchange its future.
   Brazil doesn't have to listen to world opinion. But for its own
sake, it ought to listen to the voices from within.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
