<HEAD>UNDATED: from within.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 5
   The Rapid City (S.D.) Journal on Bibles in hotel and motel rooms:
   In the off-chance that this quest to outlaw Gideon Bibles isn't a
joke, let's say that any innkeeper who wants to make the Bible
available to guests forces nothing on them, and offers them
something of value.
   Untold millions have drawn comfort, inspiration and insight from
the Bible. It's a great book from many perspectives.
   No one forces a guest to pick up the Bible from the nightstand,
any more than the guest is forced to switch on the television.
   Everyone has the right to seek truth in his or her own way.
   If the Freedom From Religion Foundation is offended by the Bible,
its members shouldn't read it.
   But trying to deprive others of the opportunity is wrong.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 3
   Chronicle-Tribune, Marion, Ind., on killer vegetables:
   All the recent reports about pesticide-tainted fruits and
vegetables have left us a little confused.
   We're now being told that pesticide residues left on 27 different
fruits and vegetables _ such items as apples, carrots, broccoli,
grapes and tomatoes _ may eventually cause cancer.
   If memory serves us correctly, for the past few years we've been
told by medical authorities that we ought to eat more of those items
to help prevent cancer.
   Sometimes you just don't know who to believe.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 6
   The News &amp; Observer, Raleigh, N.C., on day care:
   Day care is a painful dilemma for working parents, whether those
parents work to scrape by, or whether they work to afford the status
symbols of the up and coming.
   Finding care for the most important people in their lives, their
children, is a financial and emotional burden.
   It is the burden of government as well, as states seek to define
their role in providing day care assistance to those who cannot
afford it. ...
   Though it's no longer uncommon for both parents in a home to work
full-time, and certainly common for single mothers and fathers to
work, employers have taken the attitude that caring for children is
the family's problem. It is, but not entirely.
   Children who are not given adequate care in their first three or
four years frequently find themselves behind in school from the
start, and they never catch up. That hurts them in the adult work
force, and it ultimately hurts their community and their state.
   In that sense, then, the lack of good day care is everyone's
problem.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 3
   The Register-Guard, Eugene, Ore., on wasting energy:
   Making more efficient use of energy has always been the key to
improving standards of living despite dwindling resources and
mounting environmental concerns.
   But two years ago the United States' progress toward more
efficient use of energy stalled. Last year, the country actually
lost ground in terms of efficiency. ...
   For the first time since the energy crisis of the 1970s, (in
1988) Americans' appetite for oil, coal, natural gas and other types
of energy grew faster than their productive output.
   A continued decline in energy efficiency would have a number of
unwanted consequences.
   The nation's bill for imported oil _ already $40 billion a year _
would rise without a corresponding increase in economic output. The
rate at which finite energy resources are depleted would accelerate.
Air pollution, acid rain and the greenhouse effect would be
aggravated. ...
   (M)any of the problems caused by wasteful energy consumption,
ranging from smog to excessive reliance on foreign suppliers, need
to be addressed even if energy remains cheap and plentiful.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 6
   The Milwaukee Journal on juvenile antics of athletes:
   Once upon a time, the sports pages of newspapers told readers
about such things as shooting percentages, who scored touchdowns for
the Packers and goals against the Rangers, and who's on first.
   But no longer, an East-coast friend of ours complained the other
day. On a single page of his newspaper one day last week, he
reported, were the following:
   _ Bob Probert, a Detroit Red Wings forward, was charged with
smuggling 14.3 grams of cocaine across the U.S.-Canadian border.
   _ Darryl Strawberry of the New York Mets took a swing at a
teammate and walked out of training camp, angry because he was only
the sixth-highest-paid player on the team, pulling down a mere $1.4
million this year.
   _ Strawberry and his sparring partner, first baseman Keith
Hernandez, later had a meeting with _ get this _ the Mets' team
psychiatrist.
   _ A track coach testified that anabolic steroids were a major
component of the training program of sprinter Ben Johnson before the
1987 world track and field championships. ...
   It was all news, of course, and it belonged in the paper. At the
same time, we join our friend in wishing that more athletes would
act more like athletes and less like overpaid, overaged adolescents.
</TEXT>
