<FIRST>u i PM-Pope-Bishops 2ndLd-Writethru a0542 03-08 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Bishops, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0542,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Calls On U.S. Bishops To Support Church's Teachings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with meeting beginning, pope's comments.
No pickup. ^By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II opened an extraordinary
meeting with U.S. Roman Catholic leaders today and challenged them
to proclaim the church's message in ``a world that does not often
readily accept it.''
   John Paul spoke briefly in English to 36 U.S. prelates summoned
to Rome for a meeting the Americans hope will ease tensions between
U.S. Catholics and the Vatican, which has been unhappy about dissent
among the American faithful.
   Many American Catholics, for instance, disregard church teaching
on matters such as artificial birth control and remarriage for
divorced people.
   The role of the bishop is expected to be the dominant topic in
the 12 hours of discussions with top Vatican officials through
Saturday. Other issues on the agenda include the family, the
sacraments and Christian education.
   ``I wish to encourage you in your ministry,'' the pope told the
bishops, gathered in the Vatican's Old Synod Hall. ``I am fully
conscious of the challenges you face in bringing the Gospel message
to a world that does not often readily accept it.''
   ``Your people experience the difficulties of being Christians in
today's world. Yet at the same time they search for direction in
following the path marked out by Christ.''
   Earlier today, a cardinal representing the U.S. bishops declared
that American democratic freedoms are not at odds with faithfulness
to the church.
   American bishops have maintained that disagreement among
Catholics reflects their democratic heritage. The pope, however,
says people cannot dissent from church teachings and be considered
``good Catholics.''
   ``As U.S. bishops, we value highly the founding principles of our
country and its democratic traditions,'' Cardinal Joseph Bernardin
of Chicago said at a news conference before today's meeting began.
   ``While as a community we operate according to different
principles ... I do not see these freedoms or their exercise as
being in conflict with our faithfulness to the universal, Catholic
tradition that is ours.''
   Cardinal Bernardin Gantin, head of the Vatican Congregation for
Bishops, said ``there isn't alarm'' in the Vatican about the U.S.
church, but ``it is true that problems exist.''
   ``We already studied the burning, difficult, serious problems''
during visits by U.S. bishops last year, he said at the news
conference, and this week's meeting will focus on how to resolve
them. He mentioned the secularization of U.S. society as a problem
for the American church.
   ``I expect that there will be a free-flowing discussion among
everyone there,'' Archbishop John L. May of St. Louis, president of
the U.S. National Conference of Catholic Bishops, said in an
interview Tuesday.
   He added: ``There will be probably, in any free-flowing
discussion, points of difference, points of difference that will be
discussed and faced.''
   The Vatican believes the 52-million-member American church is
critical because of its size, its wealth and its potential to set
worldwide trends.
   The pope summoned much of the American Catholic hierarchy to Rome
for this week's session: the five active U.S. cardinals, 30
archbishops and a bishop, all representing major dioceses.
   Bernardin said Tuesday that the U.S. hierarchy hoped to increase
the Vatican's understanding of American culture and the church's
part in it.
   ``When you are involved in a universal church such as ours, there
is a need for communication,'' he said. ``The more we can do, the
better everyone understands what is involved.''
   May said some problems with Rome stemmed from a ``lack of
understanding'' by Vatican officials. ``Some of these men have not
been in the United States, or not very much,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
   He said he hoped the meetings lead to a ``deeper understanding of
separation of church and state, a deeper understanding of freedom of
thought in the United States ... a deeper understanding of the
democratic process that we're used to, which is not always the way
things are done in the church.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
