<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Africa-Locusts     03-08 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Africa-Locusts,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAO Says Dry Winter Easing Locust Plague</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unusually dry winter has helped ease Africa's
disastrous locust plague, a U.N. official said Wednesday.
   ``The problem has by no means been eradicated, but it has
improved dramatically in the last five months,'' said Jeremy Roffey,
a locust expert at the Food and Agriculture Organization based in
Rome.
   Other helpful factors have been strict measures to combat the
pests and their migration to the sea as they moved across the
Atlantic.
   In January, swarms of locusts devoured crops in Sudan, Ethiopia
and Chad, which already were suffering critical food shortages.
   Desert locusts aided by easterly October winds traveled 3,100
miles to reach Caribbean islands. At the same time, locusts crossed
the Red Sea into Saudi Arabia; new invasions were reported in Cape
Verde and Senegal; and swarms reached the North African states of
Algeria, Morocco, Tunisia and Libya.
   Rain provides the moisture needed for locust eggs to develop in
sand or soil.
</TEXT>
