<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru   03-08 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0590,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Says Five Soldiers Killed On Cease-Fire Line Feb. 17th</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with U.N. confirmation of deaths.
Pickup 4th pvs, `Peacekeeping officials...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's U.N. ambassador said today that an
Iraqi ambush killed five Iranian soldiers Feb. 17. It would be the
deadliest clash since a cease-fire took effect seven months ago.
   Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati said members of the
U.N. Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group, who have monitored the
truce, told him of the incident.
   A U.N. spokeswoman confirmed that Undersecretary-General Marrack
Goulding, the chief U.N. peacekeeper, had received reports from his
officers that ``five Iranian soldiers had been shot in the back and
killed.''
   ``Iran said that they had been killed in an Iraqi ambush;
however, the investigation by UNIIMOG observers could not confirm
this,'' the spokeswoman, Nadia Younes, said.
   Peacekeeping officials normally do not verify allegations of
truce violations by Iran and Iraq, leaving that for a
secretary-general's report that is issued every six months when the
mandate of the U.N. peacekeepers must be renewed. The most recent
report was issued Feb. 2.
   Mahallati's letter said ``Iraqi forces ambushed our patrols''
near Baneh, in the central sector of the front, 20 miles from the
border with Iraq and about 310 miles west of Tehran.
   The attack killed five Iranian soldiers on patrol, and a
communications operator was captured, said Mahallati.
   U.N. military observers ``have inspected the location where the
incident occurred, witnessing the martyrs, and have stated that the
perpetrators have fled to their bases,'' said Mahallati.
   In his Feb. 2 report, Perez de Cuellar said two Iranians died in
a Dec. 11 clash near the southern border. The nations' forces are
separated by only a few dozen yards in many places and in one place
face each other across 30 yards of desert, the secretary-general
said in the report.
   The only other reported fatality since the Aug. 20 cease-fire was
an Iranian report that one of its soldiers was killed by Iraqi
gunfire across the truce line hours after the cease-fire took effect.
   Perez de Cuellar did not confirm the report. Talks aimed at
making the cease-fire permanent have been deadlocked since August.
</TEXT>
