<FIRST>r a PM-BrassArrest     03-08 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brass Arrest,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Police Officials Make Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the city's top police officials
chased down a pair of robbery suspects after they saw one running
from a gas station with a wad of cash in his hand.
   ``Being policemen, we knew right away that we probably had an
armed robbery,'' said Capt. Joseph Stelma, who along with Chief D.
Roy Horne arrested the men on Tuesday.
   The officers had just finished lunch nearby when they spotted the
man with a fistful of bills jump into a car parked near the station.
   In an unmarked police car, Stelma, an 18-year veteran of the
department, and Horne, who has been with the sheriff's office for 38
years, chased the supects' car for about three blocks.
   ``We were right on their bumper,'' said Horne, who admitted it
had been a number of years since he had made an arrest.
   Before the suspects pulled over, they threw the money out of
their car.
   Horne later gathered up most of the money.
   It turned out that no weapon was used in the crime. One of the
men apparently reached into a cash register and grabbed a handful of
bills. The two men were charged with theft, police said.
