<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-MinimumWage 2ndLd-Writethru a0458 03-08 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minimum Wage, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0458,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel OKs Measure to Raise Hourly Wage to $4.65</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts graf 7, Bush raised, with White House comment.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   By PAUL PAGE=
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee
today approved legislation to raise the minimum wage to $4.65 an
hour over three years, and committee Chairman Edward M. Kennedy
predicted the first increase in eight years would be swiftly
approved next week by the full Senate.
   The committee approved Kennedy's bill, which President Bush has
threatened to veto, by an 11-5 vote with two Republicans joining
Democrats for the majority.
   ``I think we'll get an increase. This is going to be before the
Congress, before the Senate and before the president in the next few
weeks,'' Kennedy, D-Mass., said afterward.
   ``This will basically restore a minimum standard of decency'' to
workers who are now covered by the $3.35-an-hour minimum wage that
has been in effect since 1981, he said.
   Kennedy said he is ``glad to listen'' to the administration's
proposal for a lower ``training wage'' for newly hired workers but
said he and committee Democrats remained strongly opposed to it
because it has no provision for ``real training'' and all
minimum-wage workers would be covered.
   Kennedy predicted that a presidential veto would be overridden.
``We're going to get this legislation achieved,'' he said.
   Bush raised the subject of the minimum wage during a morning
meeting with Republican leaders in Congress. White House press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush had given Congress ``our best
and last figure up front and his proposal for an increase to $4.25
an hour is fair and firm and his last offer.''
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole said last week that Bush wants an
increase of 90 cents an hour, to $4.25, over three years. She said
the raise must be accompanied by a provision allowing businesses to
pay all newly hired workers $3.35 an hour for the first six months
of their employment.
   Kennedy's support for some type of sub-minimum was qualified,
with the longtime opponent of the provision saying it would have to
be accompanied by training and education for new workers.
   ``The concept of an educational component to the minimum wage,
coupled with real training, is not unappealing,'' said Kennedy.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, the ranking Republican on the committee and a
longtime opponent of the minimum wage, earlier said he will support
an increase if Democrats accept a training wage.
   ``If they'll work with the president, there will be a raise in
the minimum wage,'' said Hatch, R-Utah.
   An aide to Kennedy said the senator remains ``nowhere near the
administration's position on this'' despite his change.
   ``We are willing to discuss a training wage,'' said the aide, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``For the past eight years what we saw was intransigence (from
the White House). The Bush administration has shown some flexibility
and we too are willing to be flexible and to discuss a real training
wage,'' said the aide.
   Other Democrats also said they'll take some form of the
``training wage'' in hopes of reaching agreement with the Republican
administration.
   ``I think some kind of compromise is going to have to be worked
out, at some point,'' said Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., a member of the
Labor panel who has also opposed a sub-minimum wage.
   Organized labor has opposed the second tier because of fears that
workers would be fired in favor of those covered by the lower
standard. But the AFL-CIO now says it is ``open to discussion on the
training wage.''
   ``One of the problems in the administration proposal is that
every time you take a job you become a trainee again,'' AFL-CIO
spokeswoman Lorrie McHugh said. ``And most of the jobs, the
lower-paying jobs are not skill jobs, don't require training at
all.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
