<FIRST>r w AM-PentagonWaste     03-08 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon Waste,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Making Scant Progress Against Dangerous Wastes: GAO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department has been largely
unsuccessful in developing and implementing a program to minimize
hazardous wastes at military bases, the General Accounting Office
said Wednesday.
   The agency, an investigative arm of Congress, found that the
services have made varying degrees of progress in implementing
programs to reduce hazardous waste 50 percent by the end of 1992.
   ``Clearly the Pentagon's efforts to reduce the amount of
hazardous waste generated, have to date, been unsatisfactory,'' said
Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., one of two congressmen who requested the
report.
   The GAO study found that the Army, the Navy and the Air Force
report annually on hazardous wastes to the Pentagon but that the
report does not require the information be correlated with the
workload of major military installations.
   In addition, the GAO found a number of inconsistencies and
inaccurate methods of data collection, making the information
unreliable. ``It's the same old problem we have found in every other
aspect of DOD's hazardous waste program _ somehow the message never
gets through to the base commander or others responsible for
day-to-day waste management activities,'' said Rep. Mike Synar,
D-Okla.
   The Pentagon is spending $500 million in fiscal 1989 to clean up
the old hazardous waste dumps and other sites and more than $100
million a year disposing of newly generated hazardous waste.
   The GAO report recommended that the secretary of defense
establish a standard methodology for collecting and reporting
hazardous waste within the department.
</TEXT>
