<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1341EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AdvancedTechnology     03-08 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Advanced Technology,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel's Chairman Hits Administration's High-Technology Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a House Science subcommittee
said Wednesday his panel ``feels a very strong sense of
frustration'' over the Bush administration's failure to fund a new
program designed to assist U.S. industry with high-technology
innovation.
   Rep. Doug Walgren, D-Pa., spoke out at a hearing focusing on the
Advanced Technology Program at the Commerce Department's National
Institute of Technology and Standards.
   The program is designed to coordinate development of
emerging-technologies and manufacturing-research consortia; foster
industry, government and university partnerships, and monitor
cooperation between federal and regional agencies.
   But no money was allotted for the program in the fiscal 1989 or
1990 budgets.
   Walgren said that when the trade bill, of which the program is a
part, became law last year, ``we had high hopes that finally ... we
can move ahead and provide the same kind of support to American
companies that is provided to science-based commercial activities in
the countries which are our greatest competitors.''
   He asserted that ``if we do not modernize our thinking about the
role of government and provide the American private sector with the
resources they need to compete against the kind of competition which
is coming from overseas, we will, I'm afraid, miss out on the vast
payoffs which these technologies promise.''
   Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., said ``the jury is still out''
regarding what attitude the new administration will take toward the
Advanced Technology Program and other civilian high-technology
initiatives.
   ``Until we have a national science adviser and the president gets
his team in place, we might suspend judgment, at least critical
judgment,'' he said.
</TEXT>
