<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Tower-Bork     03-08 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower-Bork,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bork Says His Senate Ordeal Set Stage For Tower Grilling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WYOMISSING, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Supreme Court nominee Robert Bork
says his grilling before the Senate in 1987 set a precedent for the
rough treatment that John Tower is getting in confirmation hearings
for secretary of defense.
   ``Of course I feel sympathy for him,'' Bork said Tuesday before
addressing 350 local Republicans. ``I think my episode set a
pattern. ... Those folks tasted a little blood.''
   Senate confirmation of Tower has been jeopardized by allegations
of drinking and womanizing and concerns about his ties to defense
contractors.
   Bork, nominated for the Supreme Court by President Reagan,
testified for 30 hours over five days during his confirmation
hearings, defending his conservative record and narrow reading of
constitutional protections that enraged civil liberties and women's
rights groups.
   After listening to 112 witnesses over 12 sessions, the Senate
rejected Bork's nomination 58-42. It was only the 11th time the
Senate had voted against a Supreme Court nominee.
   During a dinner speech, the former federal appellate judge said,
``I think it's legitimate to ask if (Tower) has personal habits that
will interfere with the performance of his duties.'' But he added
that Tower should be confirmed because those habits did not prevent
him from being an effective senator or compiling an impressive
resume.
   Bork said there is a new ``venomous mood'' in the capital, and
``Senate Democrats in a variety of ways are intent on taking over
the functions of the president.''
   Bork left the bench in 1988 to ``debate, discuss how we should
view the Constitution and how we should select judges.'' He is
working on a book that explores the intrusion of politics into
constitutional law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
