<FIRST>r a AM-LouisianaTaxes     03-08 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Louisiana Taxes,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roemer Wins Approval Of Tax Overhaul, Draws Opposition From David
Duke</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Louisiana Legislature's approval of
Gov. Buddy Roemer's tax increase plan sets up an April 29 vote on a
constitutional amendment to overhaul a system dating to the populist
Huey Long era.
   Legislators adopted the proposal Tuesday at a special session
Roemer called to address a projected budget shortfall of $654
million for the next fiscal year.
   State revenue has fallen sharply because of Louisiana's oil-bust
recesssion and its unemployment rate of more than 11 percent, the
nation's highest.
   Rep. David Duke, the former Klan leader recently elected as a
Republican from a New Orleans suburb, promised to lead opposition to
Roemer's program.
   ``I don't care what the American Nazi Party thinks about this
program,'' the governor responded. On Monday, Duke apologized to the
House for being photographed shaking hands with an official of the
American Nazi Party.
   ``How can you dare not call this a tax increase?'' Duke shouted
at administration floor leaders during House debate. ``How can you
say that income taxes will be increased by $165 million and that's
not a massive tax increase?''
   The Roemer administration has depicted the plan as a reform
program providing a net increase in revenue of $25 million over
current levels. Current revenue includes a one-year, $500 million
sales tax increase, that expires June 30.
   The Roemer proposal would make much of that increase permanent,
along with some tax breaks and an increase in income taxes.
   Roemer's program also includes a 4-cent gasoline tax increase to
pay for a $1.5 billion improvement program for highways, airports
and ports.
   For both the highway improvement program and the tax code
revision to go into effect, a majority of voters must approve a
constitutional amendment April 29.
   Last year, Louisiana had to sell long-term bonds to pay off an
accumulated deficit of about $900 million.
   Roemer's initial attempt to revise the tax system failed before
the Legislature in October over his proposal to lower the state's
$75,000 homestead tax exemption. The governor did not touch the
exemption in his latest package.
</TEXT>
