<FIRST>r w AM-US-PLO     03-08 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-PLO,400</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Three PLO Members Cleared to Attend ^By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a move approved by Secretary of State James
A. Baker III, three members of the Palestine Liberation Organization
will be permitted to enter the United States to attend a conference
at Columbia University, the State Department said Wednesday.
   ``None of the three has any record of personal involvement in
terrorism,'' spokesman Charles E. Redman said in announcing the Bush
administration would waive a 1974 law that generally prohibits the
issuance of visas to the PLO based on a judgment that the
organization engages in terrorism.
   The Israeli Embassy reacted swiftly and negatively. ``We regret
the decision by the U.S. government to grant visas to
representatives of a terrorist organization and have expressed this
position to the administration,'' spokesman Yossi Gal said.
   The conference, scheduled Friday through Sunday in New York, is
sponsored by ``New Outlook,'' an Israeli magazine, and by the East
Jerusalem Palestinian newspaper ``Al Fajr.'' Several left-wing
members of the Israeli Knesset, or parliament, also are to attend.
   Redman said the State Department recommended issuance of the
visas to the three Palestinian Arabs, Nabil Sha'th, Noha Nicholas
Tadros and Afif Safyah, and that the Justice Department concurred.
He said Baker was ``involved'' in the recommendation.
   All three Palestinians have attended academic conference in the
past with U.S. permission, the spokesman said.
   Under the law being waived in this case, Yasser Arafat, chairman
of the Palestine Liberation Organization, was denied a visa last
year to participate in a Mideast debate at the United Nations. The
move, recommended by then-Secretary of State George P. Shultz,
evoked criticism from U.N. officials and Arab and West European
governments.
   That conference was shifted to Geneva where Arafat issued
statements urged on him by the State Department renouncing terrorism
in all forms, affirming Israel's right to exist and accepting U.N.
Security Council resolutions that all countries in the Middle East
should be able to live peacefully within secure borders.
   This led to a decision by Shultz and then-President Reagan in
December to drop a 13-year ban and open talks with the PLO. Five
meetings have been held in Tunisia with U.S. Ambassador Robert
Pelletreau.
   Three attacks by PLO guerrillas on Israeli positions in southern
Lebanon since then were sharply criticized by Baker and spokesman
Redman. In the meantime, the dialogue is being continued.
</TEXT>
