<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1925EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-AIDS     03-08 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-AIDS,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet AIDS Cases Rising Fast; Health Minister Says Danger Ignored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviets are expressing alarm over the spread of
AIDS at home, with the health minister calling it a threat akin to
that posed by nuclear weapons.
   The number of cases in the Soviet Union is expected to rise
almost tenfold next year.
   As recently as 1987, Soviet officials dismissed AIDS as a largely
Western problem due to decadent sexual mores and drug use. Foreign
Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov called the disease ``a
scourge of God for the downfallen morals in our world.''
   But now, the daily newspaper Izvestia says, ``The alarming
situation with AIDS demands rapid and decisive measures.''
   ``A long time ago, some noted epidemiologists reported with
certainty that this new 20th century plague would pass us by,''
Izvestia said Tuesday. But the rapidly increasing number of Soviet
cases shows ``AIDS is not somewhere `over there, in their country,'
it is among our population,'' the paper said.
   ``The threat that we face is no less than the ecological `bomb'
or nuclear weapons,'' Health Minister Yevgeny Chazov was quoted by
Izvestia as telling a conference of Soviet epidemiologists convened
to discuss the disease.
   In 1988, Izvestia said, 81 people in the Soviet Union were
carriers of the AIDS virus. By Feb. 1, it said, 44 more cases were
known, and now the number of people infected exceeds 140.
   ``It's expected that next year, there will be 1,342 sick
people,'' Izvestia said, apparently referring to carriers of the
virus, rather than people actually suffering the symptoms of AIDS.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer. It is spread most often through sexual
contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood
or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring.
   Izvestia said that of four Soviets actually ill from AIDS, three
have died. The Soviet Union reported its first AIDS death in
October, a 29-year-old Leningrad prostitute.
   Izvestia quoted Chazov as telling the meeting that the Kremlin
ignored warnings that AIDS could become a national calamity.
   Chazov said Health Ministry workers tried many times ``to inform
the government that the situation was menacing,'' Izvestia said.
``But noted scientists dealing with the problem eliminated the
acuteness of the question, saying it was all a false alarm.''
   In articles that horrified many Soviets, newspapers reported in
January that children at a maternity home in Elitsa, near the
Caspian Sea, had been infected with AIDS because of the multiple use
of an unsterile syringe.
   Nurses at the hospital had been reusing disposable syringes to
cover up the sale of unused needles to drug addicts, the reports
said.
   So far, 31 infected children in Elitsa have been identified,
Izvestia said, and ``on average, one more is detected every week.''
   Just as Soviets are not any more immune to AIDS than Westerners,
some are also liable to treat its victims as pariahs, Izvestia said.
   ``It seems recently we read about `AIDS phobia' (the fear of
getting AIDS) in the U.S.A.,'' the paper said. ``We read, and we
shuddered: apparently normal, decent people were compelling a sick
person to leave town. They were burning down the house where he
lived ... We told ourselves then: Well, no, that's impossible here.
But things proved that it is possible.''
   In the area around Elitsa, people throw rocks at cars with
license plates from the region ``as if the cars were spreading
AIDS,'' Soviet poet David Kugultinov wrote in Izvestia last month.
Youngsters from the region are also being discriminated against, he
said.
   ``The relationship of students leaving Kalmykia to study in
neighboring republics has sharply changed, voices are calling out,
demanding to separate them from the dormitories,'' Kugultinov wrote.
   He said his country should follow the example of the United
States in seeking to prohibit discrimination against AIDS victims.
   In the past 1{ years, the Soviets have decreed measures designed
to counter the spread of AIDS. In 1987, it became a crime to infect
someone else. Regulations announced this year require foreigners who
want to stay in the country for more than three months to prove they
are free from AIDS.
   By Western standards, the Soviets, as of now, have only a small
problem with AIDS, if the figures published by Izvestia are
accurate. In comparison, the number of AIDS victims in the United
States had risen to 86,157 as of Feb. 16, the World Health
Organization said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
