<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Powers     03-08 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Powers,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Agent Who Crack Brinks Robbery Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ADOLPHE V. BERNOTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward Powers, the FBI agent who helped
solve the 1950 $2.2 million Brinks armored car robbery and was
picked for his law enforcement background to manage the first modern
American lottery, has died at age 75.
   Powers died Tuesday in Fort Myers, Fla., where he moved in 1978
after retiring as director of the New Hampshire lottery. He had
undergone bypass surgery in 1979 and last year.
   The ``Handbook of U.S. Lottery Fundamentals,'' a 400-page
reference manual, recognizes Powers as the ``father of U.S.
lotteries.''
   He served as president of several national and international
lottery organizations. In his retirement, Powers was a consultant to
several state lotteries and companies that produce lottery
paraphernalia.
   Powers, as FBI agent in charge of the Boston office, spent six
years trying to solve the Brinks case. The break came when one of
the hold-up men informed on the others because he felt he didn't get
his fair share of the loot.
   In 1963, after 22 years with the FBI, he was hired to manage the
New Hampshire lottery because its sponsors wanted to prove it could
be run without organized crime influence.
   ``I remember opponents of the sweepstakes saying that the program
would create untold law enforcement problems and underworld
counterfeiting of tickets,'' he said in an interview shortly after
he retired.
   ``We proved them wrong. We proved a state can operate a lottery
with adequate controls and safeguards to protect the public's
interest.''
   As New Hampshire lottery director, Powers, who lived in Bedford,
was instrumental in lobbying Congress to repeal an excise tax on
lottery winnings and to allow radio and TV stations to broadcast
lottery numbers across state lines.
   The Chicago native graduated from Lawrence College in Appletown,
Wis., and Georgetown Law School in Washington.
   Survivors include his wife, Melva, two daughters and a son.
   Funeral arrangments were incomplete Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2010EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-EscapeDeath     03-08 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Escape Death,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Floats to Freedom, Dies in Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man escaped from East Germany in a homemade
balloon Wednesday but fell to his death on the western side of the
Berlin Wall, police said.
   An East German passport bearing the photograph of the dead man
was found near the site where the balloon crashed, said West Berlin
police spokesman Dieter Piete.
   He said other documents found in the wreckage indicate a woman
also may have been aboard the balloon. Police searched the site for
other clues and urged residents to help in the search.
   Piete said residents in West Berlin's Zehlendorf district
reported seeing a balloon about 7:50 a.m. floating into the city
over the wall.
   Police found the balloon after it became snared in a tree. Piete
said the balloon, made of heavy plastic, had a harness attached to
it containing a man's leather jacket.
   A plastic bag containing a small radio, books and clothing was
tied to the harness, he said.
   After searching nearly eight hours, police found the body of a
man several hundred yards from the crash site and the passport of
32-year-old Winfried Freudenberg of East Germany.
   ``The picture in the passport matches up with the dead man,''
Piete said.
   On Sept. 16, 1979, eight people in a homemade hot air balloon
floated over East German border fences to West Germany, landing
safely near the village of Naila in northern Bavaria. The story of
that escape was later made into a movie.
   According to official West German figures, 78 people have died
trying to escape to West Berlin since East Germany's Communist
authorities built the Berlin Wall in August 1961.
</TEXT>
