<HEAD>For Release at 5 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Medicare Lapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, according to a Villers
Foundation-sponsored study, is how states were complying with the
Medicare catastrophic health expansion requiring them to use
Medicaid to pay Medicare premiums for poor beneficaries.
   The survey looked at various aspects of compliance, including
what the states were doing to notify elderly Americans in their
jurisdictions that they might be eligible for additional benefits.
   The study noted that the states were provided computer tapes from
the Social Seucrity Administration containing information on
Medicare beneficaries with income below $500 per month.
   State outreach activities were reported as follows:
   Alabama: Reliable demographic information has not been collected
yet. No outreach activity under way.
   Alaska: No outreach activity under way.
   Arizona: No outreach activity under way.
   California: No outreach activity under way.
   Colorado: Agency letter and information flier to be used by
interested groups.
   Connecticut: No outreach activity under way.
   Delaware: Will send notices to all persons on the SSA tapes.
Posters are displayed in state service centers and senior citizen
centers.
   District of Columbia: No outreach activity under way.
   Florida: Workshop presentations for community agencies are being
conducted, will use utility bill stuffers, will use staff in
hospitals, press releases, brochures will be placed in SSA offices
and VA offices.
   Georgia: No outreach activity under way.
   Hawaii: Outreach activities are under way using posters, TV ads,
newspaper publicity and working with the aging network.
   Idaho: No outreach activity under way. Already getting 75 percent
to 85 percent of potential eligibles.
   Illinois: No specific outreach plans under way except to identify
current eligibles who are also eligible under new expansion.
   Indiana: No outreach activity under way.
   Iowa: Using SSA tapes to identify potential eligibles. Working
with the Bureau of Elder Affairs. Information has been included in
newsletter.
   Kansas: A general notice was sent to elderly low income energy
assistance eligibles and persons on other current eligibles lists
which might contain potential eligibles under expansion.
   Kentucky: Press releases are being used and current eligibles are
being converted to new eligibles. Research is being conducted to
identify persons listed on the SSA tapes to target outreach efforts.
   Louisiana: Will use SSA tapes and eliminate those with too much
income. Outreach activities are being planned.
   Maine: Working with community groups. Brochures have been
distributed in places where elderly persons are likely to frequent.
Sent notices to persons on SSA tapes.
   Maryland: Will use the Pharmacy Assistance Program to help
identify potential new eligibles.
   Massachusetts: No response to survey.
   Michigan: No outreach activity under way.
   Minnesota: No outreach activity under way.
   Mississippi: No outreach activity under way.
   Missouri: No outreach activity under way.
   Montana: General mailing to persons on SSA tapes, working with
Council on Aging offices, sending out news releases.
   Nebraska: No outreach activity under way.
   Nevada: No response to question.
   New Hampshire: Public notices in statewide newspapers, workshops
are being held in the community, fact sheet is available in SSA and
legal aid offices.
</TEXT>
