<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Choc'late-lyMusic     03-08 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Choc'late-ly Music,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Julia Child's Cake Pan Rhythms Yield Musical Treat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When composer Lee Hoiby watched a videotape of
television chef Julia Child whipping up ``a very special, ve-e-ery
choc'late-ly, bittersweet, loooovely cake,'' he knew he had the
recipe for a scrumptious musical treat.
   His 20-minute ode to Miss Child's chocolate cake, with lyrics
taken verbatim from the tape of a TV cooking lesson in 1961, had its
world premiere Wednesday at the Kennedy Center.
   The musical monologue, entitled ``Bon Appetit!'' after Miss
Child's familiar closing line, featured actress Jean Stapleton
singing her way around an imaginary kitchen, flouring cake pans and
beating egg whites in pantomime to Hoiby's piano accompaniment.
   ``Bon Appetit!'' was served up as the dessert course for an
evening of Hoiby's meat-and-potatoes classical fare. Then, at a
post-concert reception, the audience was invited to sample the real
thing _ Le Gateau au Chocolat, l'Eminence Brune _ prepared from Miss
Child's recipe by the Kennedy Center's head chef.
   Hoiby and Miss Stapleton will repeat their musical cake bake,
which is scored for small orchestra, during a festival of the
composer's music at Long Beach, Calif., later this month and at
Santa Fe, N.M., on April 9.
   Hoiby confessed that his work on ``Bon Appetit!'' was a severe
test of his commitment to a macrobiotic diet, which features such
ultra-healthy foods as cabbage, brown rice and fish with seaweed.
   ``I am tempted not only by the lyrics but by the cake itself,''
he said in a prerehearsal interview.
   ``I often give in to temptation and say I'll make up for it
later,'' he said. ``I love chocolate cake. The things that are out
of reach are what we love in this world.''
   The 63-year-old composer, who lives and works on a 40-acre farm
in the Catskills of New York state, wrote the piece as a
curtain-raiser for performances of a longer, operatic version of the
late Ruth Draper's monologue, ``The Italian Lesson,'' which he
composed for Miss Stapleton in 1984.
   Hoiby and associate Mark Shulgasser liked the idea of using the
script of a Julia Child cooking lesson, and had Miss Stapleton write
the TV chef for permission. She happily agreed, sent along a batch
of tapes and suggested her recipe for chicken Marengo.
   But Hoiby thought chocolate cake was a tastier choice.
   ``She gets pretty carried away about everything, but especially
this dessert,'' Hoiby said.
   During four full days of watching Miss Child's tapes, Hoiby was
intrigued by the ``rhapsodic phrases'' and musical metaphors in Miss
Child's speech as she banged pots, whisked egg yolks into a yellow
ribbon and poured out her creamy chocolate batter with a spatula.
   ``Her speaking patterns really grab you, the phraseology, the
unexpected little interjections,'' Hoiby said. ``There is a kind of
musical cadence in her speech which one isn't aware of unless one
starts to set it to music, and then there it is.''
   Miss Stapleton, a veteran of Broadway musicals who is better
known as Archie Bunker's wife, Edith, on the ``All in the Family''
TV series, agrees.
   ``What I love is her wonderful sense of theater,'' the actress
said of the chef. ``She's not just a cook. She's a character, very
rich and very humorous.''
   Miss Stapleton makes the most of Miss Child's comic touches,
tapping an invisible cake pan and instructing her audience to
``knock out the flour on the floor, if you have a self-cleaning
kitchen like mine.''
   The music accelerates when she beats egg whites in an unlined
copper bowl in a frantic race with an electric mixer. ``We're going
to see who wins,'' she sings, ``and I think maybe I'll win ...
because I'm bigger.''
   Next time _ if there is one _ Miss Stapleton says she'd like to
collaborate with Hoiby on the chicken recipe.
   ``Chickens are always funny,'' she said with a laugh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Gulf     03-08 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Gulf,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Says Five Soldiers Killed on Cease-fire Line in February</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iraqi ambush killed five Iranian
soldiers last month despite a cease-fire in the eight-year war
between the nations, Iran's U.N. ambassador said Wednesday.
   Also on Wednesday, a senior Iraqi foreign ministry official,
Riyad Al-Kassy, arrived at U.N. headquarters for discussions with
officials on coming peace talks between the foreign ministers of
Iran and Iraq.
   Iranian Ambassador Mohammed Ja'afar Mahallati said he learned of
the troop deaths from the U.N. Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group,
which has monitored the cease-fire since it went into effect Aug. 20.
   U.N. Undersecretary-General Marrack Goulding, the chief
peacekeeper, received reports from his officers that ``five Iranian
soldiers had been shot in the back and killed'' Feb. 17, said U.N.
spokeswoman Nadia Younes.
   ``Iran said that they had been killed in an Iraqi ambush;
however, the investigation by (peacekeeping) observers could not
confirm this,'' she said.
   Mahallati discussed the deaths in a letter to Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar that said ``Iraqi forces ambushed our
patrols'' near Baneh, about 20 miles from the border and about 310
miles west of Tehran. A communications operator was captured,
Mahallati said.
   Perez de Cuellar reported Feb. 2 that the worst violence on the
740-mile front line occurred Dec. 11 in the southern border region
near the Shatt-al-Arab waterway dividing Iran and Iraq.
   Two Iranians were killed in that clash, which involved artillery,
rocket and small-arms fire.
   The armies are separated by only a few dozen yards in many
places, and in one spot face each other across 30 yards of desert,
Perez de Cuellar said last month.
   The only previous report of a fatality on the front came just
hours after the cease-fire took effect. Perez de Cuellar's report
did not confirm Iran's claim that Iraqi gunfire killed a soldier in
that case.
   Peace talks between Iran and Iraq have been deadlocked since they
began Aug. 25.
   They are to resume in New York in late March or early April with
a meeting of Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran and his
Iraqi counterpart, Tariq Aziz.
   Last week, Iranian foreign ministry officials met with U.N.
officials to present their views on the talks.
   Iraqi President Saddam Hussein proposed Sunday that the nations
exchange all 100,000 prisoners of war under the Geneva Convention,
which calls for the repatriation of prisoners after active
hostilities cease.
   The exchange would be separate from the peace talks to allow for
progress even if the negotiations remain deadlocked, he said.
   The talks became deadlocked when Iran demanded that Iraq withdraw
its troops from 260 square miles of Iranian territory.
   Iraq refused and countered that Iran must relinquish its right to
search ships in international waters for weapons bound for Iraq.
Iran has not searched any ships since the cease-fire took effect.
</TEXT>
