<FIRST>r w AM-CommunityOrganizations     03-08 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Community Organizations,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Development Groups Said Responsible for 90,000 Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private, non-profit development groups based in
poor communities appear to have created or saved almost 90,000 jobs
in the last five years, according to a survey of those groups by
their association released Wednesday.
   The groups have multiplied rapidly from their beginnings in the
1960s and have grown from 200 or so in the mid-1970s to probably
1,500 to 2,000 today, said the National Congress for Community
Economic Development.
   More than 800 groups participated in the congressional survey,
the first of its kind, which was completed late last year.
   Altough found in all states, these ``community-based development
organizations'' are particularly active where they may receive state
assistance, notably in California, Florida, Massachusetts, New York,
Ohio and Pennsylvania.
   Many groups concentrate on housing for the poor; 458 reported
completing more than 23,000 housing units in 1986 and 1987.
   The organizations reported lending money to 2,048 enterprises,
owning shares in 218 and operating 427 they owned. Most loans and
share investments were for less than $25,000.
   Responding groups reported development of 16.4 million square
feet of retail space, offices, factories and other facilities in
poor communities.
</TEXT>
