<FIRST>r i AM-ArmsTalks     03-08 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Talks,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Ministers Conclude Meeting on Eve of Arms Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers of 35 nations ended a
three-day meeting Wednesday and stressed that a new round of arms
talks should focus on increasing trust as well as reducing weapons.
   The talks opening Thursday could clear Europe of many of the
troops and conventional weapons massed between the Atlantic and the
Urals in the four decades since the Cold War.
   NATO proposed the talks focus first on imbalances and reductions
in tanks, artillery and armored personnel carriers. It says the
Warsaw Pact has a 2-1 edge in such weapons.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze proposed broader
talks, saying he wants existing imbalances removed and then a 10
percent to 15 percent cut in troops and all kinds of weaponry,
including combat airplanes, over the next two to three years.
   Yugoslavia, which is not a member of either military bloc, on
Wednesday backed Shevardnadze's proposal.
   NATO says it wants to focus first on the tanks and other weapons
that could be used in a surprise land attack.
   Shevardnadze on Monday proposed huge cuts in troops and weapons
and further talks to strip the continent of battlefield nuclear
rockets.
   But Secretary of State James A. Baker III and other Western
officials rejected the Soviet suggestion, hinting they viewed it as
a ploy t
interrupted supply lines, he said.
   The wage deferral was approved by more than 80 percent of
employees, an action that Gillette said indicated strong faith in
the future of the business. A wage increase scheduled to take effect
next fall also will be deferred. The plan calls for the workers to
get half of their deferred wages back in December, and the other
half is to be returned next February.
   The Company Store mails about 25 million catalogs annually,
employs more than 1,000 workers in its busy season, and had 1988
income of about $100 million.
</TEXT>
