<FIRST>r w AM-SteelImports     03-08 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Imports,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opinions Vary on Continuing Import Curbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Steelworkers union and a
steel executive called Wednesday for extending steel-import
restraints, while a group of steel users called the curbs ``the
worst possible form of protectionism.''
   A debate sponsored by the private Economic Policy Institute
brought together advocates and opponents of America's five-year
``voluntary restraint'' program, which was negotiated by the Reagan
administration in 1984 and limits steel imports from 19 countries
and the European Community.
   The import curbs expire Sept. 30.
   President Bush pledged just before he was elected to continue the
restraints in some form. But opponents of the plan believe they can
make a case for ending it, or at least shortening the extension to
less than five years and reducing its scope.
   There was no argument at Wednesday's debate that the annual,
product-by-product, country-by-country import ceilings have aided
the steel industry's revival. Imports have been reduced to about 20
percent of the U.S. market, and employment and profits were up last
year over 1987.
   The issue is whether the restraints are still necessary, and to
what degree they have harmed other sectors of the American economy.
   Patrick Thompson, chairman of a coalition of 1,000 manufacturers
that rely on steel products, said the curbs have meant higher steel
prices and poorer product availability.
   ``Instead of growth and profitability through competitiveness,
our steel industry has a `circle-the-wagon' strategy of limiting
supply through trade protection in order to raise prices,'' said
Thompson, president of Trans-Matic Inc. of Holland, Mich.
   But Thomas Graham, president of the steel division of USX Corp.,
said most of his company's customers accept the need for continued
import protection.
   ``If we lacked customer support, believe me, we wouldn't be
here,'' Graham said. ``Ninety-five percent of our customers are with
us.''
   The U.S. industry says it lost $11.6 billion from 1982 to 1986.
   The problem, Steelworkers President Lynn Williams said, is that
the conditions that spawned the restraints _ large subsidies by
overseas governments to support steel firms _ have not changed.
   ``Just as we begin to catch up _ and we're a long way _ the worst
thing in the world would be to choke off this growth,'' he said.
   The U.S. International Trade Commission has been investigating
the effect of the ceilings on U.S. steel-consuming industries. Its
report later this year is expected to be an important part of the
debate over whether the administration should keep the program
intact in its present form.
</TEXT>
