<FIRST>r a AM-SovietAnnulment     03-08 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Annulment,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teacher Files for Annulment From Soviet Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYNN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teacher who fought nine years to win her
fiance's release from the Soviet Union has filed for annulment after
nine months of marriage, alleging he used her simply to get into the
United States.
   Elizabeth Condon, a high school language teacher, and Viktor M.
Novikov, had been reunited on the eve of the 1988 Reagan-Gorbachev
superpower summit.
   Condon, 45, met Novikov, 56, in 1967 while studying in the Soviet
Union.
   She returned to visit him and they made plans to marry, but
Soviet officials refused to let Novikov leave. In 1979, Condon began
lobbying for his release by writing letters and contacting
politicians.
   They were married May 28 in a backyard ceremony to the strains of
``Lara's Theme'' from the movie ``Dr. Zhivago.'' They exchanged vows
in Russian.
   Condon filed a complaint Feb. 3 in Essex Probate Court in Salem,
alleging Novikov encouraged her love and attention because he wanted
to leave the Soviet Union. The complaint also said the marriage was
never consummated.
   Condon, who teaches at Woburn High School, moved Novikov into the
four-bedroom home she shares with her mother. Novikov, a chemist,
began taking English lessons in an effort to begin practicing his
profession.
   But Novikov moved out Jan. 22 into the home of his wife's
brother, according to The Daily Evening Item of Lynn. The newspaper
reported that Condon was upset that Novikov did not contribute to
household expenses.
   Condon has asked the court to declare the marriage annulled,
which would return Novikov to his former status as an alien.
   Federal immigration officials said Novikov could be in trouble if
it's found that he entered the country fraudulently.
   ``He could be deported,'' said Timothy Whelan, Boston deputy
director of the Immigration and Naturalization Service. ``It's not
that automatic and there's a process to be followed, but that's
grounds for deportment.''
   Condon did not immediately return a call to her school Wednesday.
No telephone listing was available for her brother's home.
   When contacted by the Item on Wednesday, Condon said: ``I don't
know why you are calling about this. I am late to school. It is
snowing outside. I have no comment.''
</TEXT>
