<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TempletonPrize     03-08 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Templeton Prize,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>German Scientist And Scottish Minister Share Religion Prize</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A German physicist and a pathbreaking Scottish
minister were named as 1989 co-winners Wednesday of the world's most
valuable prize, the Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion.
   The prize this year is $435,000. It was the first time the prize
has been divided between two winners. A spokesman said judges split
in this 17th year of the award.
   Carl Friedrich von Weizsaecker, 76, of Starnberg, Germany, near
Munich, was cited for initiating talks between scientists and
religious scholars and for research into links between physics,
cosmology and theology.
   The Rev. George McLeod, 92, of Edinburgh, Scotland, was named for
his founding of the Iona Community, an ecumenical center of prayer,
peacemaking and work.
   The winners were announced at the Church Center for the United
Nations. The prizes will be presented privately at Buckingham Palace
in London May 10 and publicly in Tokyo on June 10.
   In statements, McLeod said he would ``use half of the money for
direct action against hunger and the other half for work for
peace.'' Von Weizsaecker said his share would go to furthering
relationships between science and faith.
   The founder of the prize, American investment counselor John M.
Templeton, said the international panel of judges picks winners on
the basis of their originality in advancing the ``love and
understanding of God.''
   He said the prize is deliberately kept larger than others, such
as the Nobel prizes in science and literature, to indicate that
``progress in religion is more important than progress in any other
field.''
   ``The accelerating discovery rate in natural sciences needs to be
matched by man's spiritual progess and discovery,'' he said.
   Von Weizaecker, credited for several discoveries in nuclear
physics, initiated talks in 1949 at the University of Gottingen
between long-hostile disciplines of science and religion and later
at other institutions.
   McLeod, a Church of Scotland clergyman, started the innovative
Iona Community on an island off the west coast of Scotland in 1938
and it has since become a much-visited and influential center.
   For its monastic-type discipline, McLeod set a simple, five-fold
rule of daily prayer and Scripture study, tithing, peacemaking and
responsible work and service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Tibet     03-08 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Tibet,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Tibet, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Criticizes Chinese Use of Force Against Tibetans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed concern
Wednesday about the continued violence in Tibet and criticized the
Chinese government's use of force against pro-independence
demonstrators.
   ``While we recognize the right of a government to maintain order,
we object to the unwarranted use of lethal force,'' said spokesman
Charles E. Redman.
   After three days of anti-Chinese rioting, official reports have
put the death toll in the violence at 12. But Tibetans say far more
have been killed, most shot to death by security forces.
   The unrest, the latest in an 18-month series of demonstrations,
has developed into the most serious challenge to Chinese rule in
nearly three decades.
   Thousands of Chinese troops have converged on Lhasa, the remote
Tibetan city where martial law was declared Tuesday after three days
of anti-Chinese rioting.
   The disturbances began on Sunday, when demonstrators protesting
Chinese rule began rioting, stoning police and building bonfires of
goods looted from Chinese-owned stores.
   Redman, asked about the State Department's reaction, noted that
he has spoken on the matter several times recently.
   He said the U.S. government had approached the Chinese Foreign
Ministry and its State Nationalities Affairs Commission about the
problem.
   ``We stressed a concern in the United States over human rights in
Tibet, deplored the violence which has led to many deaths and
injuries, and asked for an assessment of developments in Tibet and
the likely duration of martial law,'' Redman said. ``While we
recognize the right of a government to maintain order, we object to
unwarranted use of lethal force.''
</TEXT>
