<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1622EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Sudan-UN     03-08 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-UN,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Donors Urge Sudan to Stop War; Canada Threatens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western donors Wednesday urged the
government to end a six-year civil war threatening thousands with
starvation, and Canada said it will halt economic aid unless the
government starts peace talks.
   Apparently responding to those and internal pressures, Prime
Minister Sadek Mahdi on Wednesday sent his interior minister,
Mubarak Fadil Mahdi, to Ethiopia for talks with the southern rebels.
   But the move is unlikely to produce results. The Sudan People's
Liberation Army refused to talk to Fadil Mahdi on a recent similar
mission because they maintain the government first must endorse a
tentative peace agreement reached Nov. 16.
   Earlier Wednesday, Mahdi told a conference in Khartoum that his
government welcomes a United Nations call for a month's cease-fire
to permit delivery of emergency relief to more than 2 million people
facing starvation in rebel- and government-held parts of southern
Sudan.
   ``The problem is whether we can get the other side to accept this
temporary stop for relief efforts,'' Mahdi said.
   He was speaking at a U.N. conference of Western donor countries
and relief agencies organizing the $137.7 million emergency
operation.
   So far $45 million has been pledged for food and medication
mostly available in Sudan.
   The U.N. operation aims at a massive deployment by air, trains,
trucks and Nile River barges to get to 165,000 tons of relief
supplies in the south before the rainy season starts in May and
isolates the area for at least six months.
   The rebels, who want the mostly Moslem government to grant
political and economic reforms to the predominantly Christian and
animist south, have hampered relief efforts by attacking planes and
trains escorted by military personnel.
   The United Nations says 100,000 people could die if the operation
fails. Other relief officials say it could be 600,000.
   Last year, at least 250,000 southerners died, many isolated by
the rainy season.
   Canadian Ambassador Frances Miles Filleul spoke bluntly at the
opening of the two-day Conference for Donor Countries and
Organizations for Emergency Relief Operations.
   ``In absence of a settlement and national reconciliation, we will
reconsider continuing our other assistance,'' he said, emphasizing
Canada would continue humanitarian aid.
   Filleul criticized the Sudanese government for failing to carry
through on a peace proposal negotiated in November between the
rebels and the Democratic Unionist Party, then senior coalition
partner in Mahdi's government.
   Later, he told reporters Canada would cut its economic aid unless
the government took steps toward peace. Canada budgeted $56 million
for Sudan this year, $37.5 million of it in emergency humanitarian
aid.
   Japan, the United States and the European Community Japan were
among other participants that pledged to maintain humanitarian aid
to Sudan, but did not refer to economic assistance.
   The United States halted economic aid to Khartoum in January 1988
because the government owed $74 million in arrears on military and
economic debts, according to Julia Taft, director of the U.S.
government's foreign disaster assistance program. Humanitarian aid
amounting to $62 million was maintained between February 1988 and
February 1989, she said.
   ``There will never be an end to the suffering until there is
peace,'' Taft said.
   Mahdi emphatically denied his government was using food as a
weapon in the conflict, an accusation also leveled at the rebels.
   ``We want to dispel this wicked image of the government using
food as weapons and being callous to the needs of its civilians''
said Mahdi.
   In a related development, U.N. officials in Uganda said a cargo
plane failed to arrive Wednesday in Entebbe, delaying the start of a
major airlift of food to the besieged southern Sudanese town of Juba.
   Peter Matheson of the World Food Program said a C-130 Hercules
chartered from the Southern Air Transport Co. of Miami, Fla.,
apparently was having technical difficulties.
</TEXT>
