<FIRST>r w AM-US-LatinMayors     03-08 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Latin Mayors,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Defends Decision To Deny Visas To Three Mayors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration on Wednesday defended
its decision to bar mayors from Panama, Cuba and Nicaragua from
attending a drug conference in New York, saying none of these
countries can be counted on to cooperate in drug control efforts.
   The conference opened Wednesday without the presence of the
mayors of Panama City, Havana and Managua.
   ``The Americas Mayors' Conference: Drugs and Traffic'' will run
through Friday, with daily panel discussions on various aspects of
the drug problem. It is co-chaired by New York Mayor Edward I. and
Mayor Andres Pastrana of Bogota, Colombia.
   Koch criticized the administration's decision, saying the
conference represents ``an extraordinary opportunity'' for dialogue
among public officials acutely affected by the drug problem.
   The decision to bar the mayor of Havana drew a sharp rebuke from
Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., who said that Cuban President Fidel
Castro has indicated strong interest in cooperating on drug-control
activities.
   Rangel, chairman of the House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse
and Control, said in a telephone interview that the administration
decision shows that ``drugs are not on the administration's foreign
policy agenda'' despite strong public sentiment to the contrary.
   But State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the
administration questions the seriousness of the three goverments
``to undertake anti-narcotics cooperation with the U.S.
   ``In each of these cases, the mayors are in office with the
sanction of the highest authorities in his or her government,'' he
said.
   Redman noted that normal travel in the United States by officials
of the three countries has been suspended because of political
differences each has with the United States. This restriction must
be waived to allow visits by officials from any of the countries.
   Redman noted that there have been several allegations of
Nicaraguan government involving in drug smuggling.
   Last month, however, Nicaraguan officials offered to cooperate
with the United States in curtailing drug trafficking through that
country.
   Rangel's optimistic assessment of Cuba's attitude was based on a
December visit to Havana in which he and other committee members met
with Castro.
   At the time, Rangel said Castro told the delegation he wants very
much to cooperate with the United States and other Latin American
countries in interdicting shipments of drugs.
   ``If they offer to cooperate, we can't afford to say no,'' Rangel
said Wednesday.
