<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Canal     03-08 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Canal,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Technical Delegation Discusses Transoceanic Canal Across
Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Japanese scientists and
technicians began talks Wednesday with Nicaraguan officials on the
possible construction of a canal across Nicaragua.
   The six-member private delegation met with a government committe,
headed by Finance Minister William Hupper, at the Foreign Ministry
on Wednesday morning. Reporters were not allowed access to the group.
   Barricada, the official newspaper of the leftist Sandinista
government party, said the Japanese group inclues specialists in
maritime law, ecology, engineering, architecture and lumber.
   It said the delegation arrived Tuesday night in Managua but did
not say how long it would remain in the Central American cuntry.
   The Japanese Embassy in Managua has said the Japanese government
is not involved in the delegation or the canal project.
   The idea of building a canal across Nicaragua to connect the
Atlantic and Pacific oceans has been around since the late 1800s,
but Panama was chosen instead for the construction of the canal.
   The Nicaraguan government, when it announced in early February
the formation of a committee to start feasibility studies, said it
welcomed private or public investment from other countries.
