<DOCNO> AP890308-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-EconomicOpinions     03-08 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economic Opinions,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans See U.S. Second to Japan in Economic Power, Poll Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans by a two-to-one margin believe that
Japan, not the United States, is now the leading economic power in
the world, according to a public opinion poll released Wednesday.
   The poll, conducted by The Gallup Organization for the Times
Mirror Co., indicated that 59 percent of Americans now rank Japan
first with only 29 percent choosing their own country.
   ``Our survey finds, beneath the surface of general economic
contentment, much unease about the loss of U.S. economic power to
foreign competition,'' said Gallup president Andrew Kohut. ``People
see our ability to compete as declining in the Reagan years.''
   On the other hand, the survey found that 72 percent of policy
makers, executives and other opinion leaders still believe America
is the No. 1 economic power, a sharp difference with the general
public.
   There was just as big a disagreement over the question of foreign
investment in the United States. An overwhelming majority of the
public, 70 percent, saw foreign investment in very negative terms,
with many fearing that foreigners are ``buying'' America and
threatening national security.
   But opinion leaders saw foreign investment as a vital source of
capital for economic expansion.
   The survey, one of a series the Los Angeles-based news company
has commissioned on American attitudes, was conducted between Jan.
27 and Feb. 5. It included one-hour face-to-face interviews with
2,048 members of the general public and had a potential sampling
margin of error of plus or minus two percentage points.
   A separate survey sampled the opinion of 250 government policy
makers, corporate executives, Wall Street financiers and foreign
investors in the U.S. economy.
   The survey of the general public, described as the most extensive
ever on economic attitudes, indicated that 54 percent of Americans
expect things will be better for them financially next year and an
additional 28 percent expected no change in their economic outlook.
But they were much less optimistic about the nation's overall
economic prospects.
   By sizable margins, the general public said it expected inflation
to worsen and interest rates to be rise. Fully 76 percent said they
expected taxes to be increased in 1989, despite President Bush's
``no-new-taxes'' campaign pledge.
   The survey indicated that Americans strongly oppose increasing
general income taxes although large majorities were willing to see
higher taxes on tobacco, alcohol and on people with incomes over
$80,000 a year.
   The poll indicated 85 percent of Americans favored raising taxes
on alcoholic beverages to reduce the federal budget deficit, 75
percent favored boosting taxes on tobacco products and 64 percent
were in favor of a national lottery to bring in revenues.
   Four out of five Americans, 82 percent, favored increasing the
income taxes of people with incomes above $80,000. A smaller
majority, 59 percent, endorsed a proposal to create a new 33 percent
tax bracket for all income over $150,000.
   While calling the budget deficit a major problem, only 18 percent
of Americans could come within $50 billion of guessing its size.
Last year's deficit totaled $155.1 billion, but 28 percent guessed
it was over $300 billion.
   Fears of war and international tension were as low as they have
been in 40 years, the survey said. For example, 79 percent of the
public feels that tensions with the Soviets have been reduced.
   As a reflection of the eased world tensions, the survey found
strong sentiment for cutting the military budget. Asked how to
reduce the federal budget by 5 percent, the public opted to take
nearly half of the revenues from the defense budget.
   The public strongly opposed cuts in Social Security or Medicare
to balance the budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ColliderMoney     03-08 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Collider Money,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hall: Japan Should Help With Collider</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy Department negotiators should pressure
the Japanese into sharing the $4.6 billion cost of the super
collider as a way for Japan to pare its trade imbalance with the
United States, the chairman of a House subcommittee considering the
project said Wednesday.
   ``Japan is the No. 1 (cost-sharing) suspect for us because of the
bad balance of trade and (we should) approach them on that level,''
Rep. Ralph Hall, D-Texas, told DOE officials during a hearing on
foreign participation in the proposed giant atom smasher.
   Hall said later that the trade imbalance with Japan would be a
good lever in cost-sharing negotiations between officials of both
countries.
   ``It gives us a special incentive to dealing with Japan,'' said
Hall, the chairman of the Science, Space and Technology Committee's
subcommittee on international scientific cooperation.
   The United States ran a trade deficit with Japan of $55.4 billion
in 1988, 40 percent of the total U.S. trade deficit of $137 billion.
   James F. Decker, deputy director of DOE's energy research office,
told Hall that U.S. officials are in Japan holding ``unofficial, but
very significant, discussions with Japan's high-energy physics
community on possible ways of collaboration.''
   Decker said it is essential to ``encourage the enthusiastic
support of the Japanese scientists because strong endorsement at
this level is almost certainly a prerequisite for Japanese
participation.''
   But the involvement of President Bush and Energy Secretary James
D. Watkins may be ultimately be needed to convince the Japanese to
invest in the project, Decker said.
   Only India has committed to helping build the super collider,
agreeing to put $50 million into the project, a proposed 53-mile
underground tunnel south of Dallas in which beams of protons would
smash into each other with 20 times the energy of today's most
powerful accelerators.
   But neither foreign countries nor Texas will be willing to
bankroll the project unless Congress commits to its construction,
the panel was told by Decker and Thomas W. Luce III, chairman of the
Texas National Research Laboratory Commission, the state agency
handling Texas' role in the project.
   If Congress goes along with the president and agrees to spend
$250 million on the project in the fiscal 1990 budget, including
$160 million for construction, Texas and foreign countries would
read that as adequate commitment to the project, the officials said.
   The Energy Department is proposing $1.8 billion of the total cost
come from non-federal sources, including $1 billion that Texas has
promised to spend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Missiles     03-08 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Missiles,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Said To Be Building Missile Factory With Help from China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China is helping Iran build a factory to
make surface-to-surface missiles with a range exceeding 500 miles,
Western diplomatic sources said Wednesday.
   They said construction has gone ahead since a U.N.-mediated
cease-fire halted the eight-year Iran-Iraq war on Aug. 20 and that
Iran also is continuing to develop its chemical warfare capability.
   The sources, speaking on the condition of not being identified,
said the missile factory is in northeastern Iran, but they could
give no details.
   One source remarked: ``It's a missile plant and the Chinese are
lending support to build it. That much is known.''
   Tehran television, monitored in Cyprus, said China's deputy prime
minister, Tian Jiyun, ended a five-day trip to Iran on Tuesday. It
made no mention of weapons, saying only that the visit concentrated
on trade and industrial ties.
   China and Iran both deny any arms deals, but U.S. and other
Western officials say China has been a main supplier of weapons for
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's regime. They estimated such sales at
more than $1 billion.
   Among the arms supplied were two types of jet aircraft and the
HY-2 Silkworm and C-801 anti-ship missiles, which have a range of
less than 100 miles.
   The Tehran government said a year ago it was building its own
version of a ``foreign missile'' _ not further identified _ for use
against Iraq.
   According to the authoritative reference, Jane's Weapons Systems,
China's arsenal does not include a surface-to-surface missile with a
500- to 600-mile range, but Western experts said then it would be
relatively simple for Iran to have copied Soviet-designed Scud-B
rockets acquired from Syria or Libya.
   The war between Iran and Iraq, its Persian Gulf neighbor, began
in September 1980 and was marked by periodic missile bombardments of
each other's population centers in what became known as the ``war of
the cities.''
   Baghdad, the Iraqi capital, lies only 60 miles from the border,
and so the initial advantage went to Iran. Last spring, however,
Iraq began using long-range missiles to hit Tehran and other areas
of Iran previously beyond range.
   Some analysts have said Iraq's use of Scud-Bs with boosters to
increase their 160-mile range was a major factor in forcing Iran to
agree to a truce.
</TEXT>
