<FIRST>r a AM-WifeSlaying     03-08 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wife Slaying,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abused Women's Advocate Who Was Beaten to Death Laid To Rest</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SB1, SB3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mourners wore blue ribbons Wednesday to
symbolize commitment to battered women as they laid to rest a woman
who police say was bludgeoned to death by her former husband while
he was on a prison furlough.
   ``In a world filled with people who care only for themselves, she
was a person who cared deeply for others,'' the Rev. Barry England
said of Lisa M. Bianco during funeral services at St. Anthony
Catholic Church.
   Ms. Bianco, 29, a battered wife before divorcing in 1985, last
year became a counselor to battered women at an Elkhart County
shelter. She rose to program director.
   ``Lisa listened to people who cried out,'' England said. ``She
healed their wounds. Having experienced pain and hurt herself, she
continued to love.''
   Nearly 200 mourners, including Ms. Bianco's two daughters, ages 6
and 10, attended the services and burial at Chapel Hill Memorial
Gardens in Osceola.
   St. Joseph County Prosecutor Michael Barnes said a decision
whether to seek the death penalty against Ms. Bianco's former
husband, Alan L. Matheney, 38, would be made next week. Matheney is
being held without bail on murder charges.
   Matheney, who was serving an eight-year prison term for beating
Ms. Bianco and criminally confining their children in 1987, was
released Saturday from the Correctional Industrial Complex in
Pendleton on an eight-hour pass.
   Ms. Bianco was beaten to death with the butt of a shotgun
Saturday outside her Mishawaka home, police said. The force of at
least 20 blows to her head shattered the weapon's wooden stock.
Matheney was arrested later that day.
   Ms. Bianco had asked Department of Correction officials to notify
her if Matheney was released, friends and family members say. Two
prison officers have been suspended without pay for approving the
furlough and failing to notify her.
   Gov. Evan Bayh immediately suspended the furlough program pending
a review.
   The shelter's Wednesday evening counseling session, which Ms.
Bianco was to have attended, was to be held in her honor, said
shelter director Michalyn Chilcote.
   Ms. Bianco had recently joined the Mishawaka Commission on the
Status of Women, which will lobby the Legislature to improve laws to
protect victims of domestic violence, said its president, Bonnie
Bailey.
   Ms. Bianco's brother, Mark, of Mishawaka, urged people to wear
blue ribbons to symbolize their commitment, as well as his sister's,
to helping battered women. Blue was her favorite color, he said.
   ``Let the people who make the laws know we need changes,'' he
said. ``We need more help for battered women's shelters.''
   A memorial fund was set up in her name by the women's shelter.
   In an interview videotaped by prosecutors two years ago, a badly
bruised Ms. Bianco said Matheney had threatened to beat her and take
the couple's two children.
   He said ``he would make my life so miserable that I would wish
daily that I was dead,'' she said.
   ``I bartered for my life yesterday and told him that I would not
prosecute,'' she continued. ``I'm afraid if he does get a hold of me
again that I'm not going to be able to talk about it.''
</TEXT>
