<FIRST>r w AM-Turner-Crime     03-08 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turner-Crime,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>D.C. Police Chief Urges Medical Steps on Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maurice Turner Jr., the District of Columbia's
police chief, said Wednesday that medical researchers should find a
way to immunize youngsters so they won't get high on drugs and thus
would avoid becoming involved in the narcotics trade that has
contributed to a crime wave here.
   ``I believe the greatest contribution the medical community of
this great nation could ever conceive for our children would be the
development of an inoculation or vaccine that would block the
euphoria or high our youth receive from smoking, ingesting or
injecting PCP, crack cocaine, cocaine or heroin into their bodies,''
Turner told reporters.
   However, Dr. Marvin Snyder, director of preclinical research at
the National Institute on Drug Abuse, said the idea of inoculation
was ``theoretically possible'' but not practical.
   Snyder said the prospect of inoculation brings up various ethical
questions, such as whether ``anyone has the right to put someone on
a drug or chemical or immunization that would prevent them from
engaging in an activity.''
   Washington's record homicide rate has followed the trend in other
major American and Canadian cities when the crack cocaine appeared
on the drug-abuse scene, Turner said, and killings probably won't
stop until drug dealers settle turf battles.
   ``This city is one of the last cities where crack became the drug
of choice,'' Turner said.
   The city had a record 372 homicides in 1988, and police said
about 70 percent were related to drugs. By Wednesday, 100 people had
been slain in the city, compared with 55 at this time last year.
</TEXT>
