<HEAD>Students Continue Demonstration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GINSBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesting Howard University students Wednesday
escalated their demonstration, disrupting classes and blocking the
entrance of a site they thought was being used for temporary
administrative offices.
   After learning they had succeeded in driving Republican National
Chairman Lee Atwater from the school's board of trustees, the
students focused their attention on other demands.
   ``At the top of the list is assurances that there will be no
repercussions,'' said student leader William Simms. ``We also want
to see Atwater's resignation accepted in writing, and assurances of
financial aid and better housing.''
   Improved security and a graduate African studies program are also
on the list of demands at the predominantly black campus.
   Students took over the administration building Monday to protest
Atwater's appointment to the board of trustees.
   Howard President James Cheek has said the students' occupation of
the administration building could stop faculty members from
receiving their payroll checks, due Thursday. When the students
learned the school planned to set up a temporary administrative
office in the school's liberal arts building, they staged a sit-in
just inside the entrance.
   However, after Simms met with Liberal Arts Dean Wendy Winters, he
directed the students to leave the site.
   The group of 50 or so students then went on a nearby building and
interrupted classes, chanting and yelling, before regrouping and
returning to the administrative building.
   ``We're trying to rally more support,'' Simms said. ``And we will
continue to disrupt classes and this university until we can open
some lines of communication.''
   Earlier Wednesday, District of Columbia delegate Walter Fauntroy
met with the students in the administration building.
   ``I came for two reasons,'' Fauntroy said. ``To get the details
on the students' demands and to find out what they want met before
leaving the building.''
