<FIRST>u w AM-Tower-Bentsen     03-08 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower-Bentsen,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen Veers from Party, Backs Fellow Texan Tower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, in his first tough
call since running for vice president last year, parted company with
virtually all of his fellow Senate Democrats Wednesday in declaring
he'll vote for fellow Texan John Tower as defense secretary.
   But his endorsement seemed to avoid putting personal prestige on
the line for his former Senate colleague or another Texas friend,
George Bush.
   ``I hope that when I get the next chance to talk with John Tower
about tough job of keeping this country strong, it will be while
he's in his new office,'' Bentsen said in a speech to the Senate.
   His announcement ended weeks of silence on his part and
speculation by others on whether Bentsen would side with Bush or
with his Democratic colleagues.
   It came only after Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine,
predicted the votes were in place to defeat the nomination whatever
Bentsen's decision.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the Armed Services Committee chairman and
the man leading the opposition to Tower, walked over to Bentsen,
touched his shoulder and shook his hand.
   Bentsen's decision was closely watched both because of his Texas
ties and because of the visibility he has held since he had the No.
2 spot on the Democratic ticket last fall.
   Bentsen has assumed the role of party heavyweight, delivering the
Senate Democratic response to Bush's first speech to Congress and
declaring his opposition to some of the administration's spending
cuts and tax proposals.
   When Tower was nominated in January, Bentsen's vote for him
seemed a sure thing. Bentsen spoke warmly about his long-time
colleague when he first presented Tower to the Senate Armed Service
Committee as Bush's choice for secretary of defense.
   He brushed aside as ``just politics'' the brutal attacks against
Democrats by Tower during last fall's campaign. Bentsen sought to
reassure more liberal senators that the hawkish Tower was a good
choice to hold down spending.
   ``John Tower is too much of a conservative to give a blank check
from the U.S. Treasury to the Pentagon,'' Bentsen said.
   But as the showdown over the nomination grew in intensity,
Bentsen avoided the Senate debate _ until Wednesday _ and kept quiet
on how his vote would be cast.
   Republicans in Texas became impatient, as did Bush, whose calls
included one during his Far East trip. Bentsen spoke to the
president ``on three or four occasions,'' said Jack DeVore,
Bentsen's spokesman.
   Tower supporters from Texas pressured Bentsen with telephone
banks and newspaper ads.
   One of the Texas ads referred to him as ``L. Millard Bentsen'' _
a swipe at alleged snootiness derived from last year's campaign,
when Bentsen and Michael Dukakis referred to now-Vice President Dan
Quayle as ``J. Danforth Quayle.''
   But friends and allies said Bentsen, re-elected to a six-year
Senate at the same time he lost his vice presidential bid, felt
little direct political pressure.
   Bentsen reached his decision over the weekend, DeVore said.
   Fellow Democrats would understand Bentsen siding with Tower
because Texans have ``a long tradition of closing ranks,'' said
Joseph O'Neill, a Washington lobbyist who has been Bentsen's top
Senate aide and was chief of staff for his vice presidential
campaign.
   He also would have been safe politically if he had gone against
Tower, said George Christian, a Texas friend and consultant who
served as press secretary to President Lyndon Johnson.
   ``There is not a high degree of passion on either side in Texas.
It's almost titillation rather than any comsuming passion in it,''
he said. The campaigns to influence Bentsen were ``wasting their
money,'' he said.
   Tower supporters expressed relief at Bentsen's announcement.
   ``I think that the timing would have been better if it came
earlier in the debate. But at this stage, I'll take him any time I
can get him,'' said Tower friend Paul Eggers.
   Brad O'Leary, a Washington consultant who raised money for
Tower's Senate campaigns, said Bentsen's timing was ``on target''
for boosting the nomination.
   ``Waiting for one or two other people to do it and and then
standing up and doing it helps build a little psychological
momentum,'' he said.
</TEXT>
