<DOCNO> AP890308-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BirchSociety     03-08 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Birch Society,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative Group Moving To Sen. McCarthy's Hometown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The John Birch Society is pulling up roots and
moving out of the liberal stronghold of Massachusetts, but a
spokesman said Wednesday the arch-conservatives were driven away by
prices, not politics.
   ``The aspects of Massachusetts that we couldn't take was the
expense to live here,'' said John McManus at the group's
headquarters in Belmont, a Boston suburb.
   The group plans to close its Belmont and San Marino, Calif.,
offices and consolidate operations in Appleton, Wis., by the fall.
   Reasons for the move include lower overhead and the fact that the
new chief executive officer, G. Allen Bubolz, lives in Appleton,
McManus said.
   Appleton also is near Grand Chute, hometown of Republican Sen.
Joseph McCarthy, which McManus termed ``a delightful piece of
irony.'' McCarthy led investigations into alleged communist
influence in the 1950s.
   The 31-year-old society, which once labeled President Eisenhower
a ``dedicated, conscious agent of the communist conspiracy,'' has
struggled financially for years, making a appeal for funds after
founder Robert H.W. Welch Jr. died in 1985.
   ``If anybody in the Midwest wants to say thank you to anybody for
the John Birch Society moving in that area they can thank (Gov.)
Michael Dukakis, they can thank Sen. Ted Kennedy and the
Massachusetts congressional delegation,'' said McManus, blaming the
Democratic politicians for the high cost of living in the area.
   The society listed 1987 liabilities of $8.5 million in its latest
filing with the state. The fund balance showed a loss of $7.8
million, compared with a starting deficit of $7.7 million.
   ``We have always been in debt. We always spent more money than we
took in and we always had to go in and scramble,'' McManus said.
   Belmont town officials didn't return telephone calls Wednesday.
   News of the move prompted mixed reaction in Appleton. Mayor
Dorothy Johnson said the town was open to people of all views, but
City Attorney Greg Carmen said he was worried that Appleton's image
would be hurt.
   ``We don't expect everyone to welcome us with open arms,''
McManus said. ``But we mean him no harm nor do we mean harm to any
American.''
   Welch, a candy maker, was one of 12 men who founded the society
in 1958, convinced that leaders around the globe were secretly
planning a world government.
   The society was named after an American intelligence officer who
was killed by Chinese communists in 1945; Birchers consider him the
first casualty of the Cold War. McManus said the socity has several
tens of thousands of members.
</TEXT>
