<FIRST>r w AM-ArcticDrilling     03-08 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arctic Drilling,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Draft Report Overstated Dangers of Drilling: Murkowski</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dangers described in an Environmental
Protection Agency draft report on the effects of oil drilling on
Alaska's North Slope are misleading and no reason to delay oil
exploration in more arctic areas, a Senate committee was told
Wednesday.
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, said the draft report, first
described in a story in Sunday's New York Times, ``needs substantial
work before its finished.''
   ``It's not an objective portrayal,'' he said.
   Tom Williams, a member of the Senate Energy and Natural Resources
Committee staff, said the draft was a summary of a ``trip report''
after a visit to the coastal plain of the Arctic National Wildlife
Refuge (ANWR), where oil exploration has been proposed.
   ``The problems which are documented in the report are activities
which have been raised for not opening ANWR from the beginning,''
said Williams.
   The draft EPA report said improper and careless management of
chemical oil wastes on Alaska's North Slope is seriously damaging
the delicate tundra, the Times reported.
   The report said acres of tundra have been damaged by chemical
spills, oil wastes seeping from drilling pads, stacks of leaking
chemical drums, a mine flooded by a diverted river, overflowing
waste disposal pits and failure to comply with federal regulations
governing the handling of hazardous materials by oil companies in
the Prudhoe Bay oilfields.
   ANWR, just east of the Prudhoe Bay fields, is considered a
promising area for a strike that could produce up to 3.2 billion
barrels of oil, but it also is the breeding ground for North
America's largest remaining herd of migratory caribou and the
habitat for polar bears, musk oxen, wolves, arctic foxes, waterfowl
and fish.
   Legislation that would allow exploratory drilling to begin is
being debated by the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee,
but no action has been taken.
   Murkowski, in promoting the bill, said that since the drilling in
Prudhoe Bay began, there have been advancements in technology that
minimize damage to the environment.
   Furthermore, he said, if no oil is found, the area will revert
completely to its natural state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
