<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1747EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0638 03-08 0864</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness Quotes North: ``I Don't Care If I have to Lie''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with afternoon testimony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North once shrugged off the idea that
his work on behalf of the Nicaraguan Contras might get him in
trouble, saying ``I don't care if I have to go to jail for this, I
don't care if I have to lie to Congress,'' a witness testified at
his trial Wednesday.
   Charges against North include lying to Congress about his
involvement in aid to the Contras at a time when U.S. military help
was banned.
   Conservative fund-raiser Carl R. Channel said North made the
statement in a conversation with Nelson Bunker Hunt, after flying to
Dallas to brief the wealthy Texan on the situation in Nicaragua.
   ``The only thing that sticks in my mind is that Bunker said what
are you going to do? Do you mind getting into trouble?'' Channell
testified. After North gave his answer, Channell said, Hunt
``chortled.''
   Meanwhile, in a related Iran-Contra case, the trial of retired
Vice Adm. John Poindexter, formerly a national security adviser and
North's boss, was shifted from the court of U.S. District Judge
Gerhard Gesell to that of Judge Aubrey Robinson. Gesell is presiding
over the North trial, now in its fifth week.
   The testimony about Hunt was part of a day-long recitation by
Channell about putting North, then a National Security Council aide,
together with wealthy people for briefings about fighting in
Nicaragua.
   Channell said North never personally solicited contributions. The
former Marine lieutenant colonel is charged with conspiring to
defraud the U.S. Treasury as part of the money-raising efforts.
   ``He'd say if people wanted to give after he gave the briefing,
they should give to someone else,'' said Channell under
cross-examination by North lawyer Brendan Sullivan. ``If someone
said `who do I make the check out to,' he said ``you make out the
check to Spitz's organization.''
   ``Spitz'' is Channell's nickname. His organization was called the
National Endowment for the Preservation of Liberty.
   The organization was recognized by the Internal Revenue Service
as a tax-exempt foundation, meaning contributions were
tax-deductible. One of the 12 charges on which North is being tried
says that instead of the money going for charitable works it went
for Contra arms instead.
   ``I was aware we had varied from our mandate, but felt that could
be resolved,'' said Channell, who said he'd assumed since they had
been working with the White House, the legal consel there would find
a way to justify where the money had gone.
   Channell pleaded guilty on April 29, 1987, to depriving the
government of tax revenue by using the foundation to solicit
contributions for military equipment for the Contras. He has not
been sentenced. He pledged under a plea-bargaining agreement to
testify for the government whenever he was called on.
   Under questioning by North's attorney, he said he was proud of
his work for the Contras.
   He testified he received a letter from then-President Reagan
commending his efforts, and then a telephone call. The president
mentioned that he did not understand the opposition of then-House
Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill Jr. to Contra aid.
   Channell said he told Reagan that O'Neill ``prays every day to
defeat everything you believe in and you must fight him as an enemy
and defeat him.''
   He said that the North-Hunt meeting was in Dallas' Petroleum Club
on Sept. 11, 1985 and that North flew there from Washington in a
Channell-arranged airplane. At the end of the meeting North left,
saying ``something like `you all are going to talk about money and I
can't take any money.''
   During the congressional Iran-Contra hearings two years ago,
North testified, ``I do not recall ever asking a single, solitary
American citizen for money'' although ``I showed a lot of munitions
lists.''
   Hunt contributed $237,500 to the foundation and also made a
$237,500 loan to it.
   In addition, Channell testified that North told a Connecticut
woman, Ellen Garwood, about a need for small airplanes for the
rebels. Later that day, she wrote out a check for $75,000 and wrote
across the top that it was tax deductible, he said.
   Mrs. Garwood was at the airport after the North-Hunt meeting, he
said. ``Ollie talked about the need for more planes and she gave
NEPL a check for $32,000 to buy a small plane.''
   When Hunt's checks arrived, Channell said, he asked North to
telephone his thanks. North called Hunt at his home and it happened
that the late CIA director, William Casey, was a dinner guest.
Channell said North commented that the director ``would now know
what was going on.''
   He also testified he arranged for a 10-15 minute meeting between
a wealthy woman, Barbara Newington, and Reagan. Later that day, he
said, North talked with her, and Channell told North he was going to
ask her for a large grant.
   ``Grant?'' asked Gesell. ``You asked her for money!''
   ``I told Colonel North I would try to ask her for over a million
dollars,'' Channel replied.
   The woman made her contribution later, more than $1 million in
stocks, Channell said.
</TEXT>
