<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Egypt     03-08 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Egypt,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Holds Up Aid Pending Egyptian Economic Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is holding up $230 million in
aid for Egypt because President Hosni Mubarak's government has
failed to adopt acceptable economic reforms, State Department
spokesman Charles Redman said Wednesday.
   Redman denied that the aid was contingent on Egypt's agreeing
with the International Monetary Fund on an economic austerity
package, but said it was important that the reforms adopted command
broad international support, including that of the IMF and World
Bank.
   Redman denied a report in the Washington Post that quoted an
unidentified U.S. official as saying, ``We're holding out at this
point for an agreement with the IMF.''
   ``It's not because of the IMF agreement,'' said Redman.
   Egyptian sources said, however, that the United States was tying
its decision to IMF conditions, which they said may be applicable in
general but would be very difficult to implement in Egypt because of
the low incomes of many.
   The sources, who spoke to a reporter on condition they not be
identified, noted recent rioting over IMF reforms in Venezuela,
Algeria, Tunisia and Morocco and recalled that Egypt had food-price
riots 12 years ago that forced President Anwar Sadat to roll back
increases.
   At least 79 people were killed in the 1977 riots, with some
estimates of the casualties going to 800 killed and injured.
   ``We agree with the IMF on the diagnosis and the prescription,
but we differ on the amount of time to implement it,'' said one
source. Egypt, which already has increased prices on bread and other
basic commodities five to ten times in recent years, would like to
phase in the reforms over a few years, he said.
   ``Ideally we would like very much to implement the reforms at the
same pace recommended by the IMF, but it's a question of
practicality,'' he said, adding that the Egyptian government hoped
``Washington, as an ally and friend, would be more sensitive to our
political and social circumstances than a bank.''
   ``We regard the relationship with Egypt as extremely important,
both to us as well as to the interest of broader stability in the
region,'' Redman said.
   He said the aid, a portion of about $4.5 billion in economic and
military assistance approved for the 1988 and 1989 fiscal years, was
being held up because the legislation approved by Congress made it
contingent on ``the understanding that Egypt will undertake
significant economic reforms which are additional to those which
were undertaken in previous fiscal years.''
</TEXT>
