<FIRST>d a AM-AirportVote     03-08 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airport Vote,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver Voters To Decide Airport Issue May 16</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An election will be held May 16 to decide whether
to build a $3 billion Denver airport, Mayor Federico Pena announced
Wednesday.
   ``We have heard from hundreds and hundreds of Denver residents
who have indicated support for the airport, but want to vote on
it,'' the mayor said.
   Pena and several council members had opposed holding an election.
But this week, concerns mounted that a petition drive to force a
referendum could push back the project's construction timetable and
upset financing arrangements.
   Pena said the vote's outcome would be considered binding on city
government, even though the city is ready to break ground this
summer on the airport, the nation's biggest such project in 15 years.
   He said the referendum would not delay groundbreaking. Completion
of the airport is scheduled for 1993.
   The airport would be about 15 miles northeast of Denver and would
replace Stapleton International Airport, one of the nation's busiest.
