<FIRST>r a AM-Snakebite     03-08 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Snakebite,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snake Expert, Recovering From Viper Bite, Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A herpetologist bitten by a deadly viper a
week ago was released from the University of Utah Health Sciences
Center Wednesday, but will be closely monitored, a spokesman said.
   William Haast, 78, has been bitten by snakes 148 times during his
career as a venom researcher. He has built up immunity to the venom
of dozens of snakes, but became ill after being bitten on the hand
Feb. 28 by a Pakistani pit viper.
   After treatment with antivenin flown in from the San Diego Zoo
was less effective than expected, a worldwide effort was launched,
with the help of the Bush administration, to obtain more antivenin.
   Serums came from England, Iran and the Soviet Union, but were not
used because doctors feared possible side effects and because Haast
appeared finally to be recovering.
   ``He will contintue to be treated and seen by physicians on an
out-patient basis,'' hospital spokesman John Dwan said.
   Haast is director of the Miami Serpentarium Laboratories at the
university's nearby research park. He keeps an estimated 1,000
poisonous snakes at the lab, where venom is extracted for research
and the manufacture of antivenins.
</TEXT>
