<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Stalinism     03-08 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Stalinism,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Calls for Investigation of Stalinism in Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist party leaders have ordered an
evaluation of Stalinist crimes in Poland and an analysis of the
``cult'' that surrounded Poland's 1950s leader, Boleslaw Bierut, the
state news agency said Wednesday.
   The leaders also called for ways to eliminate remnants of
Stalinism and urged ``political and moral compensation for actions
of lawlessness and wrongs sustained by citizens in the Stalinist
era,'' PAP reported without elaborating.
   PAP said the comments were made at a Tuesday meeting of the
Politburo, which ``deemed it necessary to make a comprehensive and
in-depth analysis of postulates concerning the activity of Boleslaw
Bierut and the symbols of his cult.''
   Bierut, a slight mustachioed man who was installed as the Polish
leader on Soviet dictator Josef Stalin's orders, directed the Polish
United Workers (communist) Party from 1948 until his death in Moscow
in 1956 after attending the 20th Congress of the Communist Party of
the Soviet Union.
   Bierut became ill at the congress, where Stalin, his mentor who
died in 1953, was denounced by then-Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev.
   After Bierut died, he was replaced by a populist communist
leader, Wladyslaw Gomulka, who introduced a political thaw and
released thousands of people jailed for alleged political crimes
while Bierut was in power.
   The victims included many members of the underground resistance
army that fought the Nazi occupiers during World War II.
   In recent weeks, in line with the attacks on Stalinism in the
Soviet Union, there have been increasingly critical articles about
Bierut in the official press and proposals to rename Bierut
University in Wroclaw and the Bierut Steel Mill in Czestochowa.
</TEXT>
