<HEAD>Fine and Jail Term Proposed for Displaying Flag on Floor or Ground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. G.V. Montgomery, D-Miss., proposed
legislation Wednesday that would set a $1,000 fine and a one-year
term in jail for anyone displaying the American flag on the floor or
ground.
   The proposal by Montgomery, chairman of the House Veterans
Affairs Committee, would expand a 1968 law providing penalties for
publicly mutilating, defacing, defiling, burning or trampling the
flag.
   Montgomery said he was angered by a Chicago art exhibit.
``Citizens throughout the country desire that the flag be treated
with great respect,'' he said. ``It certainly does not belong on the
floor.''
   An exhibit at the School of Art Institute in Chicago consists of
the flag, a wall display of pictures of flag-draped caskets, South
Koreans burning the flag and a ``Yankees go home'' sign; and a
ledger for comments on a shelf below the photos. Veterans say the
exhibit invites viewers to trample the flag as they go to the ledger.
