<FIRST>r a AM-Fernald-Contamination     03-08 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fernald-Contamination,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uranium Plant's Contamination Risk Disputed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four plant workers and two subcontractor
employees at a uranium processing plant showed high levels of
uranium contamination in urine samples last year, the U.S.
Department of Energy said.
   However, U.S. Rep. Thomas Luken questioned the validity of the
urine tests and asked the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency to
return its inspectors to the plant at Fernald.
   The EPA yanked the inspectors from the plant last December after
independent urine tests showed that they, too, had been contaminated
by uranium.
   The plant 18 miles northwest of Cincinnati processes uranium for
the Energy Department, which uses it elsewhere to make nuclear
weapons.
   Pulling the inspectors, Luken said, needlessly alarmed some plant
workers and prompted the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency and
some companies which serve the facility to pull out their
representatives.
   Luken received a letter Tuesday from James A. Reafsnyder, the
Energy Department manager at the plant. It said the four plant
workers and two subcontractor employees were the only ones who
showed high levels of uranium contamination among 7,300 people who
were tested at the plant.
   The letter said the six showed readings above 35 micrograms of
uranium oxide dust per liter, a level considered a health hazard.
Subsequent urine samples did not show unhealthful levels, Reafsnyder
said.
   He also told Luken that 20 plant workers had test results showing
uranium levels which were lower but still above safety levels. Those
workers were reassigned to other areas.
   In his subsequent letter to the EPA, Luken said the agency's
``partial quarantine'' was an arbitrary decision and told EPA
Administrator William Reilly the ban should be lifted at once.
   ``EPA has been cavalier in advising its own employees to stay
away and leaving everyone else in a quandary,'' said Luken.
   EPA spokeswoman Anne Rowan in Chicago said the agency is still
reviewing results of tests on the two inspectors and plans to
announce early next week whether it will allow its inspectors to
return to the plant.
   The agency also has asked a new laboratory to conduct future
tests.
   Meanwhile, The Cincinnati Enquirer reported that internal memos
show that underground ponds of radioactive water have formed beneath
three more buildings at the Fernald plant, posing a threat to water
supplies as well as to the buildings.
   Westinghouse Materials of Ohio, which operates the plant for the
Energy Department, said it has begun efforts to remedy the problems.
   Graham Mitchell, Fernald team manager for the Ohio EPA, said the
information was no surprise. The underground pools could seep
through the ground and contaminate drinking-water supplies for a
wide area, Mitchell said.
   Reafsnyder said that clay under the plant seems to have confined
the contamination.
</TEXT>
