<FIRST>r i AM-MideastRdp     03-08 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mideast Rdp,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Lays Cornerstone For Palestinian Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By the Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat laid the cornerstone of a Palestinian embassy in
Pakistan on Wednesday. President Hafez Assad of Syria denounced the
PLO chairman's new peaceful image, declaring that concessions never
``win back rights.''
   Yitzhak Rabin, Israel's defense minister, said attempts by
radical PLO factions to infiltrate Israel from Lebanon were
``clear-cut terror'' despite remarks to the contrary attributed to
Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   A senior Palestine Liberation Organization official said in
Amman, Jordan, the Israeli army should expect retaliation for
attacks on Palestinians. He added, however, that the PLO will
continue the moderate position it has taken since Arafat renounced
terrorism in December and recognized Israel.
   President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt, the only Arab country to make
peace with Israel, begins a three-nation European tour Thursday
focused on Western Europe's role in Middle East peace efforts and
its economic aid to Egypt.
   Pakistan was the first country to recognize the independent state
declared in November by the Palestine National Council, which acts
as the PLO legislature.
   Aafat said to Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto, the first woman to
lead a Moslem country: ``We know for freedom there is a very high
price. As you have paid for your freedom, we will continue to pay
for ours.''
   More than 100 foreign diplomats and dignitaries attended the
ceremony.
   Assad, in Damascus, did not mention Arafat by name, but declared
in a clear reference that ``the policy of free concessions never led
anyone to win back his rights.''
   ``Whatever such concessions produce they will never achieve
anything because in the end Syria will say no,'' the president said.
``The policy of concessions is very far from our political and
doctrinal thinking.''
   He was addressing a rally for the 26th anniversary of the Baath
Socialist Party's rise to power. Assad, an air force captain in
1963, became president in 1971.
   Assad has opposed previous efforts by Arafat to negotiate with
Israel and has feuded with the PLO chairman since 1983.
   Syria is prepared to attend an international peace conference on
the Middle East, he said, but accused Israeli leaders of
``deliberate intentions of perpetual aggression.''
   Rabin told reporters at an army base in northern Israel the
guerrillas who tried to enter Israel did so ``with the purpose to
inflict damage, killing, maybe taking hostages.''
   ``What we have experienced in the last few months is clear-cut
terror,'' he said. ``If this is not terror, I don't know what is
terror.''
   A senior State Department official quoted Baker on Tuesday as
concluding the attempted raids were not acts of terrorism requiring
a break in American contacts with the PLO.
   ``We make a mistake if we define that too closely,'' he said of
Baker's view about the PLO and terrorism.
   Washington began a dialogue with the PLO after Arafat's
declaration in December.
   Mahmoud Abbas, a member of the PLO executive committee, said
raids from Lebanon are aimed at military targets and do not violate
the renunciation of terror.
   ``We did not mean that armed struggle is a form of terroris,'' he
said in the Jordanian capital. ``The Israeli army, which is killing
our children and raiding our camps, should expect retaliation.''
   He added, however: ``We will not go back on our political
position.''
   Mubarak's tour begins in Belgium and includes visits to the
Netherlands and West Germany.
   In the Netherlands, he will attend a conference on atmospheric
pollution and confer on the side with a major participant, President
Francois Mitterrand of France.
   Osama el-Baz, his chief political adviser, said Mubarak has ``two
major aims: to benefit Egypt's development, economic reform and
bilateral ties and to give a new push to peace efforts.''
</TEXT>
