<FIRST>r a AM-Symphony     03-08 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Symphony,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Orleans Symphony Resumes Concerts After One-Year Layoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New Orleans Symphony, silenced more than a
year ago with a nearly $4 million debt, set the premiere of its new
season Wednesday with a sold-out concert under the baton of
conductor Maxim Shostakovich.
   ``Fanfare For A New Beginning,'' composed by orchestra member
Richard Harrison, will launch the program.
   Also set for the opening were a balloon drop, a party and
fireworks.
   ``I think it's out of danger now,'' said Ronald W. Jones, who
took over in December as president of the symphony board. ``We have
a new emphasis on fund raising and marketing. The symphony has put
together a premier organization.
   ``In a way, the closing of the symphony focused everyone's
attention on the problem and made people determined to keep it from
happening,'' said Jones, who is also president of Louisiana
Coca-Cola Bottling.
   The symphony suspended operations Jan. 16, 1988, almost $4
million in debt.
   The financial crisis had been building for years, blamed on
mismanagement before a professional manager was hired in 1986.
Despite desperate ``save the symphony'' fund drives, musicians
walked out in 1985 and 1987 when they weren't paid, and drastic
budget cuts led to dwindling public support.
   After the 1988 spring season was canceled, a new symphony
organization took over.
   Donations of $225,000, earmarked for the symphony if it reopened,
will pay off the remaining debts and leave the books in the black
Thursday morning, Jones said.
   The symphony's home, the ornate Orpheum Theater, was sold to
eliminate $2.4 million of the debt. The buyers, whose names have not
been made public, have agreed to let the symphony play rent free for
the next five years.
   Lending encouragement to symphony officials was an unexpected
surge in public support. Two-thirds of the season tickets for the
12-week spring program have been sold, although officials had
considered a one-third sale a mark of success.
   It is the 53rd season for the symphony and the third as music
director for Shostakovich, son of the late Russian composer Dmitri
Shostakovich.
</TEXT>
