<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Personnel     03-08 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Personnel,000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tuck Nominated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Wednesday he will nominate
John Tuck, a longtime associate of former White House chief of staff
Howard Baker, to be undersecretary of energy.
   If confirmed by the Senate, Tuck would succeed Donna Fitzpatrick,
who Bush said he will nominate to be assistant secretary of energy.
   Tuck came to the White House with Baker when he became chief of
staff in 1986. Tuck worked as director of the office of the chief of
staff and executive assistant to Baker.
   From 1977 until 1986, Tuck worked in the Senate for Baker and the
Republicans, and prior to that was a GOP aide in the House.
   Bush also said he will nominate David W. Mullins Jr. to be an
assistant secretary of the treasury. Mullins was a professor of
business administration at the Harvard University graduate school of
business administration.
</TEXT>
