<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1933EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     03-08 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinista Newspaper Claims Contras Mobilizing For Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista newspaper claimed
Wednesday that U.S.-backed rebels based in Honduras are mobilizing
for attacks across the border.
   It cited unidentified sources ``close to the rebel leadership''
in the Honduran capital Tegucigalpa. The Defense Ministry said it
had no information other than the report in Barricada, the official
newspaper of ruling leftist party.
   An estimated 11,000 of the rebels known as Contras, the bulk of
the U.S.-supported force, are in Honduran camps in the border area
with their families.
   In Honduras, Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras said
Wednesday the rebel army should not be disbanded and its fighters
repatriated to Nicaragua until the Sandinista government fulfills
its promise of democratic reforms.
   That implied a longer period for dismantling the rebel force and
greater linkage to reforms in Nicaragua than suggested by an
agreement the presidents of Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala,
Honduras and Nicaragua signed Feb. 14.
   Lopez Contreras urged the United States to continue humanitarian
aid to the Contras while they remain in Honduras.
   ``An armed group devoid of humanitarian assistance and
concentrated on our border is a great danger to the security of
Honduras,'' he told a news conference.
   The rebels are in the border province of El Paraiso in camps near
Yamales, about 280 miles from Tegucigalpa.
   A $27 million U.S. humanitarian aid package runs out March 31.
Some members of Congress have proposed linking more aid, which
President Bush says he will request, to the Central American summit
agreement. The United States halted military aid in February 1988.
   Central American presidents agreed at the February 13-14 summit
in El Salvador to develop a plan for dismantling the Contra force
and repatriating its members or relocating them, presumably outside
the region.
   They called for international verification of the accord, which
contains provisions for early elections and democratic reforms in
Nicaragua.
   Morris Busby, special U.S. envoy to Central America, met with
Lopez Contreras and President Jose Azcona Hoyo on Tuesday night and
told them the United States wants the Contras to return to
Nicaragua, the foreign minister said.
   ``Repatriation would benefit the Contras,'' Lopez Contreras said.
``It would benefit Nicaragua because it could achieve democracy as
the condition for repatration. And Honduras wouldn't have any more
armed groups or Nicaraguan refugees in its territory. So everyone
wins.''
   Barricada said Tuesday the Contras were moving deeper into
Honduras to avoid detection by international observers, who have not
yet been deployed. Contra leaders in Miami denied the report.
   On Wednesday, the paper said 6,000 Contras commanded by former
Col. Enrique Bermudez had moved out of the jungle camps to strategic
points on the border.
   It said they were preparing for ``offensive actions'' against
Nicaraguan targets, not demobilization. The Contras have not agreed
to the summit demobilization plan.
   Bermudez said during the summit that some rebels might return to
Nicaragua and continue the war even without U.S. military aid.
   The Contras and Sandinistas signed a temporary cease-fire a year
ago and comparatively little fighting has been reported since.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
