<FIRST>r w AM-Sullivan-Severance     03-08 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan-Severance,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Willing To Take Pay Due</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan said Wednesday he would ``readily reverse'' his decision to
forfeit nearly $300,000 in severance pay if Congress and the White
House determine the money would raise no ethical concerns.
   A Senate committee is looking into the matter with the White
House after members expressed concern that Sullivan was making an
undue sacrifice by his decison not to take the payment to avoid any
potential conflicts of interest.
   ``I would readily reverse that decision because, as some of them
put it, I'm not a wealthy man,'' Sullivan said in an interview with
The Associated Press.
   ``Certainly that's a benefit that's accrued over 13{ years that I
would certainly love to be able to enjoy, especially at this
particular time in this town.'' said Sullivan, whose annual salary
dropped from $172,000 last year to $89,500 in the new job.
   But Sullivan said he would not reverse his decision until the
after the Senate Finance Committee completes its review.
   The severance pay was earned under Sullivan's contract with the
Morehouse School of Medicine in Atlanta, which he founded. Upon his
confirmation to the Bush Cabinet last week, he stepped down as the
school's president and took an unpaid leave of absence as a
professor of medicine.
   He had asked permission to take a paid sabbatical while at HHS,
but the White House determined the school's policy on paid leave did
not meet government ethical standards.
   The Office of Government Ethics found no ethics problems with the
severance payment, but Sullivan decided to give up the money before
the White House position was formalized.
   Sullivan said his decision was in reaction to news reports at the
time that were raising questions about his request for a paid leave.
   Last week at Sullivan's confirmation hearing, members of the
Senate Finance Committee said the sacrifice was unnecessary, unfair
and could discourage others from taking government jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
