<DOCNO> AP890308-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     03-08 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dubcek Speaks Out Against Treatment of Dissidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek, the former Communist
leader of Czechoslovakia, attacked his country's recent jailing of
dissidents and said no reform in Czechoslvakia is possible unless
the events of 1968 are reviewed.
   As Communist Party chief, Dubcek led the liberal reforms known as
``the Prague Spring'' which were crushed by a Soviet-led invasion in
August 1968.
   In an interview broadcast Tuesday night, Dubcek was quoted as
telling the British Broadcasting Corp. and Voice of America radio:
``It is impossible to start out on a new road unless you have looked
at everything behind you.
   ``This refusal to look the truth about 1968 in the eye is
preventing the party and maybe the leadership ... from recognizing
that it is not possible to move forward with perestroika
(restructuring of society and the economy) until you fill in the
blank spots of history.''
   Dubcek was interviewed on Feb. 24 in Czechoslovakia. A transcript
of his remarks was made available Wednesday by the BBC in London.
   He was also quoted as criticizing the jailing of playwright and
human rights activist Vaclav Havel and others after anti-government
protests were put down by police in the Czechoslovak capital in
January.
   Dubcek called the unrest a ``surface phenomenon'' caused by ``the
burden of the last 20 years,'' according to the transcript.
   Havel was given a nine-month sentence on Feb. 21. Seven other
dissidents were tried that week. One was sentenced to a year in
prison, one to nine months, and five received suspended sentences
and fines.
   All seven were charged with hooliganism after they tried to lay
flowers in memory of Jan Palach, a Czechoslovak student who burned
himself to death in 1969 to protest the 1968 invasion and the death
of reform in his homeland.
   ``There is a serious issue here and that is that this legal
system here does not adhere to the democratic rules of the game or
to the democratic rules of law,'' Dubcek reportedly said.
   On Thursday, cultural activists Ivan Jirous and Jiri Tichy face a
court in the Moravian town of Jihlava in Czechoslovakia on charges
of anti-state activity that could jail them for up to five years.
   Milos Jakes, the current Communist Party leader, and other
prominent members of the Czechoslovak leadership continue to say the
1968 invasion was justified because Dubcek's reforms threatened the
socialist system.
   The refusal to re-evaluate was reiterated in an interview
published last month in the Soviet weekly Moscow News with Zdenek
Horeni, editor of the Czechoslovak party newspaper Rude Pravo.
   Moscow News editor Yegor Yakovlev had asked pointedly whether the
time had come to re-evaluate the events of 1968.
   ``Those events are over and done with. We will not return to
their reappraisal _ at any rate our generation,'' Horeni replied.
``There is no inner need for this.''
   Indications have grown in Soviet news media of some impatience in
Moscow with Prague's refusal to introduce more reform and with its
handling of the unprecedented week of anti-government protests in
Prague in January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
