<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Gregg-Sununu     03-08 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gregg-Sununu,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gregg Says Sununu Not To Blame For State's Cash Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMA LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unpredictable economy, not the
stewardship of former Gov. John Sununu is responsible for New
Hampshire's cash crisis, Gov. Judd Gregg said Wednesday.
   ``I was left with a very strong state, an extremely positive
fiscal situation,'' Gregg said.
   Gregg commented in response to reports that Sununu, now White
House chief of staff, left Gregg with the same financial problems
for which Sununu denounced Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis during
the presidential campaign.
   Sununu forecast a $10 million budget surplus in his departing
speech to the Legislature in January. Five days later Gregg warned
of a potential $13 million deficit when he cut most state spending 3
percent.
   The sudden turnaround prompted Democrats to accuse Sununu of
masking a deficit to make himself look good and Dukakis bad.
   The potential deficit was based on revenue projections that are
still in debate. Also, the Legislature under-funded several programs
last spring when it wrote a supplemental budget for 1989.
   Legislative leadership said then that better revenue and cost
estimates would be available in January to use in adjusting the
estimated $571 million general fund budget. A supplemental spending
bill to ensure the state ends the year in the black is still under
consideration.
   When it appeared agencies were spending more than legislators
estimated out of their 1988 budgets, Sununu privately twisted arms
last spring to produce $24 million in lapses, appropriated but
unspent funds.
   That left the state with a $13 million surplus last July 1.
   Usually criticized for being overly cautious in his revenue
estimates, Sununu says early receipts made him feel confident the
state would take in more revenues than estimated by the Legislature
in April. Gregg's January estimate also was lower than Sununu's.
   Sununu's estimate of how much agencies would return to the
treasury on June 30 also was higher than Gregg's.
   When Gregg announced the turnaround, he deducted for under-funded
programs and used revenue and lapse estimates that were $13 million
less than those projected by Sununu.
   Gregg said in an interview last month that Sununu ``still could
have been optimistic into December'' that his estimates were correct
``and if I were a departing governor, I suspect I would have been.''
   A key element in the equation are the lapses. In his six years in
office, Sununu's taskmaster style of management produced the results
he sought.
   In an interview last week, Sununu said he felt ``we still would
have been able to manage it'' and that based on revenue estimates
when he left, a small surplus would have been left even after those
bills he felt had to be paid were deducted.
   Though he warned aggressive management would be required to
ensure any of the $10 million was left on June 30, Sununu didn't
mention the debts when he talked about a surplus.
   Critics say that painted too rosy a picture, but Sununu says they
weren't listening closely.
   ``For folks to say I didn't say revenues were tight is just not
true,'' he says. ``I was the one who said it was going to be a
tough, tough biennium.''
   Gregg reiterated Wednesday that Sununu wasn't to blame.
   ``I don't point the finger of blame at anyone,'' he said. ``I
think we are caught in a situation where revenues are falling. It
was an unpredictable situation. I don't think it was poor
management.''
   Gregg praised fellow Republican Sununu and New Hampshire's
Republican-controlled Legislature for prudent use of state funds
during Sununu's three terms as governor.
   ``We had very good stewardship over the last six years,'' he said.
   Gregg said Sununu's criticism of Masschusetts was justified.
While New Hampshire spent supluses on one-time projects, such as the
land conservation program, Dukakis spent large sums on new programs
that have to be funded or cut in lean times, he said.
   Gregg predicted the universal health care program enacted by
Massachusetts ``is going to bankrupt that state in my opinion.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
