<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ParentalLeave     03-08 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Parental Leave,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Parental Leave Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee gave party-line approval
Wednesday to legislation that would require large employers to
provide up to 10 weeks of unpaid leave for parents to take care of
newborn or seriously ill children.
   The bill, a major part of congressional Democrats' domestic
agenda, also would require companies with 50 or more employees to
grant similar leave to workers who need extended time off to take
care of ailing parents.
   And it would require them to give up to 15 weeks of unpaid leave
for the workers' own serious illness.
   In each instance, the only direct cost to the employer would be
to continue whatever company-paid health benefits were in force at
the time the worker requested leave.
   However, many private and public employers, including the
National League of Cities, oppose the measure on grounds it would be
overly disruptive to their operations to hold jobs open for workers
requesting such extended leaves even though the direct financial
cost might be minimal.
   The measure cleared the House Education and Labor Committee on a
23-12 vote at the end of a daylong meeting in which the panel beat
back about two dozen Republican-sponsored amendments.
   The bill is expected to be scheduled for floor debate in May
after facing review by the House Post Office and Civil Service
Committee.
   Only two major amendments were adopted Wednesday _ one to include
congressional offices and another to exempt public elementary and
secondary schools from some of the measure's provisions.
   The amendment applying to public schools was sponsored by Rep.
Marge Roukema, R-N.J., who offered it at the urging of the National
School Boards Association.
   She read panel members a letter from the association in which it
agreed to drop its opposition to the overall bill if the amendment
it sought was adopted.
   Arguing that whatever was fair for public schools was fair for
private schools, Rep. Steve Bartlett, R-Texas, attempted to amend
Ms. Roukema's amendment to spell that out.
   He was defeated, 25-10.
   Later, Bartlett attempted to have the bill spell out that the
same special considerations that public schools could apply to
teachers on leave _ mainly special leeway in offering them
equivalent work, rather than the same work _ would extend to police
and fire departments and public health agencies.
   Again, he was defeated, 25-10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
