<FIRST>r i AM-ChannelTunnel     03-08 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Channel Tunnel,0140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protests Modify Rail Link To Channel Tunnel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-speed rail link from London to the Channel
Tunnel will be built underground and through deep surface cuttings
for two-thirds of its way because of environmental protests, British
Rail announced Wednesday.
   The state network bowed to a furious campaign by residents in
southeast London and picturesque Kent, who said demolition along the
68-mile route and the noise of trains would devastate their lives.
   The changes will increase the cost of the rail link project from
$2 billion to $2.9 billion, British Rail said.
   The route won't be ready until the late 1990s, so existing
railway tracks and lower speeds on the England side will have to be
used when the Channel Tunnel now being built to link England and
France opens in 1993.
</TEXT>
