<HEAD>Bush Goes To Play</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and his wife Barbara invited six
friends to the White House for dinner Wednesday night and then
whisked them to the Kennedy Center to see the comedy ``Steel
Magnolias.''
   It was his first trip to the theater since becoming president and
a rare outing from the White House for Bush, who originally had been
expected to have an active social life.
   The Bushes' guests, all longtime friends, were Mr. and Mrs.
Fitzgerald Bemiss of Richmond, Va., Mr. and Mrs. Walter Ganzi Jr. of
Washington and Dr. and Mrs. Tabb Moore, also of Washington. The
play, written by Robert Harling, is a portrait of six Southern women
whose lives intersect in a small town beauty shop.
   It stars June Lockhart, Barbara Rush and Carole Cook. The story
has been made into a movie with Dolly Parton, Shirley MacLaine,
Sally Fields, Darryl Hannah, Olympia Dukakis and Julia Roberts.
