<FIRST>r a AM-BurlingtonMayor     03-08 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burlington Mayor,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Socialist Mayor's Successor Says He'll Continue Similar Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor-elect Peter Clavelle promised
Wednesday to continue pushing the agenda of retiring socialist Mayor
Bernard Sanders, though perhaps with a lower voice.
   Clavelle, the city's director of economic development, won
election Tuesday under the banner of Sanders' Progressive Coalition
party, defeating a Democratic rival by a 53-to-42 percent margin.
   ``I think what the people of Burlington have said yesterday is
that we've had Progressive government for the past eight years, and
it's been good government,'' Clavelle said at a news conference.
   While eschewing the socialist label that made Sanders something
of a celebrity, Clavelle said in an interview that he favors such
leftist goals as workplace democracy and a shift from military to
social spending.
   ``Those who have the money and those who have the power tend to
represent themselves pretty well,'' Clavelle said, adding that he
sees the job of mayor as being the one who ``tips the scales just a
little bit'' toward those without money and power.
   Clavelle showed surprising strength in traditionally Democratic
and Republican wards in his victory over Democrat Nancy Chioffi. He
received 5,626 votes to her 4,400 votes.
   Two minor party candidates split a few hundred other votes.
   Clavelle, 39, is the grandson of French-Canadians who came south
to work in the woolen mills of neighboring Winooski. He said he gets
his politics from his working-class background, not from Marxist
theory.
   His term begins April 1.
   Sanders, 47, who ran unsuccessfully for governor in 1986 and for
Congress last year, announced in December that he would leave
politics to teach and write. He doesn't rule out another try for
elective office.
   He was first elected mayor in 1981 and won three subsequent
two-year terms. He is the only avowed socialist mayor in the nation.
</TEXT>
