<FIRST>u i AM-NorthernIreland 1stLd-Writethru   03-08 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0735,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bomb Kills Two Soldiers; Britain Says IRA Planning Bomb Blitz on
Mainland</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with two soldiers killed in bombing.
Pickup 2nd pvs, `Hurd's warning...'; EDITS thereafter to trim.</UNK>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two British soldiers were killed
and six others injured when a guerrilla land mine exploded under
their jeeps Wednesday night in Londonderry, Northern Ireland's
second-largest city, police reported.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility, but suspicion fell
on the Irish Republican Army, fighting British rule in Northern
Ireland.
   Sgt. John Brown, a police spokesman in Belfast, said the soldiers
were in a patrol traveling north out of the city in two armored Land
Rover jeeps shortly before midnight when a massive land mine
exploded.
   He said the second of the two jeeps took the main force of the
blast.
   Security forces sealed off the area after the blast.
   No other details were immediately available.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA wants to unite the predominantly
Protestant province with the 95 percent Catholic Republic of Ireland
under socialist rule.
   Earlier Wednesday, the IRA issued a statement saying two elderly
men killed a day earlier in a triple murder at a gas station were
slain by mistake. It said the targets were three Protestants
allegedly questioned by police about recent attacks on Roman
Catholics.
   In London, Home Secretary Douglas Hurd said the IRA plans a
bombing blitz in Britain using large quantities of explosives and
arms supplied by Libya.
   Hurd's warning followed discovery of an arms and explosives cache
at Scarborough, northeast England, that caused speculation the IRA
will try to kill Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher during a
Conservative Party conference there March 17-18.
   Party leaders confirmed Wednesday the meeting of the party's
national council would be held as planned at the Spa Conference
Center in Scarborough. Government sources said Mrs. Thatcher and
other Cabinet ministers were determined to defy the threat.
   An IRA bomb attack Oct. 12, 1984, at the annual Conservative
convention in the south coast resort of Brighton killed five people,
but Mrs. Thatcher was not hurt.
   While answering questions in the House of Commons, Hurd said:
``The Provisional IRA have a substantial amount of arms and
explosives which they got from Libya.
   ``These arms and explosives are concealed. They are being found
quite regularly in Ireland, north and south. Now they are being
found in London and north Yorkshire.''
   He said it was too early to tell if the arms were linked to an
IRA bomb factory police discovered Dec. 21 in Clapham, south London.
   Tom King, the Northern Ireland secretary, said: ``The intention
of the IRA is to kill, maim and murder wherever they find easy
targets and where carnage can be created.''
   He cited the latest discovery in proposing the annual renewal of
tough anti-terrorism measures for Northern Ireland. The vote to
renew was 239-118.
   In its statement about Tuesday's killings in Coagh village,
County Tyrone, the IRA said violin-maker Austin Nelson, 62, and
pensioner Ernie Rankin, 72, were shot down in the ``general
confusion.'' It said they had no paramilitary connections.
   The third man killed, station owner Leslie Dallas, was in the
Ulster Volunteer Force, an outlawed Protestant paramilitary group,
the IRA said.
   Two other men dived safely for cover. Police denied those men and
Dallas had been questioned about Protestant attacks, and said the
men named as the other two targets were not at the scene.
</TEXT>
