<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2252EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-VD     03-08 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-VD,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Says VD Cases Quadrupling Every Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of venereal disease cases in China has
quadrupled annually in recent years because of increased
prostitution, sexual freedom and contacts with the outside world,
China's official news agency said Wednesday.
   Xinhua News Agency said the problem is particularly serious
because the sexually transmitted diseases were practically
non-existent in China for decades, and few doctors know how to
diagnose or treat them.
   The report did not give any nationwide figures, but it said
National Disease Prevention and Research Center statistics showed an
average 312 percent annual growth in VD cases in recent years. It
did not say how many years.
   It said Canton, China's most open city because of its proximity
to Hong Kong, recorded 10,000 VD cases between 1984 and September
last year.
   The semi-official China News Service said Wednesday that a
1-day-old boy in Canton recently was found to have been born with
gonorrhea contracted from his father. It said he was the ninth child
in the city confirmed to be suffering from VD.
   According to statistics from venereal disease centers in 16
cities, 70.5 percent of sufferers are male. About 77 percent are
gonorrhea cases, while 16.77 percent are syphilis.
   The return of VD was attributed to greater sexual freedom that
has broken barriers against premarital sex, more contacts with the
outside world and the ``rampancy of prostitution'' in some areas.
   Xinhua quoted the daily Health News as saying some women are
becoming prostitutes simply to make money, while others are forced
into prostitution by gangs and some are frustrated in love and
ignorant about sex.
   Before the Communist takeover in 1949, an estimated 10 million
people in in China had VD, 500,000 in Shanghai alone.
   But the Communist government eradicated prostitution in the early
1950s, and in the early 1960s it claimed that VD no longer existed
in China.
   Health News said that because China was VD-free for so long,
chapters on the diseases were left out off medical books and doctors
are not able to recognize or treat them. Fake medicine dealers and
charlatans are exploiting some people afraid to go to hospitals with
their problems, it said.
   In the past few years, China has set up 192 treatment and
prevention agencies throughout the country and established a
national center in Nanking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2254EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FirefightersKilled 1stLd-Writethru a0805 03-08 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Firefighters Killed, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0805,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Firefighter Dies; Two Critically Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Firefighter ..., to CORRECT name to Jeffrey,
sted Jeffery.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KO3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 4-year-old boy playing with a heater
accidentally set a fire Wednesday that engulfed a wood frame house
and triggered an explosion that killed one firefighter and
critically burned two others, officials said.
   Authorities said the ``flash over'' _ a detonation of gases
produced by combustion _ pushed the temperature in the house to over
1,000 degrees, melting the clothes and protective gear off the three
firefighters.
   Firefighter Jeffrey N. Lindsey, 23, a four-year veteran whose
brother helped fight the same fire, was the first Oklahoma City
firefighter to die while fighting a fire since 1950, Fire Chief Tom
Smith said.
   Bennie D. Zellner, 44, and Jimmy L. Ayers, 46, were hospitalized
in critical condition with second- and third-degree burns covering
70 percent to 90 percent of their bodies, officials said. Two other
firefighters sustained minor injuries.
   ``The heat was so bad it disintegrated everything they were
wearing,'' said Dr. Peter Silverstein of the Baptist Medical Center
burn center, who estimated their exposure at 1,000 degrees. Smith
said the temperature was probably even higher.
   ``These guys are young, healthy men, and we expect that their
vital organs will give us a good fight and keep going,'' Silverstein
said. ``Physiologically they stand the best chances of anybody of
surviving.''
   The fire in a frame house in southwest Oklahoma City was started
in a closet by a child who was playing with wood in an open-faced
heater, fire officials said.
   Smith said the child's mother tried to put the fire out with
water before going to neighbors' homes to call the fire department.
   The fire chief said the three firefighters were wearing full
protective gear, but that the explosive intensity of the fire was
too hot for it to prevent the burns.
   ``There is nothing on the market that would have protected them
under those conditions,'' he said.
   Officials said American and state flags at all the fire stations
were lowered to half-staff Wednesday in honor of Lindsey.
   Smith said funeral services have not been scheduled for Lindsey,
who is survived by his wife Melissa Lindsey, who is expecting their
first child.
</TEXT>
