<FIRST>r a AM-Iditarod 1stLd-Writethru a0740 03-08 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iditarod, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0740,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Champion Dog Sledder Presses for Lead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with afternoon developments; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>McGRATH, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Declaring that she must ``do everything
right from here on in,'' Susan Butcher prepared to leave here late
Wednesday afternoon in her quest for a fourth consecutive victory in
the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race.
   Butcher reached McGrath, 407 miles into the race, at 8:17 a.m.
Wednesday, about 15{ hours after Joe Runyan of Nenana became the
first musher to arrive in the Kuskokwim River community.
   Butcher was followed by four-time Iditarod winner Rick Swenson in
the No.3 position at 10:05 a.m. Dee Dee Jonrowe and Martin Buser
completed the top five, arriving in McGrath at 10:11 a.m. and 11:03
a.m., respectively. Another 10 mushers in the field of 45 pulled
into McGrath by late afternoon.
   Runyan said he would stay in the village for the 24-hour layover
required in the course of the 1,168-mile race from Anchorage to
Nome. Completing the layover meant Runyan was unable to leave
McGrath before 4:43 p.m. Wednesday.
   Twelve of the mushers still in the race Wednesday had not taken
their layovers. Many, including Butcher, completed them at Rohn.
   Butcher said the number of teams leading among the 45 still in
the race hadn't thinned as much as she expected. She also said she
believed the frantic pace Runyan set had sapped his dogs.
   ``It took him 15 hours to cross the (Farewell) Burn,'' she said.
``It took me only 10.''
   Forty-nine mushers left the Iditarod starting line Saturday in
Anchorage. Three dropped out relatively early in the race and a
fourth, David Aisenbrey, added his name to the scratch list
Wednesday. Officials at the Iditarod headquarters in Anchorage said
they did not know the reason for Aisenbrey's withdrawal.
   The annual Iditarod began 17 years ago and was inspired by a 1925
relay of serum to Nome during a diphtheria outbreak. The race, which
carries a $250,000 purse, is put on largely by volunteers.
   Gov. Steve Cowper has been among them, but he said Wednesday that
he no longer has the time to offer his services. Nonetheless, he
made it to Nikolai, the checkpoint before McGrath, to see some of
the activity.
   ``A lot of the mushers are pretty good friends of mine from way
back,'' Cowper said. ``I love this race and I'd do anything I can to
promote it.''
   The governor said musher and Iditarod founder Joe Redington, No.
14 in the rankings Wednesday afternoon, has offered to provide him
with a dog team if he wants to compete some year.
   ``That may be a little ways down the trail, as they say,'' said
Cowper, who is serving his first term. ``It probably won't work
until I leave my present employment.''
</TEXT>
