<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Arms     03-08 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Arms,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arms, Explosives Found Near Thatcher Conference Venue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Monday cq in 5th graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police reported on Tuesday the discovery of an arms
and explosives cache near the northeast seaside resort of
Scarborough, where Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher is to address a
political gathering next week.
   The newspaper The Independent said in its Wednesday issue, early
copies of which were available Tuesday night, that police believe
the discovery may have foiled a new attempt by the Irish Republican
Army to kill Mrs. Thatcher.
   The Times of London described the find as ``a substantial IRA
terrorist cache.'' It said the discovery highlighted police fears
that the IRA had re-established on the British mainland with plans
for an extensive campaign.
   Mrs. Thatcher survived an IRA bombing on Oct. 12, 1984 in which
five people died at the Conservative Party's annual convention at
the south coast resort of Brighton. The blast partly demolished the
hotel in which Mrs. Thatcher, many of her Cabinet members and many
prominent Conservatives were staying.
   North Yorkshire police said guns, ammunition, 25 pounds of Semtex
explosive and other bomb-making materials were found on Monday
buried in woodland near a road by a man gathering leaf mold for his
garden.
   Deputy Chief Constable Frank Morritt said he could not discount a
link between the find near Scalby village, two miles outside
Scarborough, and Mrs. Thatcher's visit to Scarborough for the March
17-18 national council conference of her governing Conservative
Party.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting British rule in
Northern Ireland. It wants to unite the Protestant-led province with
the 95 percent Catholic Republic of Ireland under socialist rule.
</TEXT>
