<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Tibet 2ndLd-Writethru a0791 03-08 0896</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tibet, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0791,0919</SECOND>
<HEAD>Travelers: Chinese Pulled Tibetans From Homes; Arms Smuggling Alleged</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: 5 grafs SUB for grafs 4-5 pvs, There were ... UPDATING with
China says separatists smuggled in arms, issues further martial law orders.
Picks up 6th graf pvs, The foreigners ... with minor editing to trim</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHENGDU, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces dragged Tibetans from their
houses Wednesday as thousands of Chinese troops took up posts around
Lhasa after three days of anti-Chinese riots, travelers said.
   By official count, 12 people had been killed and more than 100
wounded in violence since Sunday when Tibetans marched in Lhasa,
demanding an end to nearly four decades of communist rule and the
return of their spiritual leader, the Dalai Lama. Travelers quoted
Tibetans as saying the actual death toll was much higher.
   The Dalai Lama's government-in-exile in India offered to hold
talks with China to discuss the future of Tibet. The Chinese Embassy
in New Delhi refused comment.
   China on Thursday accused Tibetan separatists living abroad of
smuggling weapons into Tibet and instigating riots in Lhasa, the
Tibetan capital. In a commentary, the official Xinhua News Agency
also defended China's human rights record in Tibet, saying it is
those opposed to Chinese rule who trample on the rights of the
Tibetan people.
   Foreign witnesses to this week's rioting said they saw no
Tibetans with weapons.
   China also announced further martial law orders: all foreigners
must report to police; Tibetans harboring criminals must turn them
in, and People's Armed Police will continue to suppress and root out
separatists.
   No reports surfaced of further demonstrations or gunfire on
Wednesday and early Thursday, but Westerners in Lhasa said troops
filled the streets.
   Beginning at midnight Tuesday, trucks with loudspeakers drove
through the city of 70,000 announcing martial law was in effect and
ordering Tibetans to stay inside, said foreign travelers, most of
whom spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The foreigners gave the following account:
   Dozens of trucks packed with soldiers entered the city and troops
_ some drinking beer _ set up checkpoints 15 miles outside Lhasa and
at nearly every block in the city. Soldiers stopped all but official
vehicles and arrested Tibetans in the streets.
   ``They were just collaring people ... and stuffing them into
jeeps,'' said an American.
   Tibetans screamed with fright as Chinese troops pulled them from
their homes.
   ``These were women's voices,'' said an Australian. ``The truck
kept coming back. They would pick up a couple people, drive off with
a half-dozen militia holding them down, then come back.''
   It was not known who the people were, why they were picked up or
how widespread the roundups were because the foreigners were
confined to their hotels. But foreigners contacted at several hotels
said they saw police raiding the homes of ordinary Tibetans along
the streets in front of their hotels.
   Mobs led by Tibetan youths ransacked Chinese shops in three days
of rioting through Tuesday, and a European traveler said not one
Chinese-owned shop in the old quarter of the city escaped damage.
   The estimated 150 foreigners in Lhasa have been ordered to leave
the city by noon Thursday, but they were forbidden Wednesday to
leave their hotels to buy tickets.
   Tourists said they were given a choice of going to Nepal by bus,
going to other cities in Tibet or flying to Chengdu.
   One traveler said soldiers stopped her and five others from
catching a chartered bus for Nepal. Officials later told her they
had arranged another bus to the border but wanted $4,185, three
times the previous price, she said.
   ``They can shoot people and arrest people, but getting you a
ticket and helping you change money is beyond their capacity,'' said
one American.
   The travelers spoke in telephone interviews from Lhasa to
Chengdu, the capital of neighboring Sichuan province and one of the
few points of entry to the remote Himalayan region.
   Police detained two British reporters overnight. Jasper Becker of
the Guardian newspaper said he and a reporter for the Reuters news
agency were released Wednesday after being questioned, with
authorities most concerned about photographs.
   One Swiss who refused to turn over his film Sunday said police
beat him and pointed a gun at his head. He said the police still had
his camera and passport and wouldn't return them until he hands over
the film and pays a fine. He said he was not injured.
   Three Swedes and an American who also took pictures were given
back their cameras and passports after they paid fines.
   The imposition of martial law marked the first time Chinese
authorities had taken the step anywhere since the 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution.
   Authorities apparently took the measure to prevent demonstrations
on Friday, anniversary of the failed uprising that led the Dalai
Lama to flee to India in 1959.
   The violence that began Sunday was the fourth clash in 18 months
between Chinese security forces and Tibetans. Troops were not
deployed in the previous episodes, in which at least 40 Tibetans and
police were killed.
   China claims Tibet has been part of China since the 13th century.
But many Tibetans maintain the territory was an independent nation
before the communists took over in 1949.
   In New Delhi, the Dalai Lama's government-in-exile said it was
ready to work for a peaceful solution to the unrest.
</TEXT>
