<FIRST>u a AM-Measles-Tournament     03-08 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Measles-Tournament,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Measles Outbreak Makes Basketball Tournament a Box-Office Bust</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LIGHTFOOT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The organizers of a college basketball
tournament stand to lose up to $50,000 this week because a measles
outbreak has forced them to hold the games in an empty 15,000-seat
arena.
   Officials at the host University of Hartford have juggled
schedules, canceled events and asked fans to donate the cost of
their unused tickets. But despite their efforts, the event's winners
_ who must bear the greatest share of the loss _ could be financial
losers.
   ``If I was to put ink to paper right now, I'd estimate those
losses are going to be $30,000 to $50,000,'' University of Hartford
Athletic Director Don Cook said Wednesday.
   The tournament, to pick the winner of the East Coast Athletic
Conference's North Atlantic Conference, is scheduled to start
Thursday and end Sunday.
   A Hartford basketball player's case of measles and an outbreak of
the highly contagious disease on the campus of Siena College,
another NAC member, prompted the spectator ban.
   Hartford, as host, is fronting the money for the tournament. Any
losses will be reimbursed from proceeds the winning team receives
from the National Collegiate Athletic Association. The winner
receives an automatic bid to the NCAA tournament worth just more
than $250,000 this year, Cook said.
   The first priority in distributing the $250,000 is
administrative. The winning team gets 50 percent of the balance, and
the remaining 50 percent is shared by the other nine member schools.
   Cook said organizers would have a better estimate of losses once
they know how many of Hartford's 2,000 season ticket-holders ask for
refunds on their $18 tournament tickets.
   ``We've had people who have donated their tickets or their
money,'' he said. ``We've had others that ask for refunds.''
   Meanwhile, tournament organizers have done their best to see that
no one else gets the measles.
   Players will be met by a tournament delegate at their hotel and
led through a service entrance into the Civic Center, where the
games will be played, Cook said.
   Reporters covering the tournament will be asked to prove they've
been immunized against the disease; if not, they'll receive
vaccinations on the spot.
   For fans, it will be a bleak three days, with just one bit of
consolation: Saturday's championship game will be televised on ESPN.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
