<FIRST>u i AM-Greece     03-08 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Calls Scandal a Conspiracy, Denies Involvement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELENA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou on Wednesday
denied any involvement in a financial scandal rocking the country
and called it an international conspiracy to topple his Socialist
government.
   In a 15-minute televised address to the nation, Papandreou also
said he will sue the U.S. news magazine Time for defamation, both in
Greece and abroad, over an interview it carried with the fugitive
banker George Koskotas.
   ``I felt the need to communicate with you because for the first
time in my political life my character is being doubted. ... I want
to make clear that not a trace of the mud that is flying from all
quarters involves me,'' the 70-year-old leader said.
   In the magazine report, Koskotas, the former chairman of the
privately-owned Bank of Crete, accused Papandreou and other senior
Socialist leaders of demanding and receiving millions of dollars in
payoffs from his bank.
   The 34-year-old banker, who rose to fame creating a publishing
empire in just four years, fled the country in November after being
indicted in the $200 million fraud, forgery and embezzlement scandal.
   Time ran the story in its March 13 issue following a series of
six interviews with the financier in a Boston prison, where he is
awaiting an extradition hearing scheduled for March 16.
   ``Time is a magazine of the American establishment. ... Now we
can see clearly which forces are hiding behind the attempts to
uproot democracy in our country,'' Papandreou said in the address.
   Papandreou added that the attempts to overthrow his government
will continue up until the June 1989 general elections.
   The Koskotas affair has spurred both the Conservative and
Communist opposition parties to call for the leader's immediate
resignation.
   The government has also come under increasing attack from members
of the ruling Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK) for its
handling of the scandal. In the five months since the scandal first
emerged it has triggered the resignations of seven Cabinet members.
   Although the government has maintained from the start that the
allegations were part of a domestic and foreign-inspired plot to
usurp Papandreou from power, it has avoided naming the forces behind
it.
   Recent opinion polls have indicated that Papandreou's popularity
has declined sharply in the past six months because of his highly
public extramarital liasion with a former air hostess.
   The premier, who underwent open heart surgery in London last
fall, made the address from his suburban home in Kastri. He has been
living with his 34-year-old girlfriend in a nearby villa since his
return from the British capital.
   Papandreou's televised address was delayed when journalists went
on a three-hour strike. The walkout was called by the Union of
Athens Journalists at the two state-run television channels to
protest the government's alleged monopoly of the medium and the
behavior of state officials toward the news media.
</TEXT>
