<FIRST>r a AM-WrongRescue     03-08 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wrong Rescue,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vandals Mistake MIA `Rescue' Group for Anti-Abortion `Rescue' Organization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GARDEN GROVE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals targeting an anti-abortion
group also have been hitting an organization with a similar name
that is dedicated to gathering information on servicemen missing in
Southeast Asia.
   The office of Operation Rescue Inc., the missing-in-action group,
and the office of Operation Rescue of Southern California, the
anti-abortion group, were vandalized late Sunday night or early
Monday.
   The vandals left wire coat hangers, silhouettes of people in red
spray paint and leaflets stating ``Operation Rescue Operation
Death.''
   ``They think we're this other group,'' said Krista Eppley,
spokeswoman for the MIA group, Operation Rescue Inc., which was
founded in 1983. She said there have been other misdirected
hostilities over the last two months.
   ``The phone messages have been all fairly radical, real ugly and
threatening,'' she said Monday.
   Police Lt. Stuart Finkelstein said the vandals have not been
identified, and said the damage was under investigation as malicious
mischief.
   Operation Rescue of Southern California, part of a national group
that demonstrates at clinics where abortions are performed, opened
an office here in January.
   Ms. Eppley said she's asked the anti-abortion group to change its
name.
   ``We've been around for a long time; it's not like we're some new
kid on the block,'' she said. ``I don't want to have to worry about
some weirdo shooting at me.''
   Kenneth Tanner, the anti-abortion group's director, apologized
for the other group's distress but said the name would not be
changed.
   He said the telephone company has been asked to clarify the
directory listing and that the group is also planning to move to
another city.
   ``We sympathize with them and feel really bad,'' he said.
``Hopefully, whoever is responsible for this will realize what a
foolish mistake they made.''
