<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS boy's name to Felipe, sted Felix in Ashlock obit. Separates
moved for AMs on Pelat as a0740, a0653 on Andrews, a0771 on Ashlock and
as a0785 on Kossman.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Roger-Patrice Pelat</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roger-Patrice Pelat, a longtime friend of President
Francois Mitterrand, died Tuesday of a heart attack, three weeks
after he was charged in an insider trading scandal that has
embarrassed France's Socialist government. He was 70.
   Pelat and Mitterrand met in a German prisoner-of-war camp in 1940
and later fought together in the French Resistance.
   On Feb. 16, Pelat, was charged with receiving insider information
that allowed him to buy shares of the U.S. company Triangle
Industries Inc. shortly before the French state-owned aluminum
manufacturer Picheney SA offered a much higher price last year in a
successful takeover. Pelat and his family sold their shares after
the price soared, making a profit of about $350,000.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Harry Andrews</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harry Andrews, a craggy, jut-jawed character actor
who specialized in military roles, died Monday at age 77.
   Andrews made his stage debut at age 21 and had many Shakespearean
roles, including Horatio in ``Hamlet'' in New York in 1936. He made
his first movie in 1952, opposite Alan Ladd in ``The Red Beret.''
   Andrews' is most remembered as the tough warden of a British army
prison who played opposite Sean Connery in the 1965 film ``The
Hill.'' His towering physique and growling voice made him a natural
for the part of a general in ``The Battle of Britain'' in 1969, but
he also showed a comic flair as the campy older man in 1970's
``Entertaining Mr. Sloane.''
   In 1985, Andrews was asked to play a single-episode deathbed
scene as Blake Carrington's long-lost father in ``Dynasty.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Donna Ashlock</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PATTERSON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donna Ashlock, the teen-ager who
received a dead admirer's heart when her own failed, died in her
sleep Tuesday while awaiting a second transplant.
   Ashlock's body had repeatedly tried to reject the heart of
15-year-old Felipe Garza Jr., which she received after Garza died in
January 1986. She was waiting for a new heart when she died while
taking a nap.
   Ashlock's case drew international attention when it was reported
that Garza, who had a crush on his high school classmate, had told
his parents he wanted to leave her his heart after his death.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Jacob Kossman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacob Kossman, a lawyer regarded by court
friends as a legal genius whose list of clients included prominent
mob figures Angelo Bruno and Albert Anastasia, died Sunday at age 79.
   Among those Kossman represented were James Hoffa, the late
president of the Teamsters Union; Anastasia, the former head of what
was known as Murder Inc.; and Bruno, the Philadelphia mob boss who
dined with Kossman the night Bruno was gunned down in front of his
home.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Donald Phillips</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald E. Phillips, 85, a former reporter and
founder of the University of Arizona's news bureau, died Thursday
after a series of strokes.
   Phillips attended the University of Arizona and worked for the
Tucson Citizen before graduation. Upon graduation in 1928, he worked
for the Arizona Daily Star in Tucson until 1934, when he became
Tucson correspondent for United Press.
   Phillips also corresponded for the New York Times, Aviation
Magazine and Science Service. He founded the university's press
bureau in 1936.
   In 1938, Phillips organized the the Border Conference Press
Association. He was part of a network which set up national football
statistics for colleges.
   Survivors include his wife, Cecil, and several neices and
nephews.
</TEXT>
