<DOCNO> AP890308-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-FetalResearchEthics Adv13   03-08 1085</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fetal Research Ethics, Adv 13,1115</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday PMs, March 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tissue from Aborted Fetuses at Center of Scientific, Ethical Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The use of aborted fetuses is redefining the ground rules of
medical research, pitting scientists who hope to alleviate suffering
against ethicists who fear the specter of Nazi-style experimentation
on unwilling subjects.
   Critics of fetal tissue research envision abortion-for-profit
from tissue sales and foresee organ ``parts shops'' in hospitals.
Proponents counter that researchers are steering a morally neutral
course.
   Can science separate the use of human material from the way it
was obtained? That central ethical question of the Nuremburg medical
trials following World War II is being raised again over fetal
tissue research, a new frontier of medicine.
   ``The only answer to this obviously is the answer ... which our
whole culture is in anguish over: Are these people (fetuses) human
beings?'' said the Rev. Richard John Neuhaus, a Lutheran theologian
who was among more than 500 signers of an interfaith letter urging
the federal government to ban funding for research using
intentionally aborted fetuses.
   ``If we learned anything from the medical trials at Nuremberg, it
is that science is not in itself good. It can be used for good or
evil,'' said Richard Doerflinger, associate director of the Office
of Pro-Life Activities of the U.S. Catholic Conference. ``Our point
is, the way science is implemented has to respect human dignity.''
   On the other side there are human concerns, too.
   For decades, a 52-year-old patient of Dr. Curt Freed has suffered
from degenerative Parkinson's disease but now, after implants of
fetal tissue to the brain, the man is improving, said Freed of the
University of Colorado Health Sciences Center in Denver.
   The implants may alleviate the sudden loss of function and other
symptoms that Parkinson's sufferers endure. ``They may find
themselves frozen sitting in church, for example,'' Freed said. ``It
would be that kind of phenomenon, eliminating freezing episodes.''
   A special National Institutes of Health advisory committee
decided last December it would be ``acceptable'' for the federal
government to back medical research involving the transplant of
tissue of intentionally aborted fetuses.
   And a month later, at the annual meeting of the American
Association for the Advancement of Science, Stanford University
President Donald Kennedy classified right-to-life advocates who
would ban all research with fetal tissues as among ``the enemies of
scientific progress.''
   Researchers hope that transplanting fetal cells into people with
diabetes and Parkinson's disease may provide an effective treatment,
and also see the potential such research has for similarly treating
other serious diseases such as Alzheimer's.
   Tissue can be obtained elsewhere, including from the patient's
own body, but some experts say fetal tissue has the advantages of
eliminating the need for surgery on the patient to gather the tissue
and its immaturity may make it more adaptable.
   ``We must separate the issue of abortion from medical research,''
said the chairman of the NIH advisory committee, retired federal
appeals Judge Arlin M. Adams of Philadelphia.
   The committee recommended guidelines such as prohibiting profits
from the sale f fetal tissue, but the panel's majority opinion was
that the ethics of where the tissue was obtained largely should not
be considered.
   If not used, fetal brain cells and other tissues would simply be
discarded, say many researchers who see no reflection of the moral
abyss of the Nazi era.
   ``From my perspective, the bottom line is, once a woman decides
she's going to have an abortion ... I just don't understand why it
(fetal tissue) shouldn't be used,'' said Dr. Myron Genel, a
professor of pediatrics and an associate dean of the Yale School of
Medicine.
   ``I say this as one who had a substantial number of my family
destroyed in the Holocaust.''
   To others, it's impossible to distance the act of abortion from
the use of resulting fetal tissue.
   ``It's as separate as me being here and you being there and we
being held together by only the one bullet which I have just
fired,'' said the Rev. James Burtchaell, a member of the NIH panel
who dissented from its report. ``It's an absurd claim.''
   Burtchaell, a professor of moral theology at the University of
Notre Dame, said government sponsorship of fetal tissue research
would be the most powerful expression of public approval of abortion
since the Supreme Court's decision in Roe vs. Wade.
   The ambivalence and misgivings that make the abortion decision so
painful for some women ``could easily be relieved by the
rationalization, yes, this is a tragic thing, but some good could
come out of it,'' Burtchaell said.
   If the research becomes profitable, ethical concerns may be
forgotten, Neuhaus added.
   ``Health is big bucks, superbucks, mega bucks. ... There are few
things Americans are willing to pay more for than health for the
prolongation of life,'' he said. ``The commercial dynamics are
powerfully on the side of blocking out moral reflection. It is not
in any way far-fetched to envision that in not too many years every
hospital will have a parts shop.''
   Arthur Caplan, director of the Center for Biomedical Ethics at
the University of Minnesota, sees a ``vexing moral problem'' with
using aborted fetal tissue and believes research must be closely
regulated.
   Fetal tissue should be handled, he said, through a third-party
system like that used for organ donations.
   Such donations are regulated to separate the physicians awaiting
the organ from the patient's treatment, in order to assure the
patient, as Caplan put it, ``I'm not trying to kill you to get your
parts.''
   It also is no longer simply academic speculation that someone
might create life to destroy it for valuable tissue, Caplan said.
``I know of three people who have been willing to get pregnant to
donate tissue either to themselves or a family member.''
   Rabbi James Rudin of the American Jewish Committe, who serves on
the New York State Task Force on Life and the Law, finds compelling
arguments on both sides.
   Rudin said he has no objection to the use of fetal tissue for
medical research, but he is worried that the practice may encourage
abortions and eventually may lead to poor women selling fetal tissue.
   ``I was raised where science was going to answer all our
problems,'' Rudin said.
   But science per se is neutral, Rudin said. ``Our moral and public
policy guidelines are just now catching up with what we're capable
of doing.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, March 13</NOTE>
