<FIRST>r f BC-Parretti-Hollywood     03-08 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Parretti-Hollywood,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Financier Denounces Report of Money Laundering, Mafia Ties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Giancarlo Parretti, the Italian financier
trying to assemble a Hollywood movie powerhouse, denounced news
reports suggesting he has been involved in money laundering and has
ties to the Mafia.
   Parretti, who with a partner has in recent months bought
controlling interests in the Cannon Group Inc., New World
Entertainment Inc. and Pathe Cinema of France, said in a news
release that the money for the purchases came from legitimate
sources.
   Reports in the trade and financial press have questioned the
source of Parretti's money, as he and his partner, Florio Fiorini,
invest with the avowed goal of becoming a significant force in
Hollywood.
   A Business Week magazine article March 13 quoted unidentified
associates of Parretti and Fiorini as saying the pair's network of
foreign holding companies include money-laundering operations. The
magazine said associates of Fiorini have warned him that Parretti
has ties with Sicilian crime families.
   ``The article makes untrue and baseless accusations of money
laundering,'' Parretti said in his news release Monday, citing
outside audits of his companies. ``The suggestion of supposed `close
ties with Sicilian crime families' is slanderous and totally false.''
   The magazine's editor in chief, Stephen B. Shepard, responded in
a statement: ``We have nothing to add except to note that Business
Week already printed Mr. Parretti's denial in our story.''
   Parretti, through an employee, refused an interview request
Tuesday.
   Parretti, born in Orvieto, Italy, has been charged with criminal
offenses twice in that country and jailed briefly, according to
Business Week and an article last week in the Wall Street Journal.
   He was acquitted of charges that he defrauded a bank that failed
in Palermo and is awaiting trial on charges stemming from alleged
misstatement of the balance sheet of his soccer team, Siracusa
Calcio in Sicily, the magazine said.
   Additionally, Parretti was arrested in Rome in 1986, but the
extortion charge was dropped, Business Week said.
   Parretti says he and his partner intend to assemble their various
movie assets into an entertainment conglomerate under the name Pathe
Entertainment. It will be headed by moviemaker Alan Ladd Jr., who
brought ``Star Wars'' to the screen, they say.
   Through holding companies, Parretti and Fiorini control Melia
International, a Spanish travel agency, and Renta Inmobiliaria, a
Spanish real estate firm. Separately, Fiorini is part-owner of
Sasea, a Swiss merchant bank.
   They recently bid $22 million for De Laurentiis Entertainment
Group Inc., which is in Chapter 11 federal bankruptcy proceedings,
and have hinted interest in MGM-UA Communications Co. Reported
prices for the pair's recent acquisitions include $150 million for
Pathe of France and $138 million for New World.
   Financing for the recent acquisitions was arranged through Credit
Lyonnais of France and public and private equity and revenue from
the pair's various firms, Parretti said.
</TEXT>
