<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     03-08 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0897</SECOND>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge refused to order Eastern Airlines
pilots back to work, although Eastern warned it couldn't otherwise
survive the 4-day-old Machinists strike. A spin-off job action by
pilots nationwide failed to clog airports as feared.
   Earlier Tuesday, Eastern sent 2,500 more non-union workers home,
blaming pilots for leaving it with ``no business on the books.''
   Company attorney David Ross warned during a court hearing that
Eastern was faced with bankruptcy without its 3,600 pilots, who have
firmly refused to cross picket lines the Machinists union set up
Saturday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American workers' productivity rose a barely
perceptible 0.1 percent from October through December while unit
labor costs, a major inflation measure for business, shot up at an
annual rate of 5.6 percent, the government reported.
   The figures released Tuesday by the Labor Department confirmed an
initial report by the department a month ago which showed that
productivity, or output per hour of work, turned sluggish in the
final three months of the year while inflationary pressures
intensified.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Senate Banking Committee told
savings and loan officials they had lost their credibility after the
executives asked Congress to reduce the industry's contribution to
its own rescue.
   The presidents of the U.S. League of Savings Institutions, the
industry's largest trade group, and the National Council of Savings
Institutions said Tuesday the plan proposed by President Bush
threatens the health of solvent S&amp;Ls.
   However, members of the committee told the lobby groups their
influence had waned. Sen. Richard Shelby, D-Ala., noted the league
had in the past tried to play down S&amp;Ls' poor condition.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. stock soared amid speculation that an
outside bidder might offer the media giant a more lucrative deal
than its planned $18 billion merger with Warner Communications Inc.
   Time stock shot up $9.25 a share Tuesday to close at $116.75 in
heavy New York Stock Exchange trading.
   However, analysts doubted a bid would materialize, and predicted
the merger would go through.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Justice Department's antitrust
division has vowed to take a harder look at proposed airline mergers
now that the Transportation Department has given up that job.
   Assistant Attorney General Charles F. Rule said Tuesday the
antitrust division has a broader perspective and greater legal
powers to conduct merger reviews than the Transportation Department,
whose authority lapsed last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 670 production workers from Lockheed Corp.
will be loaned to Boeing Co. to help build Boeing's new 747-400, the
world's largest passenger jet, Boeing said.
   Boeing said Tuesday it was nearing final agreement with Lockheed
on an ``industry assist contract'' that would bring experienced
Lockheed workers to the 747-400 production line in Everett for up to
six months.
   Lockheed, a major aerospace defense contractor based in
Calabasas, Calif., stopped making commercial jets in the mid-1980s.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. gave checks of about $2,800
each to more than 152,000 employees, the second-highest
profit-sharing payment in auto history.
   The Ford payments handed out Tuesday far outpaced those of
General Motors Corp. and Chrysler Corp., which will distribute their
profit-sharing checks later this month. GM has said its typical
worker will receive $254 and Chrysler's average profit-sharing check
will be about $720.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government pressure forced Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. to agree to dismiss bond trader Michael Milken and withhold his
pay as part of a landmark securities fraud settlement, the head of
the investment firm said in court papers.
   This was the first time Drexel Chief Executive Frederick H.
Joseph publicly asserted the firm opposed parts of the $650 million
criminal plea agreement reached in December.
   The documents were filed Tuesday in Manhattan federal court as
part of a challenge by Milken and his brother, Lowell, also a Drexel
executive, to provisions of the criminal settlement that capped a
two-year investigation of securities law violations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrialized nations committed themselves to
banning chemicals destroying the ozone layer, but they reacted
coolly to Third World demands for money to find substitutes.
   China, India and other populous developing nations embarking on
mass production of consumer goods containing chlorofluorocarbons
reason that since the West invented and produces most of the
ozone-destroying chemicals, the West should pay to replace them.
   Despite the split, the 123 countries at an international
conference on the ozone layer agreed Tuesday that pressure is on
scientists and industry to find safe alternatives before more damage
is done to the fragile atmospheric shield.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted a small loss Tuesday after the Dow Jones
industrial average made a short-lived run past the 2,300 level. The
average fell 4.11 to 2,290.71.
   The dollar rose against most foreign currencies.
   Bond prices fell slightly as traders awaited Friday's release of
February unemployment figures.
   A resurgence of commercial and speculative buying pushed platinum
futures prices to a 3-month high, boosting gold and silver futures
as well; crude-oil futures tumbled; soybeans retreated; grains were
mixed; cattle futures advanced; and pork futures fell.
</TEXT>
