<DOCNO> AP890308-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel     03-08 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drexel Chief Executive Cites Government Pressure To Fire Milken</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. opposed part of the
Wall Street firm's landmark securities fraud settlement but went
along with it out of fear the government would bring more serious
charges, Drexel's chief executive is quoted as saying in court
papers.
   Drexel agreed to dismiss bond trader Michael Milken and withhold
his pay depite the company's disagreement with the terms, Chief
Executive Frederick H. Joseph said in a separate filing Tuesday.
   It was the first time Drexel publicly asserted that the firm
opposed parts of the $650 million criminal plea agreement reached in
December.
   Lawyers for Milken said Joseph told employees that Drexel settled
because the government planned to bring charges under the federal
Racketeer Influenced and Corruption Organizations act that could
have frozen billions of dollars of the firm's assets.
   The documents were filed in Manhattan federal court as part of a
challenge by Milken and his brother, Lowell, also a Drexel
executive, to provisions of the criminal settlement that capped a
two-year investigation of securities law violations.
   ``They were going to indict us under RICO ... (and) there would
be a multihundred-million-dollar forefeiture,'' Joseph said Jan. 6
in a telephone hookup with employees, papers filed by the Milkens
stated.
   ``We ultimately concluded the bottom line was the firm absolutely
had to settle _ that a financial institution cannot stand up to a
RICO indictment,'' he stated, according to the court papers.
   The plea agreement forces Drexel to dismiss Michael Milken and
withhold his more than $100 million in 1988 pay and keep at least
half of Lowell Milken's pay and fire him if he is indicted.
   Joseph said in an accompanying affidavit that the Milken
provisions ``were initiated by the government and inserted in the
plea agreement at the government's request.''
   He said Drexel opposed the action but took them ``in order to
reach an overall agreement with the government.'' He said Drexel
would be willing to pay the Milkens if not for the pact.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Carroll said the government would
have no comment on the filings. A hearing on the Milkens' motion is
set for March 14.
   One week ago, Joseph filed a supporting affidavit for the
government in the same case, admitting that Drexel ``entered into
the plea agreement voluntarily and without coercion after consulting
with counsel.''
   The government has said the possibility of indictment on more
serious charges does not constitute coercion and that Drexel was not
threatened with RICO charges during negotiations.
   The Milkens are asking U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood to reject
or modify the settlement, under which Drexel has agreed to pay $650
million in fines and restitution and plead guilty to six felonies,
because it violates the Milkens' rights.
   To show Milken was under contract with Drexel, his attorney
Tuesday submitted a 1975 agreement _ still in effect last year _
stating the high-yield ``junk'' bond trader is entitled to a minimum
of 15 percent of any profits under $1 million to 35 percent of
department profits over $8 million.
   Michael Milken is one of the biggest targets of a federal
securities fraud crackdown and is expected to be indicted on fraud
and racketeering charges. He was named in a civil suit filed by the
Securities and Exchange Commission against Drexel last September but
faces no criminal charges and has denied any wrongdoing.
   The criminal plea cannot take effect until the SEC settles civil
charges with Drexel. Negotiations are continuing.
</TEXT>
