<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UniversalFoods     03-08 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Universal Foods,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Favorable Ruling In England Boosts High Voltage Takeover Hopes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A favorable ruling by the London Stock Exchange
won praise from High Voltage Engineering Corp. but was dismissed as
``an interesting sidelight'' by the company's takeover target,
Universal Foods Corp.
   The London exchange decided Tuesday that Berisford International
PLC, a British food company financing High Voltage's $643 million,
$35-a-share bid for Milwaukee-based Universal Foods, does not have
to ask its shareholders to approve its role in the takeover.
   ``We're very excited,'' said Clifford Press, deputy chairman of
High Voltage.
   Press said that, in light of the decision, High Voltage and
Berisford are considering changing a provision under which a change
of ownership of High Voltage or Berisford would allow the other to
purchase the stake in Universal Foods.
   Press said the attempt to bring Berisford into the takeover
action has been ``a complete sideshow, a desperate effort (by
Universal Foods) to avoid dealing with us. We're pleased it's been
put to bed.''
   But Paula Norton, a Universal Foods spokeswoman, discounted the
impact of the Berisford decision.
   ``Berisford's problem with its shareholders is an interesting
sidelight,'' she said. ``But it's just that; it's peripheral to the
issues being decided by Judge (Joseph) Stadtmueller.''
   She was referring to High Voltage's effort to get Universal
Foods' anti-takeover defenses overturned in U.S. District Court in
Milwaukee.
   High Voltage launched the takeover attempt for Universal Foods in
December. The Burlington, Mass.-based company is owned jointly by
Berisford and two New York investors.
   Universal Foods, seeking to have the High Voltage takeover
attempt halted, has argued that Berisford failed to reveal its exact
role in the takeover bid, in violation of the requirements of the
U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Universal Foods stock closed Tuesday at $34.75 a share, up $1.50,
on volume of 514,800 shares.
   Berisford also said Tuesday that it hopes to renegotiate its
partnership with Hyde Park Holdings of Massachusetts. Berisford and
Hyde Park own equal stakes in High Voltage.
   The decision to seek changes in the partnership accord was
Berisford's first public response to complaints from Associated
British Foods PLC, which owns a 24 percent stake in Berisford.
   Associated British Foods argues that the partnership accord may
constitute a so-called poison pill that would discourage any company
considering a takeover of Berisford.
   Associated British Foods also has sought to have Berisford submit
details of its role in the Universal Foods bid for shareholder
approval.
</TEXT>
