<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time-Warner Bjt   03-08 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Warner, Bjt,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Stock Soars As Takeover Rumors Abound</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street analysts have dismissed rumors that
Time Inc. might receive a takeover bid more lucrative than the media
giant's planned $18 billion merger with Warner Communications Inc.
   But investors were captivated by the idea of a possible outside
offer, and bid Time stock up $9.25 a share Tuesday to $116.75 in
heavy New York Stock Exchange trading. Warner, meanwhile, rose 62{
cents to close at $48.87{.
   Time has been the target of persistent takeover rumors, but the
analysts rejected the latest talk and predicted the company's plans
to merge with Warner through an exchange of stock would go through.
   ``It would be puzzling that anyone would necessarily (make a bid)
now, because of the discount value (Time has) traded at for years,''
said Mary Kukowski, an analyst with Bear Stearns &amp; Co. ``There's
been a window of opportunity and no one did it before, so why do it
now?''
   Jay Nelson, an analyst with Brown Brothers Harriman Inc., said
``the odds are better than 50-50'' against a bid, partly because of
the anti-takeover atmosphere in Washington after the late 1988 wave
of multibillion-dollar leveraged buyouts.
   Members of Congress and the Bush administration have suggested
steps be taken to curb takeovers following the record $24.53 billion
buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc. by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   Big buyouts financed through heavy borrowing, such as the RJR
Nabisco deal, are seen as un-American, Nelson said, while Time and
Warner ``are positioning the deal as pro-America and pro-business.''
   ``If I read Congress correctly, they would prefer to see someone
run the business and not break it up and lay off employees,'' Nelson
said. Time and Warner say no jobs will be lost as a result of their
merger, and that the combined company will be better able to compete
with other international media giants.
   Although investors focused Tuesday on Time, they continued buying
stock in other media companies, whose stock prices rose sharply
Monday in industry-wide takeover speculation.
   Gulf &amp; Western Corp., owner of Paramount Pictures Corp., rose
$1.25 to $47.12{ a share Tuesday, while MCA Inc. rose $1.25 to close
at $54.25.
   CBS Inc., which soared $6 on Monday, finished down $2.12{ at $170
on Tuesday.
   Other questions about the Time-Warner merger lingered, such as
the possible opposition of Chris-Craft Industries Inc., Warner's
largest shareholder.
   When the Warner board voted 12-0 with one abstention to approve
the merger, Chris-Craft Chairman Herbert J. Siegel was the
abstaining director, according to a Warner source who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Siegel, who has bickered with Warner Chairman Steven Ross for
years, has kept an uncharacteristically low profile since the
Time-Warner deal was announced. He did not return a reporter's
telephone calls seeking comment on the merger.
   Chris-Craft acquired its stake when it helped Warner fight an
unwanted takeover by media giant Rupert Murdoch in 1984, but Siegel
tried to stop Warner's recent acquisition of Lorimar Telepictures
Corp. In the past, he and Ross argued about the makeup of the Warner
board and the size of Ross' salary.
   But analysts, noting that Siegel's power will be diluted in the
merger, said he won't be able to stop the deal.
   Warner officials say Siegel's stake in the new company will
decline to 6 percent to 7 percent from his current 11 percent Warner
share, while the amount of shareholder votes he controls will drop
to 14.2 percent from the 17 percent he controls at Warner.
   Chris-Craft stock closed down 12{ cents a share at $33.37{
following a $3.75-a-share rise on Monday.
</TEXT>
