<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0252EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TimeWarner-Cable Bjt   03-08 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time Warner-Cable, Bjt,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critics Say Time Warner Merger Could Reduce Variety on Cable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The proposed merger of the media giant Time Inc.
and entertainment producer Warner Communications Inc. could lead to
fewer programming choices on their huge cable system operations,
critics say.
   Both companies own cable systems that are among the five largest
in the nation. The combination would rank second behind the biggest
cable operator, Tele-Communications Inc.
   The proposed Time-Warner combination could ``diminish the free
flow of information,'' said Andrew Schwartzman, executive director
of Media Access Project, which describes itself as a public interest
law firm.
   He said Tuesday that the combined cable operations may turn to
the programming produced by sister businesses at Warner _ which has
major movie and television production operations _ rather than buy
it from independent producers.
   ``It will affect the prices paid for programming and the variety
and diversity of programming that is available and impair the
ability of other companies to come in and compete effectively,''
Schwartzman said.
   Tom Rogers, president of NBC Cable, the General Electric Co.
division that is preparing to launch a new cable network, Consumer
News and Business Channel, said the merger could make it tougher to
get a big audience for CNBC.
   Rogers said cable systems with 12.5 million subscribers already
have signed up for CNBC, ahead of earlier projections for the
service's launch.
   But he said Time has refused to put the service on its cable
systems, adding that could be because Time has the right to take
over another cable service, Cable News Network, if CNN's owner,
Turner Broadcasting Corp., is sold.
   ``If Warner is merged into Time, that is 5.5 million subscribers
that are outside CNBC distribution,'' he said.
   Michael Luftman, a spokesman for Time's American Television and
Communications Corp., said it was premature to speculate how the
combination would affect programming choices.
   But he said that once the merger is completed, the cable systems
will be run fairly autonomously even though one person will oversee
both of them.
   Paula Greer, an analyst for the media research firm Paul Kagan &amp;
Associates of Carmel, Calif., said the combined cable operation
probably would be able to command a cheaper rate for programming
than the systems paid as separate entities. She said there also may
be economies of scale in combining some of their administrative
operations.
   She said the combination extends a trend toward consolidation in
the cable business, which has raised concerns that the operators,
who have been freed from federal rate regulation, will boost their
prices.
   Those fears were not borne out last year, the first year of full
rate deregulation, when the average basic cable rate rose about 10
percent, down from a 19.7 percent rise the previous year, she said.
   Time owns 82 percent of American Television, based in Stamford,
Conn. It is the second-biggest cable system operator, with about 4
million basic subscribers.
   Warner Cable Communications, based in New York, has about 1.5
million basic subscribers and ranks fifth among operators.
   But a combined Time Warner cable company still would trail
Denver-based TCI, which has about 9.7 million subscribers. That
figure includes its share of subscribers to systems in which it has
a part interest, Kagan said.
   Officials of Time and Warner told securities analysts earlier
this week that they anticipated no serious antitrust problems with
their merger, which was announced Saturday. The merger requires
stockholder approval.
   They said Time Warner may have to sell American Television's
cable system in Southern California, which has 30,000 subscribers,
because of Warner's minority interest in BHC Inc., which owns
television station KCOP in Los Angeles.
   The government prohibits companies from operating a television
station and a cable system in the same market.
</TEXT>
