<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ProfitSharing     03-08 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Profit Sharing,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Checks Given To Ford Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-two Ford Motor Co. employees got a
little extra along with their profit-sharing checks _ a brief chat
with the company's vice chairman.
   Harold Poling dropped by Ford's sprawling Rouge complex on
Tuesday to hand out profit-sharing checks of about $2,800 apiece to
workers at the Dearborn assembly and stamping plants.
   Poling chatted briefly with Betsy Cole, a Ford employee for 16
years, who's been at the Dearborn assembly plant for 13 of them.
   ``I told him I was going to put it down on a new car,'' she said
after talking with Poling. She said she hasn't decided which car she
would buy, but it definitely would be a Ford.
   A little further down the line, Joe Hines got his check and told
Poling it would go for his daughter's college tuition. Hines, 62,
has been a Ford employee for 35 years.
   And before heading to the line, Poling gave a check to Fred
McNulty of Garden City, who's been working at Ford's Dearborn
assembly plant for 25 years.
   ``I already put it in a money market account,'' he said. ``I've
always have put it in a money market.''
   Poling said that if a Ford employee had been around to collect
all six profit-sharing checks the automaker has issued, the worker
would have received about $12,200.
   ``Despite my reputation as a cost-cutter, I'm a strong believer
in profit sharing, count on it,'' he said before his stroll by an
assembly line on which new Mustangs rolled past.
   More than 152,000 workers received their checks Tuesday. The
amount was the second-highest in auto industry history and far
outpaced those of General Motors Corp. and Chrysler Corp., which
will distribute their profit-sharing checks later this month.
   GM has said its typical worker will receive $254, while
Chrysler's average check will be about $720.
   Profit-sharing among each of the nation's Big Three automakers is
based on financial performance in their North American operations.
Profit for those activities must reach certain levels for
profit-sharing to kick in.
   Ford and GM began distributing profit-sharing checks in early
1984, and Ford has continued every year since.
   GM, which will mail this year's checks March 14 to about 450,000
hourly and salaried workers, had no profit-sharing payments in 1987
or 1988.
   Chrysler will distribute its profit-sharing checks Friday to more
than 82,000 hourly and salaried workers. The No. 3 automaker didn't
begin profit-sharing payments until this year, but handed out $500
checks to employees in each of the past two years in lieu of profit
sharing.
   Last year, Ford provided about $3,700 per employee in
profit-sharing, the largest in the five-year history of the payments
by automakers. The lowest amount Ford workers have received was
about $400 each in 1984.
   While some Ford employees celebrated this year's profit-sharing
checks with dinners or long-planned purchases, others never will see
the money.
   Last year, in an agreement between Ford and the Wayne County
Friend of the Court, the company withheld profit-sharing checks for
more than 2,300 employees who were behind more than $500 in
child-support payments.
   For the most part, though, Tuesday was a happy day at Ford
factories.
   ``It makes the whole year worth it,'' said Reginald White, a
quality upgrader at the Dearborn assembly plant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
