<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0729EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-08 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Down On News Of New Scandal Arrests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index fell today
after word of new arrests in a major stock-profiteering scandal, and
the dollar fell against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 61.08 points
Tuesday, fell 100.28 points, or 0.31 percent, closing at 31,837.66.
   After gains in early trading, news of the arrests discouraged
investors, said a dealer with Nomura Securities, Japan's largest
brokerage.
   Prosecutors today arrested former Labor Ministry official Takashi
Kato, 58, for allegedly receiving bribes from the employment
information conglomerate Recruit Co. Former Recruit executive Masao
Tatsumi, 46, was arrested for allegedly offering bribes.
   This brought to 12 the number of arrests in the case.
   The scandal, uncovered last fall, has shaken the government of
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita. Three Cabinet ministers, including
Finance Minister Kiichi Mitazawa, have resigned in connection with
the affair.
   ``The news of Wednesday's arrests contributed to the downtrend
because trading already was becoming unstable without incentives for
buying,'' the Nomura dealer said.
   ``Institutional investors, who have big influence on the
direction of trading, lost buying interest, which caused the losses
in the afternoon,'' said the dealer, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Investors also were waiting for February's U.S. unemployment
figure, due to be announced Friday, the dealer added.
   In active trading, with sell orders outweighing buy orders,
volume traded on the first section was estimated at 1.2 billion
shares.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar ended at 128.73 yen,
0.30 yen lower than Tuesday's 129.03-yen finish. The dollar opened
at 128.68 yen and ranged between 128.65 yen and 128.90 yen.
   ``The dollar-yen rate has hardly moved since around 10 a.m.,''
said a dealer with Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo, also requesting
anonymity.
   He also cited caution before announcement of the U.S. jobless
figures.
   Meanwhile, Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita told a news
conference today that he did not see foreign exchange rates as
likely to fluctuate widely, but added that the central bank was
prepared to ``take appropriate measures'' if rates showed
significant changes.
</TEXT>
