<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     03-08 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was little changed in light European
trading early today.
   Gold prices were higher.
   Dealers said they expected the dollar to trade within a narrow
range for the rest of the day.
   ``It's purely a technical market today,'' said a trader at a
major West German bank in Frankfurt. ``The dollar is desperately
searching for a trend, but can't find one.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.30 Japanese yen to a closing 128.73 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 128.55 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.8527 West German marks, up from 1.8520; 1.5830
Swiss francs, down from 1.5847; 6.2952 French francs, down from
6.3000; 2.0905 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0945; 1,361.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,362.37; 1.2005 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1985.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7225 from $1.7220 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $391.75 a troy ounce, up
from $391.45 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $393.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $392.70, up from $390.90 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $4.74 to close at a bid $388.21.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $5.89 a troy
ounce, up from $5.88 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
