<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-FlightAttendants 1stLd-Writethru f0020 03-08
0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Flight Attendants, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0020,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Want Ad Draws Applicants Despite Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, Never mind, to update number of employees furloughed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Tired of the nine to five grind? See more of
the world in a month than most people see in a lifetime,'' the
help-wanted ad said.
   The job? Flight attendant at Eastern Airlines.
   Never mind that the nation's seventh-largest airline has
furloughed 9,500 employees, grounded almost all of its flights and
is teetering on the brink of ruin.
   Approximately 20 young men and women showed up at a Washington
hotel on a cold, snowy Tuesday to answer the ad that appeared in
Sunday's Washington Post.
   The Eastern official who did the interviewing, Jeff Bowen,
insisted the ad was not placed in anticipation of the strike that
hit the airline Saturday.
   ``What we are doing is trying to fill the commitment we made in
the newspaper ads, rather than lock the door. We had no idea we
would be faced with this situation,'' Bowen said.
   Members of Local 533 of the Transport Workers Union, which
represents the flight attendants, scoffed at the claim.
   ``They're hiring scab flight attendants to replace us,'' said
Teal Carter, a stewardess with Eastern for five years, as she
picketed outside the hotel.
   Judy Coughlin, secretary-treasurer of the local, said Eastern
conducted similar interviews in Miami on Sunday and Monday and in
Boston on Tuesday and planned to do so in New York today.
   ``We are meeting these people at every hotel,'' Ms. Coughlin
said. ``We have had great success in convincing people to turn away.
We handed them a flier and told them about other airlines that were
hiring flight attendants and would pay them more money, and we said
please come back some day when things are better at Eastern.''
   The pickets drew the support of Local 25 of the Hotel and
Restaurant Employees Union, which represents workers at the
Washington Hilton hotel, where the interviews were held.
   Ron Richardson, executive secretary-treasurer of the local, said
he telephoned William H. Edwards Jr., general manager of the hotel,
Monday night and ``asked him to throw Eastern out of there.''
   ``His response was that they had already rented the place, and
they couldn't legally get out of it, but that it was just that one
morning, and he did not think they would be back,'' Richardson said.
   ``It is strange for a union company to hold a meeting of that
nature in a union hotel,'' said Edwards. ``It was a situation that
they could have avoided. I don't foresee it happening again.''
   Peter Chatilovicz, labor counsel for the Washington Hotel
Association, said he spoke with Eastern's lawyers about the matter
Tuesday.
   The job-seekers, meanwhile, were mostly oblivious to the furor
over Eastern.
   ``I want a job,'' said a young woman who would identify herself
only as Barbara. ``I really didn't know about the controversy that
was going on.''
   She said company interviewers did not talk to her about the union
or tell her that people were being laid off. She also said she was
not given encouragement that she would get a job.
   Dennis Jones, an unemployed Washington resident, said he was not
aware that Eastern had been struck and was furloughing employees. He
said he just wanted to work for an airline.
   ``We are not passing out applications,'' said Bowen. ``We are
just trying to get an idea of those individuals who would be
interested in working for Eastern in the event that we had to do
some replacement of flight attendants.''
</TEXT>
