<FIRST>r f BC-PSGroup-Barkley     03-08 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PS Group-Barkley,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chief of PS Group Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Barkley, the president and chief executive
of PS Group who helped guide Pacific Southwest Airlines through the
deregulation of the airline industry, announced that he will resign
in April.
   ``It's time to give it to another generation,'' Barkley said
Tuesday. ``I had a contract that said I could go home when I was 60.
I will be 60 next month, so I'm going home.''
   PS Group's board of directors named George Shortley as Barkley's
successor. Shortly, 48, joined PSA in 1968 as controller and
currently serves as executive vice president of the firm.
   Barkley will remain a member of the board of directors of PS
Group and chairman of its exeucitve committee.
   PS Group was the parent company of PSA until it sold the San
Diego-based carrier to USAir last year. PS Group then emerged as a
``liquid investment company'' that is building one of the nation's
largest travel networks as well as leasing aircraft and selling fuel
to U.S. airlines.
   Barkley ``quietly led the company and kept it stable during the
deregulation period,'' said Russell Ray, former PSA president who is
now the vice president for commercial marketing for Douglas Aircraft
Co.
   ``I'm happy for the calm, but it certainly isn't the same world''
as the heated days of cut-throat competition in the deregulated
airline industry, Barkley said. ``It was a tough business to be in,
but it was exciting and dramatic.''
   The most difficult year in PSA's history was 1978, the year that
deregulation was announced, he said.
   A collision over San Diego that year involving a PSA jet and a
private plane killed 144 people, including 37 PSA employees.
   Fuel prices began to climb in 1978, prompting PSA to make the
tough choice of buying a new fleet of aircraft for short flights to
replace its gas-guzzling 727s.
</TEXT>
