<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-NoodleBuyout     03-08 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Noodle Buyout,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cookie Giant Buying Out Local Noodle Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOLUCA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tortellini, ravioli and manicotti will soon
be added to the cookies, crackers and snacks sold by Keebler Co. if
the proposed buyout of a Toluca-based frozen pasta manufacturer goes
through as planned.
   Keebler has signed a letter of intent to purchase Bernardi
Italian Foods _ a family business which traces its roots to 1932 and
a small restaurant run by the son of Italian immigrants.
   Today, Bernardi employs about 120 people in the production of
about 40 varieties of fresh and frozen pasta which it distributes
nationally and in Canada.
   ``They are going through our books right now and we're supposed
to close the deal in mid-April,'' Jerry Bernardi, chief executive of
the pasta company, said Tuesday.
   Terms of the proposed sale were not disclosed.
   ``But nothing is going to change here,'' Bernardi said. ``It's
going to be business as usual and everything will remain under the
Bernardi label. We will be a subsidiary of Keebler, operated
independently. My son, Dick, and I are even going to continue to run
it.''
   Keebler spokesman Stuart Greenblatt, at company headquarters in
the Chicago suburb of Elmhurst, said the purchase of Bernardi was
tentative and requires the approval of Keebler's parent company,
United Biscuits (Holdings) PLC of London.
   Greenblatt said the acquisition would give Keebler, which ranks
second to Nabisco with $1 billion annual sales of cookies, snacks
and crackers, a foothold in the lucrative and growing pasta food
market.
   ``I wouldn't say we're looking to get into frozen pasta,''
Greenblatt said. ``Bernardi's is a good fit with our current food
service operations. And we have a frozen snack bread product so
we're already into frozen foods.
   ``But this would be our first pasta operation.''
   Bernardi's interest in the pasta business dates back to 1932 when
his father, Nildo ``Mona'' Bernardi, opened a restaurant in Toluca,
a town of 1,500 located about 40 miles north of Peoria.
   Bernardi, 58, joined his father in the restaurant and in 1969, he
bought a machine that automatically makes the family specialty:
tortellini.
   The machine allowed Bernardi to replace five women who produced
about 150 pounds of tortellini each week by hand _ production the
machine could match in one day.
   Bernardi began mass-production of the pasta in an old
meat-packing plant and in 1980 entered the frozen-food business,
marketing his product under his father's nickname ``Mona's.''
   Along with frozen tortellini, Bernardi's menu includes
pre-cooked, filled pastas, such as ravioli and manicotti. Other
items include lasagna and rotini and raw pastas such as egg noodles,
fettuccine and gnocchi.
   The company also sells its own line of entrees with sauces.
   Bernardi originally sold tortellini and other pasta primarily to
area restaurants, school cafeterias and private institutions.
   ``Italian food and pasta has become extremely popular,'' Bernardi
said. ``In the last two years, the growth has been tremendous.''
</TEXT>
