<FIRST>r f PM-BiosphereTest 1stLd-Writethru f0036 03-08 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Biosphere Test, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0036,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biologist To Be Housed For Five Days in Closed Ecosystem</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-3 to CORRECT that Earth, not module, is Biosphere
I.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORACLE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When biologist Abigale Alling steps inside
an airlock, she'll begin a stay in what eventually will be a new
world on Earth.
   Starting late today, Ms. Alling is scheduled to live for five
days inside a self-contained environment _ a completely closed
ecosystem independent of the air, water and nutrients of Earth,
which researchers call Biosphere I.
   Her five-day stay in the module is a precursor to a two-year stay
in a larger and more complex version of the airlock, or Biosphere II.
   Project spokeswoman Kathleen Dyhr said researchers hope Ms.
Alling's five days in the airlock will have no startling
developments.
   In similar but shorter experiments, ``nothing dramatic happened,
which is exactly what we wanted,'' she said. ``Nothing unusual goes
on, and then that's normal.''
   Ms. Alling, a 29-year-old design coordinator for the Biosphere II
project, will be monitoring and studying the various systems that
control the environment inside the sealed 15,000-cubic-foot
glass-and-steel space-frame structure. Project managers on the
outside will be doing the same.
   Ms. Alling's heart and respiration rate and other vital signs
also will be monitored during her five-day stay.
   ``I will be breathing air that is apart from Earth. Water
recycling will be apart from Earth. This is really a milestone,''
Ms. Alling said.
   The nearly 2.5-acre, 7-million-cubic-foot Biosphere II is under
construction, and in September 1990, eight researchers called
``biospherians'' will be sealed inside for two years.
   The aim will be to see whether man can exist in a complex and
evolving but completely enclosed world. Biosphere II will have seven
separate environmental systems, including a tropical rain forest,
marsh, and desert. About 3,800 plant and animal species are being
selected for the project.
   ``Learning how to do a better job of stewardship of Biosphere
I,'' will be the ``big payoff of Biosphere II,'' said Carl Hodges,
director of the University of Arizona's Environmental Research
Laboratory and a consultant on Biosphere II. Such global problems as
air pollution, acid rain and the greenhouse effect would be some of
the issues studied, he said.
   The $30 million Biosphere II project is being undertaken by Space
Biospheres Ventures, a private company funded largely by Texas
oilman Edward P. Bass.
   There have been 2{ years of unmanned studies and a three-day
manned study in the test module.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0247 </DOCNO>
