<FIRST>r f PM-S&amp;L-SanFrancisco     03-08 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;L-San Francisco,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Francisco FHLB Will Back Bush S&amp;L Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Home Loan Bank of San Francisco
said it would support the Bush administration's so-called fallback
financing plan for insolvent savings and loans.
   Only two weeks ago, directors of the San Francisco bank had
voiced opposition to the plan to offer emergency funds, fearing
insolvent S&amp;L's might not be able to pay back the money.
   But a spokeswoman for the bank said Tuesday that ``directors had
been talking with Washington to get clarification on the plan and
today that clarification was received.''
   The bank said in a brief statement that it ``has agreed to
participate with other Federal Home Loan Banks in the shared lending
program with the Federal Reserve Banks.''
   Under the plan, the U.S. Treasury, the nation's 12 Federal
Reserve banks and the 12 Federal Home Loan banks would make the
loans if there were a run on desposits at insolvent thrifts.
</TEXT>
