<FIRST>r f PM-Microsoft 1stLd-Writethru   03-08 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Microsoft, 1st Ld-Writethru,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Microsoft Stock Plunges On Lower Earnings Forecast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 new grafs after 4th graf pvs with additional comment;
picks up 5th graf pvs, `In heavy...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDMOND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Microsoft Corp.'s stock plunged nearly 14
percent in heavy trading after the personal computer software
publisher announced it expects lower sales and profits for its third
quarter, ending March 31.
   The stock sank $8.50 a share to $53.50 Tuesday and was the most
actively traded over-the-counter issue, with more than 5 million
shares changing hands.
   Microsoft blamed the lower forecast on delays in shipments and
overstocking by key distributors.
   ``This came as a nasty surprise. We can't tell how serious it is
yet,'' said James Mendelson, a stock analyst with Morgan Stanley &
Co. in New York.
   Microsoft President Jon Shirley said, ``Customer demand for our
broad range of products remains good,'' and better results are
expected in the final quarter.
   Buck Ferguson, director of administration and investor relations
for Microsoft, said investors overreacted.
   Bill Whitlow, a securities analyst with Dain Bosworth, and Teresa
Lotzgesell, an analyst with Ragen MacKenzie Inc., agreed.
   ``None of this is a reflection of the company's position or its
products,'' Whitlow said.
   In heavy over-the-counter trading, Microsoft was off $8 a share
at $54 late in the session, a drop of nearly 13 percent.
   In a news release, Microsoft predicted third-quarter sales of
$180 million to $200 million, down from the $200 million to $215
million expected by many market analysts.
   Microsoft had sales of $161.8 million for the third quarter of
last year and profits of $37.3 million. The company said it expected
profits for the current quarter ``to be somewhat less than a year
ago.'
   Shipments of Microsoft's new versions of its word-processing
program, Microsoft Word 4.0 for Apple Macintosh and Word 5.0 for
IBM-compatible computers, were delayed and strong demand caused the
company to run out of stock for current versions of both, Microsoft
said. It said the new versions should be shipped next month.
   Overstocked distributors are reducing their inventories, and
demand for other Microsoft products remains good, said Microsoft
President Jon Shirley. ``The shipping of both new Microsoft Word
versions and the inventory reductions will improve our results in
the next quarter,'' he said.
</TEXT>
