<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-High-DefinitionTV 1stLd-Writethru f0022 03-08 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High-Definition TV, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0022,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mosbacher Says Private Industry Must Take Lead in High-Definition
TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with testimony; picks up 2nd graf pvs, If
the, removing pvs graf 4, The House, as outdated. ^By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher told
Congress today that private industry, and not the government, must
take the lead in developing high-definition television production in
this country.
   Mosbacher said HDTV sales in this country could reach $140
billion in the next 20 years and that the impact of HDTV will go far
beyond entertainment uses. He cited potential advances in education,
retailing and the military and said the United States must take a
leading role in this developing industry.
   But the private sector should remain ``pre-eminent'' in this
effort, he said, and any U.S. funds that are expended for research
in HDTV should go to the domestic industry and not to foreign
competitors.
   ``In my view the private sector must take the lead...and we're
the ones who will be getting the hindrances out of the way,'' he
said.
   He suggested the government role could include tax incentives and
possible antitrust exemptions for U.S. manufacturers of HDTV
products. He said development of a government policy in this regard
has the ``highest priority'' at the Commerce Department and that he
expects to be able to make a recommendation to Congress on the
government role in the next two months.
   A private study released Tuesday said the United States must move
aggressively into the new high-definition television and flat-screen
display industries or lose more than 2 million jobs annually and
suffer a $225 billion trade deficit in electronics by the year 2010.
   If the United States does not compete effectively with the
Japanese and other nations in the high-technology arena, the
personal computer and semiconductor industries alone could have
respective deficits of $114 billion and $76 billion early in the
next century, the report from the Economic Policy Institute said.
   Its author, Robert Cohen, said: ``Our nation stands at a critical
juncture. If we do not create a strong industrial base centered on
development of HDTV and flat-display screen technology, it will not
only weaken our industrial base, but also reduce the numbers of
skilled jobs that are needed to make us more competitive.''
   Proponents of HDTV claim it can provide motion picture-quality
images on flat television or computer screens using digital
components.
   Japan expects to have an HDTV system in full operation by the
mid-1990s, whereas the U.S. telecommunications industry has barely
begun testing of HDTV technology.
   The U.S. Defense Department is soliciting bids for companies to
share in a $30 million HDTV research and development program.
   Cohen said HDTV technology will improve the entire ``food chain''
in the electronics industry.
   ``HDTVs will be used in the home, as display screens for personal
computers, and by the nation's businesses to improve controls over
automated production in auto, steel and manufacturing plants, to
integrate video and print media in newspapers, and for the
collection and transmission of important medical results such as
X-rays and computer tomographs,'' Cohen said.
   He said he based his study on findings recently released by the
American Electronics Association. According to the AEA study, a
``strong'' scenario represents a case in which 50 percent of the
U.S. market for HDTV is controlled by U.S. companies. In a ``weak''
scenario only 10 percent of the U.S. market would be controlled by
U.S. concerns.
   Cohen said that with a strong HDTV base the U.S. personal
computer industry would attain an estimated $176 billion in sales by
2010, in contrast to an expected $44 billion in sales with a weak
HDTV sector.
   In the semiconductor industry, sales would be $99 billion in a
strong U.S. HDTV industry compared with $25 billion in a weak
industry.
   The trade imbalance in electronics could range from an estimated
surplus of $10 billion under a strong HDTV program to a $227 billion
deficit with a weak HDTV program, Cohen said.
   In the employment area, the personal computer industry could have
588,000 employees in 2010 under a strong HDTV scenario, or 147,000
employees under a weak HDTV program, he said.
   In all related industries, including HDTV receivers and VCRs,
automated manufacturing equipment, personal computers and
semiconductors, there could be nearly 1.1 million jobs under a
strong scenario and 274,000 jobs under a weak program.
   Cohen said spinoff employment from a strong HDTV program could
create another 1.1 million jobs _ even more if flat-screen display
technology is used extensively in retailing, education or in
automobile assembly.
   The Economic Policy Institute is a labor-backed think tank based
in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   03-08 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Trade Mostly Lower On Slack Demand, Mild Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were trading
mostly lower this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting
slack demand and forecasts for milder weather in the Midwest and
Great Plains.
   Pressure on the soybean market also stemmed from lower cash
prices domestically and lower values for soybean meal and oil on
overseas markets. But analysts said losses in the soybean oil market
were limited by perceptions that Morocco and Pakistan may be in the
market for U.S. soybean oil.
   The corn and wheat markets also declined amid slow export demand
despite rumors of new Chinese or Soviet buying interest in wheat.
   An expected warm-up to springlike conditions in the nation's
midsection also weighed on grain futures by reminding traders that
spring planting and increased barge shipping are not far away.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 1 cent lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.33 a bushel; corn was \ cent to
1} cents lower with March at $2.76{ a bushel; oats were { cent lower
across the board with May at $2.13} a bushel; soybeans were { cent
to 3} cents lower with March at $7.60{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were narrowly mixed in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .10 cent lower with April at 77.57
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent lower to .13 cent higher
with March at 81.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent lower to
.13 cent higher with April at 44 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .25 cent lower to .25 cent higher with March at 38.85 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures settled lower on Tuesday while pork futures
advanced.
