<FIRST>r f BC-Pepsi-MadonnaAds     03-08 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pepsi-Madonna Ads,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepsi Changes Plans To Run Madonna Ad On MTV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pepsi-Cola Co. changed its plans to run its new
two-minute commercial with pop star Madonna on MTV last weekend
after the cable network started running the singer's potentially
controversial new music video, a source close to the soft drink
maker confirmed Wednesday.
   The Pepsi ad with Madonna, which was dubbed ``Make a Wish'' and
included an abbreviated verision of her new song ``Like a Prayer,''
debuted last Thursday on what Pepsi said were top-rated television
shows in 40 countries.
   The next day, the cable network MTV began running a separate
music video designed to herald the launch of the singer's new song.
   The video shows Madonna in a black slip, dancing among burning
crosses and seeking refuge in a church where she kisses a statue of
a saint who comes to life.
   Pepsi had planned to run the two-minute ad last weekend on MTV,
but withheld it while the video is running, according to the source
who spoke on condition he not be identified.
   The source said the change in plans was motivated by a desire to
avoid competing for attention with the video and not by worries
about the controversy that could be stirred by the video.
   Carole Robinson, a spokeswoman for MTV, said the network has
received no complaints about the video, which has been running since
last Friday.
   Liz Rosenberg, a spokesman for Warner Brothers Records, Madonna's
record label, said the record company had received no complaints
here about the video.
   She said a state-run television network in Italy delayed its
plans to carry the video last weekend after a Catholic group
objected to what it had heard may be in the video. But she said the
network has since reviewed the video and plans to begin airing it
within the next 10 days.
   Tod MacKenzie, a spokesman for Pepsi, declined to comment on
whether the Pepsi ad was withdrawn from MTV but said the company had
not changed its overall ad campaign plans.
   He said those plans were to air the two-minute version of the
commercial before the song was released and then air shorter
versions of the two-minute ad after the singer's record had begun to
rise on the record charts.
   The single of Madonna's song was released earlier this week, and
the album is due out later this month.
   MacKenzie said he could not say when the shorter ads will begin
appearing.
  
</TEXT>
