<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-AdvertisingTax     03-08 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Advertising Tax,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sponsor of Connecticut Ad Tax Proposal Rates Its Chances as Slim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDD EVERHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief sponsor of a bill that would
impose the state's 7.5 percent sales tax on advertising says it has
little chance of becoming law.
   But Sen. William A. DiBella said he wants to keep all options
open with the state facing huge deficits.
   ``There wasn't much support for it, was there?'' DiBella,
D-Hartford, joked after a day-long hearing on the issue Tuesday.
   The proposal is not being given serious consideration as
Democrats look for hundreds of millions of dollars to erase this
year's deficit and balance next year's budget.
   DiBella, co-chairman of the tax-writing Finance Committee,
estimates that such a levy would produce $120 million a year for the
state.
   DiBella rejected arguments that the tax would hurt the economy,
saying it would simply be passed on to customers in the form of
higher prices for products, as most other taxes are.
   Under his proposal, newspapers, television stations and others
accepting advertisements would collect the taxes from advertisers
and pass them along to the state.
   Connecticut faces a $195 million deficit in the current year, and
Democrat Gov. William A. O'Neill has called for $737 million in new
taxes to balance the 1989-90 budget taking effect July 1.
   O'Neill's tax package didn't include the advertising tax, but he
said again Tuesday that he is willing to look at any proposal.
   If the tax is enacted, it would be the only one in the country.
Florida imposed an advertising tax in 1987, but it was repealed
later that year after a storm of protest from retailers and the
media. The Florida experience was repeatedly mentioned during
Tuesday's hearing.
   The committee heard hours of testimony from scores of people on
the proposal, and not one favored it. A committee vote on the
proposal could come as early as Thursday.
   Most of those testifying said it would be self defeating and cost
Connecticut jobs. They also said it would be difficult to administer
and collect and would hurt new businesses competing for customers.
   Michael Fisch, a vice president of The Hartford Courant speaking
on behalf of the 21-member Connecticut Daily Newspaper Association,
told the committee that ``advertising is the spark plug of the
economy.''
   Susan Weiner, senior vice president for advertising for the May
stores, including G. Fox, Caldor, Lord &amp; Taylor and Filene's, said a
tax on advertising ``will depress advertising and related sales and
will result in a decrease in sales tax revenues.
   Warren Gould of the painters union in New Haven, whose members
paint billboards, said the tax would almost certainly result in
layoffs.
   Typical of the media opponents was William J. Pape II, editor and
publisher of the Waterbury Republican and American.
   ``A tax on advertising would seriously and adversely affect the
Waterbury newspapers, the retailers and businesses which rely on us
to present their merchandise and services to the public, and the
public itself, which would receive a diminished amount of
information on which to base its buying decisions,'' Pape said.
   ``Inevitably, sales tax receipts of the state will be reduced,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
