<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher today as traders
awaited new government figures on the employment situation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 9.83 to 2,300.54 by
noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 6 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 657 up, 563 down and
577 unchanged.
   Analysts said traders were playing it cautious awaiting the
employment report for February from the Labor Department on Friday.
   Wall Streeters hope the data will show a slowing of economic
growth, providing a favorable portent for the inflation outlook and
a possible easing of upward pressure on interest rates.
   But evidence of that kind has been slow in coming for many months
now, leaving many market participants leery of any surprises in the
data.
   Brokers also noted that enthusiasm for stocks seemed to cool a
bit on Tuesday after the Dow Jones industrial average made a run
past the 2,300 level and then fall back.
   Time Inc. slipped { to 116\ after jumping 9\ points on Tuesday.
The big gain was attributed to speculation that the company, in
reaching its weekend agreement to merge with Warner Communications,
might have opened itself up to a takeover bid from some other
direction.
   But some analysts quoted in press reports today said they were
skeptical that that would happen.
   Gainers among the blue chips included American Express, up { at
30~; International Business Machines, up ] at 120\; Ford Motor, up [
at 51[, and Philip Morris, up 2 at 113|.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.41 to 165.69. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .02 at 328.85.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 73.44 million shares at noontime,
down from 83.40 million at the same point Tuesday.
