<FIRST>r f PM-ChicagoMerc-Penalties     03-08 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Merc-Penalties,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Fined In Commodity Exchange Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three members of a prominent Chicago Mercantile
Exchange broker group and another floor trader have been fined a
total of $400,000 and suspended for up to one month following
allegations of violating Merc rules, according to their lawyer.
   The Merc charged that the brokers prearranged trades to
circumvent limits on trades among members of the same broker group.
The violations occurred in the pit where futures contracts are
traded on Eurodollars, attorney Jeffrey Cole said today.
   Richard Lowrance, who resigned from the exchange's board of
governors last month, was fined $200,000 and suspended for 30 days,
Cole said. Lowrance stepped down before an appearance before the
Merc disciplinary committee in the case.
   David Rothner received a $75,000 fine and a 10-day suspension.
Patrick Maloney was fined $25,000 and barred from trading for five
days. Floor trader Brian Elliott, who was accused of serving an an
intermediary in the violations, was fined $100,000 and suspended 30
days, according to Cole.
   The penalties were imposed in an agreement reached late Tuesday
under which the brokers neither admitted nor denied wrongdoing.
   Broker groups are teams of floor traders who fill public orders.
They are legal, but have come under scrutiny by an FBI investigation
into suspected fraudulent trading at the Merc and Cgation, he said.
   ``There is no doubt the fines were as high as they were because
of the climate in which traders currently find themselves because of
the federal investigation,'' Cole said.
   Last June, Maloney was fined $1,000 for exceeding limitations on
customer order filling in Eurodollar futures. Rothner was fined
$1,000 for a similar violation in Eurodollar contracts in April 1988.
</TEXT>
