<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern-Railroads 3rdLd-writethru f0114 03-08 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Railroads, 3rd Ld-writethru, f0114,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Extends No-Strike Ruling at Railroads</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to correct; picks up 2nd graf, `The order...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for striking Eastern Airlines machinists
argued today that a federal judge improperly barred railroad workers
from honoring picket lines that could close down Amtrak and New
York's commuter railroads.
   The order by U.S. District Judge Robert P. Patterson ``violated
the clear command of the Norris-LaGuardia Act,'' Joseph Guerrieri
Jr., lawyer for the machinists, told the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
   That law says federal courts cannot issue injunctions in labor
disputes, except in cross-industry secondary strikes.
   Patterson ``was wrong in enjoining unions from engaging in
secondary boycotts,'' said Guerrieri. ``The unions are free to
engage in a full range of secondary activities.''
   Patterson on Tuesday extended until midnight Friday his temporary
orders barring strikes at Amtrak and New York's commuter railroads
in sympathy with the Eastern Airlines walkout. He scheduled a
hearing for today on whether to issue a long-term ban on sympathy
strikes.
   An aide said the judge extended his temporary orders _ which
would have expired at 3 p.m. today _ to allow himself time to rule.
   Before Patterson's hearing, the appeals court heard an appeal by
the International Association of Machinists and the Brotherhood of
Railroad Signalmen of his temporary order.
   The IAM has said it may set up picket lines at the railroads, and
rail workers' unions have said they would honor such lines. That
could severely disrupt rail transit.
   The unions asked the appeals court to consolidate the three
lawsuits brought by the various railroads into one case and delay
Patterson's restraining order or order him to throw it out.
   But Bernard M. Plum, a lawyer for Metro-North Commuter Railroad
and the Long Island Rail Road, argued that their employees are
required to honor their labor contract until they have exhausted all
non-court remedies under federal railroad laws.
   ``Those contracts require people to come to work every day.
That's a basic obligation,'' said Plum.
   Plum said that under the Railway Labor Act, ``The question is
that they first had to go to (those procedures) before it was
determined if they could honor picket lines.''
   Appeals court Judge Irving R. Kaufman noted, ``Whatever we do,
really, is meanigless because you're going to right to the Supreme
Court _ either side _ won't they?''
   Plum conceded the parties probably would ``given what is at
stake.''
   The appeals panel, which included judges George C. Pratt and
Richard J. Cardamone as well as Kaufman, said it would issue a
decision later today.
   Amtrak, the LIRR, Metro-North and New Jersey Transit sought and
won the temporary orders from Patterson forbidding walkouts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
