<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CropInsurance     03-08 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crop Insurance,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses Call for Changes in Crop Insurance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TIFTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Richard Ray, a witness at the first
of 15 hearings on the federal crop insurance program, said the
program is wasteful and fails to provide farmers with fair and
equitable protection.
   ``Our country is in tough times right now,'' the congressman said
Tuesday. ``We're looking for a decade of economic stagnation. Our
debt of $2.8 trillion and our interest payments ... have gotten us
in such a situation that we must not waste dollars. The bureaucratic
way in which the federal crop insurance group was put together
causes us to waste a lot of federal dollars. We need to refine
that.''
   Ray, a Democrat who represents Georgia's largely rural 3rd
District, was among 27 witnesses who lined up to testify before the
Commission for the Improvement of the Federal Crop Insurance
Program. The 25-member commission, created by Congress to protect
more farmers from droughts and other disasters, will hold hearings
in 14 states.
   Ray noted that crop insurance reform has the backing of key
Georgia lawmakers, including Sens. Sam Nunn and Wyche Fowler, and
said he is optimistic such legislation could win congressional
approval.
   Kellye Eversole, the commission's executive director, said 50
crops, including peanuts, tobacco, soybeans and peaches, are
eligible for crop insurance. Growers can select policies that cover
50 percent, 65 percent or 75 percent of their average yields.
   Ms. Eversole said concern about the nation's record budget
deficit could mean farmers will have to rely more heavily on crop
insurance, rather than disaster payments.
   ``We're trying to find out what is wrong with the crop insurance
program and why participation is so low,'' she said, noting just 17
percent to 27 percent of the nation's farmers opt for crop coverage.
   Wilbur Gamble, chairman of the Georgia Peanut Commission, said
the two chief objections of Georgia's 10,500 peanut growers is that
crop insurance penalizes growers who have had low yields because of
disasters and forces growers to insure all of their crops, rather
than acreage that faces the greatest risk.
   ``The risks in farming are great, and government rules and
regulations are constantly changing,'' he said. ``These factors have
led to higher costs of production and low prices. We believe it is
extremely important to ... help farmers bear the unpredictable risks
of farming.''
   Johnny Deal, a vice president of the Sea Island Bank in
Statesboro, said his bank requires borrowers to have crop insurance
on at least some of their crops.
   ``In many instances we will have insurance only on peanuts or in
some cases tobacco,'' he said. ``Only a small percentage of our
farmers carry federal crop insurance on corn, wheat, soybeans or
cotton. Their reasoning is that the premium is too high for the
dollar amount of coverage they receive.''
   Another banker, Sam Way, president of the Planters Bank in
Hawkinsville, said banks may decide to grant fewer agricultural
loans unless the crop insurance program is improved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
