<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1335EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-RealEstate     03-08 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Real Estate,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Spend Record $16.54 Billion On U.S. Property In '88</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese investment in U.S. real estate rose
nearly a third last year with California attracting more investment
than any other state and Los Angeles more than any other city, a
study says.
   Japanese investors spent a record $16.54 billion on U.S. real
estate in 1988, up from $12.77 billion in 1977, to boost their
holdings to a total of $42.88 billion, according to the study by
Kenneth Leventhal &amp; Co., an accounting firm.
   California ranked first among the states with $5.62 billion in
Japanese investments in 1988, followed by New York at $2.8 billion
and Illinois at $1.87 billion, according to the study, released
Tuesday.
   Los Angeles topped all cities with $3.05 billion, with New York
City in second at $2.8 billion, according to the study.
   Among the major Japanese investments in Los Angeles were the
former Wells Fargo office building for $147 million, the Century
City Marriott for $85 million and a 49 percent interest in the
Riviera Country Club.
   The Leventhal figures were more than double the 1988 Japanese
investment total of $7.1 billion reported last week by Salomon
Brothers Inc., New York investment bank.
   But Salomon Brothers analyst Susan R. Jordan said its estimates
were lower because the firm does not include projects under
construction, as does Leventhal.
</TEXT>
