<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1340EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Norway-Economy     03-08 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Norway-Economy,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norway's Economic Cure Working Despite Side Effects, Bank Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Norwegian state bank said Wednesday the
country's economic health appears to be improving following tough
government measures but that rising unemployment is a
worse-than-expected side effect.
   ``There has been signficant progress,'' Norges Bank said in its
quarterly report Wednesday.
   The central bank praised recent negotiated and legislated wage
limits but said unemployment, which doubled in one year to 3.9
percent in February, was higher than expected. Another 2 percent of
the jobless were employed in extraordinary government programs.
   ``There is no simple way to reduce unemployment, but it is vital
that the measures used do not undermine efforts to turn the
Norwegian economy around,'' said the report.
   Central Bank President Hermod Skaanland said he did not foresee a
prompt decline in unemployment but that state intervention will
probably not overstimulate domestic demand.
   Income from Norway's North Sea oil fields, now pumping 1.44
million barrels per day, plummeted with the 1986 oil price collapse,
at the peak of a domestic spending and borrowing spree.
   Such earlier measures as interest rate hikes and legislated wage
limits, now extended to March 31, 1990, helped turn Norway's trade
deficit into a January surplus of 3.7 billion kroner, or $552
million, and reduce 1988 consumer spending by 1.6 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
