   The stock market staged a rally today as traders
awaited new government figures on the employment situation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 18.58 to 2,309.29 by
2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 798 up, 533 down and
566 unchanged.
   Analysts said investors were growing more optimistic awaiting the
employment report for February from the Labor Department on Friday.
   Wall Streeters hope the data will show a slowing of economic
growth, providing a favorable portent for the inflation outlook and
a possible easing of upward pressure on interest rates.
   That theme also seemed to catch on in the foreign-exchange
market, where the dollar rose, and in the credit markets, where
interest rates declined a bit.
   Traders also seemed to be impressed when the Dow Jones industrial
average broke through the 2,300 level at mid-session. The average
made a run past 2,300 on Tuesday but then fall back.
   Time Inc. slipped { to 116\ after jumping 9\ points on Tuesday.
The big gain was attributed to speculation that the company, in
reaching its weekend agreement to merge with Warner Communications,
might have opened itself up to a takeover bid from some other
direction.
   But some analysts quoted in press reports today said they were
skeptical that that would happen.
   Gainers among the blue chips included American Express, up | at
31; International Business Machines, up { at 120]; General Electric,
up { at 45|, and Philip Morris, up 3[ at 114}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.82 to 166.10. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .43 at 329.26.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 117.01 million shares with two
hours to go.
