<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     03-08 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Slightly Higher; Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A version for AMs is planned by 5:30 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended slightly higher after drifting
without direction in dull European trading Wednesday, with the
market lacking any fresh news on which to trade.
   Gold prices rose.
   ``The market is slightly favorable toward the dollar, but there
is a lack of conviction over what extent the dollar should rise,''
one London dealer said.
   Another London dealer said: ``No one knows what's going to happen
next. There's an equal spread of people who think the dollar will
rise and those who think it will fall.''
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.7200 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7220 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
rates included: 1.8585 West German marks, up from 1.8520; 1.5865
Swiss francs, up from 1.5847; 6.3080 French francs, up from 6.3000;
2.0930 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0945; 1,362.20 Italian lire, down
from 1,362.37; and, 1.20155 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1985.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.30 Japanese yen to a closing 128.73 yen. Later, in
London, it also was quoted at 128.73 yen.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $393.80 a troy ounce,
compared with $391.45 bid late Tuesday.
   In Zurich, gold closed at a bid of $394.75 compared with $390.90
bid late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $4.74 to close at a bid of
$388.21.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $5.91 a troy ounce, compared with
$5.88 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
