<FIRST>r f BC-ConsolidatedOil     03-08 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Consolidated Oil,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consolidated Oil Seeks Chapter 11 Reorganization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consolidated Oil and Gas Inc., recently taken over
by a group of disgruntled investors, has filed for Chapter 11
reorganization in U.S. Bankruptcy Court for the District of Colorado.
   In its filing Tuesday, Consolidated listed assets of $38.6
million and liabilities of $51.5 million.
   The company has been under financial pressure in recent years
because of slumping oil and gas prices. In 1987, it reported a $9.3
million loss, compared with a loss of $21.5 million the previous
year.
   A group of investors headed by Maryland-based Energy Recovery
Fund and Texas-based Investment Limited Partners reacted by
launching a proxy fight for control of the company.
   The investors captured control of Consolidated late last year,
ousting existing management, including founder and chairman Harry
Trueblood.
   During the takeover bid, the investor group accused Trueblood and
the company's board of directors of milking the Consolidated assets
for their benefit.
   Consolidated officials did not immediately return phone calls
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
