<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-08 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Break Sharply On Farmer Selling, Brazil Harvest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply lower
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as speculators were unnerved
by the looming Brazilian harvest and an increase in farmer selling.
   Grain futures fell in sympathy with soybeans.
   Soybean growers in Brazil, the world's second-largest producer
after the United States, are preparing to harvest their largest crop
ever.
   The movement of Brazilian _ and then Argentine _ soybeans into
the global pipeline will help ease the supply tightness that has
contributed to the market's recent firm tone.
   The Agriculture Department has estimated Brazil's 1988-89 soybean
crop at 20 million metric tons compared with 17.8 million the
previous year. On Wednesday, a widely watched private weather
service raised its Brazilian soybean estimate to 20.7 million metric
tons from 19.6 million.
   ``I think the real qustion is not whether it's going to be a
record, but how much of a record,'' said Ted Mao, a grain specialist
with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Mao said a rise in soybean prices over the past 10 days had
prompted more selling of stockpiled beans by U.S. producers.
   At the close, wheat was 1} cents to 4 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.30 a bushel; corn was } cent to
2} cents lower with March at $2.75{ a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to
5 cents lower with March at $2.05 a bushel; soybeans were 4{ cents
to 11{ cents lower with March at $7.56 a bushel.
</TEXT>
