<FIRST>r f AM-WeirtonSteel     03-08 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weirton Steel,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weirton Steel Employee Owners Approve Outside Stock Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STEUBENVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weirton Steel Corp. officials say a
vote to sell stock outside the company will help the employee-owned
steelmaker continue its $650 million modernization program.
   The employee owners voted by a 4-1 margin Tuesday night in favor
of selling stock to outside investors.
   Company officials and union officers of Weirton Steel announced
the voting results at Tuesday night's annual meeting held in
Steubenville. Approximately 8,000 employee owners cast ballots,
officials said. An exact tally was not immediately available,
officials said Wednesday.
   Weirton Steel officials announced Monday the rank and file of the
Independent Steelworkers Union had voted by a better than 3-1 ratio
to cut back the percentage of profit-sharing from 50 percent of
after-tax income to 35 percent.
   Both changes are designed to help the Weirton, W.Va., company
finance a $650 million modernization program that includes
renovation of the hot mill and the introduction of new continuous
casting facilities.
   Employee owners also have approved amendments to company bylaws
that will keep control of Weirton Steel in employee hands despite
the sale of stock on the open market.
   Weirton Steel celebrated its fifth anniversary as an
employee-owned company in January.
</TEXT>
