<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-ChristianPilots     03-08 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Christian Pilots,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Pilots Group at Eastern Appeals to Lorenzo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Eastern Airlines pilots aren't as quick as fellow strikers
to vilify boss Frank Lorenzo with shrieked epithets and shredded
effigies _ they want to reach him through Christian dialogue and the
Scriptures.
   A group of pilots and other employees at strike-torn Eastern are
praying that ``someone sends Christian witness to Frank Lorenzo,''
said Bob Fuhrman, who has flown for Eastern for 16 years.
   ``We need some dignity; we need our voices to be heard,'' Fuhrman
told a reporter as he stood on a picket line Tuesday in the empty
Eastern terminal at Atlanta's sprawling Hartsfield International
Airport.
   Fuhrman, 43, said there are about 1,000 members in Eastern's
branch of the Fellowship of Christian Airline Personnel, including
about 100 pilots. The other members include Eastern flight
attendants, mechanics, baggage handlers and ticket agents.
   Many angry Eastern workers have screamed ``Down with Lorenzo!''
on airport picket lines up and down the East Coast. On the first
night of the walkout, strikers outside the airline's Miami office
tore up Lorenzo effigies and held placards reading: ``Frank Lorenzo:
We are Your Worst Nightmare!''
   Fuhrman has a quieter message for the chairman of Eastern's
parent, Texas Air Corp.:
   ``Mr. Lorenzo, I hope that you know the love of Jesus Christ and
if you don't, I hope that the Holy Spirit guides you to knowing the
love of Jesus Christ. We pray that if we can find that common bond
and we can stand in God's love and wisdom, we can run Eastern
Airlines.
   ``We need the dignity and we need the respect and we need your
love, Mr. Lorenzo.''
   Efforts to reach Lorenzo for comment weren't successful. He has
remained largely out of sight since the strike began. A Texas Air
spokesman, Ned Walker, did not immediately return telephone calls
from The Associated Press.
   Eastern's rival Delta Air Lines has succeeded where Eastern has
failed partly because Atlanta-based Delta ``has a Christian
philosophy,'' Fuhrman said.
   ``I think they run the airline by Christian philosophy at Delta.
They're there for the family; if someone has a problem, they're
there,'' said Fuhrman, who was furloughed as a pilot for 4{ years
starting in April 1973 and spent some of the time as an airline
cleaner. His wife Brenda has been a flight attendant at Eastern for
12{ years.
   Fuhrman wrote President Bush in mid-February asking him to
intervene in the Eastern dispute by extending the 30-day cooling-off
period that ended at midnight last Friday, triggering the strike.
   ``President Bush, I know we both share a faith in the Lord Jesus
Christ,'' Fuhrman's letter read. ``I ask of you in God's Wisdom to
consider my request, so that we might know the Mind of God
concerning the situation at Eastern which affects the lives of so
many people.''
   Fuhrman said he didn't receive a reply from Bush, who has stated
several times he wouldn't intervene.
</TEXT>
