<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Pillsbury-GrandMet Bjt   03-08 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pillsbury-Grand Met, Bjt,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Met Sells Pillsbury Unit For $431 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC, the British food and
liquor concern that acquired Pillsbury Co. earlier this year,
announced Wednesday the sale of the company's Steak and Ale and
Bennigan's restaurant chains to a management-led investor group for
$431 million.
   Grand Met said the investors included senior management of the
operating company for the two Dallas-based chains, S&amp;A Restaurant
Corp., and DJS-Inverness and Co., a New York-based private
investment partnership.
   Financing for the deal is to be provided by Citicorp Capital
Investors Ltd. and other sources, Grand Met said in a statement.
   Grand Met announced its intention to sell S&amp;A in January, after
the British conglomerate acquired Pillsbury for $5.7 billion,
because U.S. laws prohibit liquor companies from owning outlets
which sell alcoholic beverages. Grand Met's businesses include
liquor distilling.
   Wednesday's announcement followed a move Monday in which Grand
Met said it would lay off 550 of the 2,350 employees in Pillsbury's
Minneapolis headquarters, citing an ``overlap of functions'' and
desire to streamline the company.
   The layoffs affected all job classifications, from clerical
support employees to managerial and staff-level functions.
   Last week, Grand Met announced it had eliminated Pillsbury's
affirmative action office and created two new units, Grand
Metropolitan Foods Europe and Pillsbury International, to aid
international expansion of Pillsbury's food brands.
   Ian Martin, chairman of Pillsbury and a Grand Met director, said
proceeds from the restaurant sale would be invested in the growth of
its Pillsbury Foods and Burger King units ``to enhance our
shareholders' investment.''
   ``We received several expressions of interest,'' he said, but the
deal from the investor-led group was the only one to be ``clearly in
the best interests of the Pillsbury Co., Grand Met shareholders and
S&amp;A employees.''
   Stephen Carnes, an analyst at the investment firm Piper, Jaffray
&amp; Hopwood, said the sale should have positive effects for Pillsbury.
   ``The long-term winner is obviously Burger King,'' he said.
   In the year ended May 31, S&amp;A had operating income of $50 million
on sales of $716 million. It employs about 33,000 people with 159
Steak and Ale outlets in 24 states and 221 Bennigan's in 32 states.
   Grand Met is a real estate, liquor and gambling conglomerate. Its
U.S. holdings include Alpo dog food and Pearle Vision Centers, and
its liquor brands include Smirnoff vodka and J&amp;B scotch.
   Pillsbury makes Pillsbury flour, Green Giant vegetables, Haagen
Dazs ice cream and a variety of other products.
   Grand Met reported sales of more than $11 billion in fiscal 1988.
Pillsbury had sales of $6.2 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
