<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSupply Bjt   03-08 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Supply, Bjt,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rising Car Inventories And Strong Production, Can They Mix?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. automakers are likely to relay more on sales
incentives than on production cuts to reduce swollen inventories of
unsold cars, analysts say.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. have been
maintaining production levels that have led to a big rise in the
number of automobiles on hand.
   The authoritative Ward's Automotive Reports said that at the end
of January, there was an 85-day supply of of cars made by U.S.-based
companies in inventory, up from 67 days at the end of December.
   Although incentives tend to cut into the automakers' profits,
they are more appealing to customers and autoworkers, who want to
keep production high.
   ``It's becoming increasingly clear that if you can maintain
production volumes at a fairly steady pace, it's easier to control
raw materials, your work force is happy and, ultimately, your
warranty costs come down,'' said analyst John Kirnan of Kidder,
Peabody &amp; Co. of New York.
   ``I think they're going to hesitate on the (cutting) production
route as long as possible and rely heavily on incentives,'' Kirnan
said Wednesday.
   GM's inventory was reported at 95 days, Ford's at 80 days and
Chrysler's was at 89 days, the weekly journal said.
   Higher inventories early in the year aren't particularly
worrisome to automakers, since January and February sales typically
are slower than other months and companies sometimes build up their
supplies before the usual spring sales rush.
   However, there is some concern on Wall Street.
   ``To the extent that inventory stays up and sales go down,
something has to give,'' said analyst Carol Verschell of Moody's
Investors Service Inc. of New York. ``Eventually, there will have to
be an adjustment, cut production or increase incentive programs.''
   GM has done both.
   Earlier this week, the nation's No. 1 automaker extended some
existing incentives into April and May and created new ones in an
effort to lure buyers to dealers' showrooms. Last week, GM doubled a
two-week shutdown of its Doraville, Ga., Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme
assembly plant because, as plant manager F. Thomas Brady said,
``We've got too many cars out in the field.''
   Chrysler did not immediately match GM's new incentives, but its
existing enticements have no time limits. On the same day GM issued
its new incentives, Ford Vice Chairman Harold Poling said his
company would remain competitive with other car makers' marketing
schemes.
   Ford is in better shape. For months, the No. 2 automaker has been
producing more than 15 percent of its vehicles on overtime, meaning
Ford can withstand a sales slump and still remain at full production.
   Chrysler, meantime, has been struggling in sales as a number of
its factories change over to new models or begin ``ramping up''
production of newly introduced cars.
   Last week, Chrysler Vice Chairman Gerald Greenwald said the Big
Three would be tested this month, when sales are expected to rise
from January and February levels amid continued reliance on
incentives.
   Car sales by the Big Three are down 10.6 percent during the first
two months of this year compared with January and February of 1988.
February car sales for GM, Ford and Chrysler were 14.4 percent below
the pace for the same month last year.
   Verschell and Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc. wondered whether the usual spring buying surge
would be enough to shrink inventories to levels easing pressure to
boost incentives or cut production.
   ``There are just so many cars out there fighting for the same
consumer,'' Verschell said.
   ``I don't think it's going to be enough to reduce it,'' Heaney
said.
   But Kirnan was more bullish about spring sales, saying, ``The
inventory problem will probably disappear by late March and early
April, and production schedules are probably going to be maintained
for the second and third quarter.
   ``I just don't the,'' Kirnan added. ``I think thee degree that
some people believe,'' Kirnan added. ``I think the traditional types
of incentives are going to continue to do some magic.''
</TEXT>
