<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     03-08 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Head Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices rose Wednesday, driven by
market rumors and technical factors.
   The April contract for the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
West Texas Intermediate, settled 24 cents higher at $18.54a barrel,
regaining some of the ground lost Tuesday when the contract fell 37
cents on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the
April contract for wholesale home heating oil settled 0.29 cent
higher at 51.37 cents a gallon, after falling 0.35 cent the previous
session.
   April unleaded gasoline, which lost 0.18 cent on Tuesday, rose
0.44 cent to 51.85 cents a gallon.
   ``Having settled on a sour note Tuesday night ... the market has
really turned around,'' said Mary L. Haskins, a vice president at
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Some of incentive for the turnaround came from reports
circulating in the market of a conflict between Iran and Iraq.
   Before details of the reported conflict filtered fully through
the market, energy futures rallied temporarily with dealers buying
in speculation that tensions between the two Persian Gulf countries
might cause supply disruptions. The buying lost momentum once it
became clear in the market that the conflict referred to an incident
that occurred in mid-February.
   But at the same time, the rally drove crude past technical price
thresholds that triggered more buying, Haskins said.
</TEXT>
