<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-08 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up; Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened Wednesday against all
major currencies in moderate trading as some traders concluded that
the Bush administration was showing flexibility on a tax increase to
reduce the federal budget deficit.
   Gold prices declined after rising overseas. Republic National
Bank of New York quoted a bid of $391.90 a troy ounce of gold around
4 p.m. EST, down $1 from Tuesday's late bid.
   Currency dealers attributed the dollar's rally Wednesday to a
report quoting Michael Boskin, chairman of President Bush's Council
of Economic Advisers, as saying the administration ``has not ruled
out a discussion'' of taxes as part of a formal budget negotiation.
   Boskin also said the administration has not abandoned its
opposition to higher taxes. His statements were consistent with
those of other administration officials in recent weeks.
   Nevertheless, the market chose to interpret Boskin's testimony as
good news for the dollar. Robert Ryan, senior currency trader for
Irving Trust Co., said, ``Bush is now conceding that he may allow
higher taxes.''
   Dealers said there were reports of the Federal Reserve selling
small amounts of dollars to stem its rise Wednesday but that most
market participants saw that intervention as more symbolic.
   ``I think they just wanted to remind us that they were still out
there,'' Ryan said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.30 Japanese yen to a closing 128.73 yen. It also
was quoted at 128.73 yen in London, and later, in New York, it rose
to 129.225 yen from 128.825 yen Tuesday.
   The dollar gained against the British pound in London, where it
cost $1.7200 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7220 late Tuesday.
Sterling fetched $1.7155 in New York, down from $1.72155.
   Other later dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.86325 West German marks, up from 1.85525; 1.5910
Swiss francs, up from 1.5845; 1.20145 Canadian dollars, up from
1.19825; 6.3230 French francs, up from 6.3030; and 1,366.875 Italian
lire, up from 1,362.625.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday: 1.8585
West German marks, up from 1.8520; 1.5865 Swiss francs, up from
1.5847; 6.3080 French francs, up from 6.3000; 2.0930 Dutch guilders,
down from 2.0945; 1,362.20 Italian lire, down from 1,362.37; and,
1.20155 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1985.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $393.10 a troy ounce, down from $393.30 late
Tuesday.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $393.80 an ounce,
compared with $391.45 bid late Tuesday. In Zurich, gold closed at a
bid of $394.75 an ounce, vs. $390.90 Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $4.74 to close at a bid of
$388.21 an ounce.
   Silver prices also were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery settled at $5.865 a troy ounce, down
from $5.874. Silver rose in London to a late bid price of $5.91 an
ounce from $5.88 Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
