<FIRST>u f AM-Time-WarnerSuits     03-08 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time-Warner Suits,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholders File Suits Against Time-Warner Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders filed three suits in
Delaware state court Wednesday to block the planned $18 billion
merger between Time Inc. and Warner Communications Inc.
   One of the suits, filed by four Warner shareholders against Time
and Warner, Warner's board of directors and Warner Chairman, Steven
Ross, alleged the merger and a planned preliminary exchange of stock
between the two companies _ known as a lock-up transaction _ would
prevent an outsider from making a possibly higher bid for Warner.
   In the lock-up, Time will exchange 12.5 percent of its stock for
12 percent of Warner's shares. Such transactions commonly are
undertaken by companies planning to merge as a defense against
unwanted takeovers.
   ``The merger and lock-up transaction are nothing more than a plan
and scheme by the director-defendants to entrench themselves and to
make it much more difficult and highly unlikely that Warner will be
subject to an outside takeover,'' said the class action suit, filed
in Delaware Chancery Court.
   The suit asked the court to declare the merger void or
alternatively prevent the defendants from proceeding with it.
   The merger, which would be accomplished through a stock swap,
would create the world's largest communications concern, Time Warner
Inc.
   Spokesmen for Time and Warner said their companies had no comment
on the suit.
   Court papers for the other two suits were not immediately
available, and it was not immediately known who filed the actions or
who the defendants were.
   The suits were filed in Delaware because Time and Warner are
incorporated here.
</TEXT>
