<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1831EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Apples-Schools     03-08 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Apples-Schools,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apples Pulled from Big Apple School Menus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If a student in the Big Apple wants to give
teacher a little apple, it will have to come from home. Fresh apples
have been pulled from school cafeteria menus because of worries
about carcinogenic pesticides.
   The Board of Education, which feeds students in 1,200 public and
parochial schools under a federal program, barred the sale of apples
last month, at least until it receives advice from the Environmental
Protection Agency, said Kevin Gill, director of support services for
the board.
   The Washington-based National Resource Defense Council has
reported that the pesticide diaminozide, which is known by its brand
name Alar, could increase the incidence of cancer in children who
drink a lot of apple juice.
   Apple growers contended only about 4 percent of all apples sold
in the United States show any traces of Alar and those amounts are
well below EPA standards.
   Alar is used to maintain firmness and resist bruising in fruits
and vegetables.
   Gill's program sells or hands out about 13 million apples a year.
He said students had not been complaining about the fruit's
disappearance. ``It's only been a few weeks, and we offer a wide
variety of fruits,'' he said.
   Applesauce and apple juice are harder to replace and will
continue to be served, he said.
</TEXT>
