<FIRST>r f AM-WyCal-PacificGas     03-08 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WyCal-Pacific Gas,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wyoming-California, Pacific Gas and Electric Enter Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Natural gas from Wyoming will flow to California
under an agreement announced Wednesday between Pacific Gas and
Electric Co. and a unit of Houston-based Coastal Corp.
   Coastal's Wyoming-California Pipeline Co. said PG&amp;E has agreed to
withdraw its opposition to WyCal's proposal to provide new
interstate natural gas pipeline capacity to California.
   WyCal will provide interstate shippers on WyCal's proposed
pipeline system with the option in California of utilizing WyCal's
pipeline or a Federal Energy Regulatory Commission-regulated
expansion of San Francisco-based PG&amp;E's existing facilities for
transportation within California.
   In January, the regulatory commission authorized WyCal to
construct and operate a 650 million cubic feet per day natural gas
pipeline system from the Overthrust producing region in Wyoming to
Kern County, Calif. Through interconnections with other pipelines,
the WyCal system also can transport Canadian natural gas.
   Under either alternative, shippers would be assured of FERC
regulation of their transportation contracts for up to 25 years.
After 25 years, jurisdiction would be subject to regulation by the
California Public Utilities Commission.
   PG&amp;E has been granted the right to purchase 50 million cubic feet
a day of firm transportation capacity on WyCal's system for 20
years. If PG&amp;E exercises that right, it can acquire a 25 percent
ownership interest in the WyCal system.
</TEXT>
