<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1901EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Milken-Speech     03-08 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Milken-Speech,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Milken Scheduled To Give First Speech Since Drexel Plea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Multimillionaire financier Michael Milken is
planning his first speech here since Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
agreed to fire him as part of a securities fraud plea deal with the
government, his spokesman said Wednesday.
   Milken is scheduled to deliver the keynote address next week at a
financial industry black-tie dinner honoring the ``chief executive
officers of the decade'' as selected by Financial World magazine,
spokesman Kenneth Lerer said.
   Milken was named in a Securities and Exchange Commission civil
suit against Drexel last September in connection with securities
fraud charges that included insider trading. He is expected to be
indicted on criminal fraud and racketeering charges.
   Milken has headed Drexel's Beverly Hills, Calif., ``junk'' bond
financing department since the mid-1970s and is credited with
turning the low-cost, high-yield securities into a $175 billion
annual market. The bonds often are used to finance takeovers and the
growth of small- to medium-sized companies.
   Lerer said Milken last spoke in New York at a business luncheon
in December, several weeks before terms of Drexel's plea deal with
the government settling criminal charges against were announced.
   Under the deal, Drexel agreed to pay $650 million in fines and
restitution and plead guilty to six felonies. The deal is pending a
separate settlement with the SEC on civil charges.
   Milken, who has denied any wrongdoing, recently asked a federal
judge in Manhattan to modify or throw out the agreement on the
grounds it violates his rights. Drexel agreed in the deal to dismiss
Milken and withhold his 1988 compensation of well over $100 million.
   Lerer said Milken is working part-time at Drexel while preparing
his legal defense. He said Milken also regularly attends charity and
financial community dinners. He is not scheduled to receive an award
at the New York dinner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890308-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 2119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HelpWanted     03-08 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Help Wanted,0136</SECOND>
<HEAD>Help Wanted Ad Volume Declines in January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The volume of help wanted advertising declined in
January, indicating the demand for labor continues to fluctuate, the
Conference Board said Wednesday.
   The business-supported financial research organization said its
Help Wanted Index declined to 155 in January, compared with readings
of 161 in December and 157 in November.
   In January 1988, the index, which measures the volume of
classified advertising in 51 major newspapers across the country and
is considered sensitive to changes in demand for labor, stood at 152.
   The Conference Board said the volume of help wanted ads rose in
New England and in the West North Central and East North Central
regions during January. Volume declined in all other parts of the
country.
</TEXT>
