<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 1920EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp 1stLd-Writethru   03-08 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Tumble As Speculators' Nerve Crumbles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, West Texas ..., to CORRECT that crude oil prices
rose, sted fell.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices fell as much as 10} cents a bushel
Wednesday, erasing much of the past week's gains as speculators
unnerved by the looming Brazilian harvest and an increase in farmer
selling backed away from the market.
   On other markets Wednesday, energy futures posted strong gains on
signs of renewed tensions between Iran and Iraq; precious metals
retreated; copper futures fell; and livestock and meat futures
finished mostly lower.
   Grain futures followed soybeans lower on the Chicago Board of
Trade. Wheat settled 1} cents to 4 cents lower with March at $4.30 a
bushel; corn was } cent to 2} cents lower with March at $2.75{ a
bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 5 cents lower with March at $2.05 a
bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 10} cents lower with March at
$7.55{ a bushel.
   Soybean growers in Brazil, the world's second-largest producer
after the United States, are preparing to harvest their largest crop
ever.
   The movement of Brazilian _ and then Argentine _ soybeans into
the global pipeline will help ease the supply tightness that has
contributed to the market's recent firm tone.
   The Agriculture Department has estimated Brazil's 1988-89 soybean
crop at 20 million metric tons compared with 17.8 million the
previous year. On Wednesday, a widely watched private weather
service raised its Brazilian soybean estimate to 20.7 million metric
tons from 19.6 million.
   ``I think the real question is not whether it's going to be a
record crop, but how much of a record,'' said Ted Mao, a grain
specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   U.S. soybean growers harvested 1.54 billion bushels last year, or
about 41 million metric tons.
   Mao said said a rise in soybean prices over the past 10 days had
prompted more selling of stockpiled beans by U.S. producers.
   Oil futures rallied on the New York Mercantile Exchange following
a report that Iran's United Nations ambassador had accused Iraqi
soldiers of killing five Iranian soldiers on Feb. 17.
   The incident would mark the bloodiest clash between the Middle
Eastern nations since the beginning of their 7-month cease-fire.
   The energy market's rally also was seen as partly a reaction to
Tuesday's weekly American Petroleum Institute report, which showed
declines in U.S. stocks of gasoline and distillates, although
crude-oil supplies increased.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 24 cents to 45 cents
higher with April at $18.54 a barrel; heating oil was .29 cent to
.97 cent higher with April at 51.37 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .44 cent to .83 cent higher with April at 51.85 cents a
gallon.
   Gold and silver futures retreated on New York's Commodity
Exchange, selling off late in the session after gold for April
delivery encountered resistance at $398.80 a troy ounce.
   Bernard Savaiko, a metals analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in New
York, said April gold's failure to close above $396 an ounce
indicated ``the recent rally is tiring.''
   Gold settled 30 cents to 60 cents lower with April at $395.40 an
ounce; silver was 1.2 cents to 1.8 cents lower with May at $5.947 a
troy ounce.
   Copper futures also finished lower on the Commodity Exchange
after initially rising. Analysts said the decline reflected
perceptions that physical demand for copper has slowed with the
metal's rise in price during the past month.
   Copper settled 2.9 cents to 4.1 cents lower with May at $1.404 a
pound.
   Weakening cash markets contributed to a late slump in cattle
futures on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Most pork futures
retreated on ideas that Wednesday's increase in hog marketings would
result in lower cash prices on Thursday.
   Live cattle finished .25 cent to .45 cent lower with April at
77.12 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .40 cent lower to .03 cent
higher with March at 81.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent
lower to .08 cent higher with April at 44.10 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .25 cent lower to .12 cent higher with March at
38.85 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
