<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-Oil     03-08 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Oil,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices for Far East Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for Mexican crude oil exports to the
Far East rose by 23 cents per barrel in February over January
levels, the government oil monopoly Pemex said Wednesday.
   Exports of Pemex's light Isthmus crude sold in the Far East at
$15.08 a barrel last month, up from $14.85 in January, Pemex said.
The monopoly's heavy Maya grade sold at $12.43 a barrel in February,
up from $12.20, Pemex said.
   ``These price increases for Mexican export crudes reflect the
favorable evolution of the international petroleum market,'' Pemex
said.
   Mexico has announced it will cut its exports April 1 by 5
percent, or 68,600 barrels a day, to buttress producers' efforts to
shore up prices on the international market. Mexico's base level of
exports was 1.35 million barrels per day in 1988.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed last
year to cut its members' production by 4 million barrels a day, to
around 18.5 million barrels. Mexico, the world's sixth-largest oil
producer, does not belong to the 13-nation cartel but closely
monitors its pricing and production guidelines.
   Most Mexican crude exports to the Far East market are purchased
by Japan, Mexico's third-biggest customer last year, Pemex said.
Japan will buy 180,000 barrels per day of Mexican crude in 1989.
</TEXT>
