<FIRST>r f AM-FloppyDisks     03-08 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Floppy Disks,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>BASF, Fuji To Make Floppy Disks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BASF Corp. and Fuji Photo Film USA Inc.
will manufacture 3.5-inch floppy computer disks in a joint venture
beginning as early as this fall, the companies said Wednesday.
   The new venture, called B&amp;F Microdisks, will produce an estimated
90 million disks a year at a $48 million planty to be built this
summer in Bedford, a town northwest of Boston, the companies said.
   BASF spokesman Richard C. Howland Jr. said the new business is
expected to create about 230 jobs, mostly in manufacturing. BASF and
Fuji will have an equal stake in the venture, he said.
   The 75,000-square-foot plant, designed to serve the North
American personal computer market, ``will be one of the largest of
its kind in the world,'' Howland said.
   An estimated 375 million 3.5-inch floppy disks with a retail
value of $600 million will be sold in North America this year. By
1991, the market is expected to grow to 600 million units with a
retail value of over $1 billion, Howland said.
   Among the joint venture's competitors are Sony, Maxell, TDK, 3M
and Eastman Kodak Co.'s Verbatim. BASF Corp., headquartered in
Parsippany, N.J., is a division of BASF AG of Ludwigshaven, West
Germany. Fuji's parent is Fuji Photo Film Co. Ltd. of Tokyo.
</TEXT>
